<1ST_LINE>u w AM-SweepstakesFraud     11-18 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sweepstakes Fraud,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fund-Raising Letter Prompts Federal, State Probes and Warnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Postal Inspection Service and several
state agencies are investigating possible consumer fraud in
connection with a nationwide cancer charity sweepstakes organized by
a direct-mail company, according to a published report.
   The Washington Post reported in Friday's editions that the Watson
and Hughey Co. of Alexandria, Va., has sent letters to about 48
million households throughout the country soliciting participation
in a fund-raising campaign on behalf of three cancer research
organizations.
   The letters state that the recipient has ``won a cash prize in
the $5,000 Sweepstakes'' and ask for a voluntary contribution of $5,
but closer reading reveals that the total value of the contest is
$5,000, with a maximum individual award of $100 and a minimum of 10
cents, the newspaper said.
   The letters were signed by Washington attorney Robert R. Stone
and sent on behalf of the Pacific West Cancer Fund of Seattle, the
Knoxville, Tenn.-based Cancer Fund of America and the Walker Cancer
Research Institute of Edgewood, Md.
   The Post said the mailings have prompted calls to consumer and
legal agencies from people believing they had won $5,000, two
lawsuits alleging consumer fraud in Missouri and Illinois,
suspension of charity registration in Maryland for two of the cancer
research organizations, consumer warnings in other states and
investigations in Virginia and by the federal government.
</TEXT>
