<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Wedtech-Biaggi     11-18 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wedtech-Biaggi,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Biaggi to be Sentenced Friday for Wedtech Conviction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Rep. Mario Biaggi faced up to 146 years in
prison and $7 million in fines at sentencing Friday for a
racketeering conviction in the Wedtech corruption scandal.
   The New York City Democrat was convicted Aug. 5 on federal
racketeering, conspiracy, extortion and mail fraud charges for
turning Wedtech Corp., now a defunct defense contractor, into a
racketeering enterprise that paid millions of dollars in bribes to
public officials.
   U.S. District Judge Constance Baker Motley was scheduled to
sentence Biaggi, 70, and four other defendants.
   Also convicted of racketeering in the four-month trial in federal
court in Manhattan were former Bronx Borough President Stanley
Simon, 58; Wedtech founder John Mariotta, 58; former Small Business
Administration official Peter Neglia, 40, and Biaggi's former law
partner, Bernard Ehrlich, 59.
   Biaggi's eldest son, Richard, 39, was acquitted of racketeering
charges but was found guilty of bribe receiving, mail fraud and tax
charges.
   All except Ehrlich, who was to be sentenced at a later date, were
to appear before Motley Friday.
   A seventh defendant, Ronald Betso, 40, was acquitted on all
counts.
   Biaggi, a 10-term congressman who had been a highly decorated
city police officer from 1942 to 1965, was convicted of all but one
of the 16 counts against him. He resigned his House seat the day
after his conviction.
   Biaggi was found guilty of extorting $50,000 in cash and stock
once worth more than $3 million from Wedtech in exchange for his
political clout. He also was convicted of filing false financial
disclosure statements and bogus income tax returns to cover up his
illegal profits.
   He did not testify in his defense after the judge gave
prosecutors wide latitude to cross examine him about such things as
his 1987 conviction for obstructing justice and taking an illegal
gratuity. He received a 30-month sentence in that case.
</TEXT>
