<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Governor'sRecount     11-18 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Governor's Recount,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sundlun Ready to Concede Governor's Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Bruce G. Sundlun was ready to
concede the governor's race after picking up only 61 votes on
Republican Gov. Edward DiPrete during a recount ended Thursday,
Sundlun's campaign manager said.
   Sundlun is to make the concession speech Monday, almost two weeks
after the Nov. 8 general election, said campaign manager Kenneth
Haupt.
   ``I don't think there will be a bitter tone to it. He was pleased
with the tone of the campaign and the showing he made,'' Haupt said.
``I think he's going to make it clear that Bruce Sundlun is not
disappearing, because he's not.''
   Sundlun, a millionaire communications executive, was in
Washington on business and unavailable to comment before then, Haupt
said.
   The unofficial tally before the recount was 202,962 for DiPrete
and 196,188 for Sundlun, giving DiPrete a lead of 6,774 votes.
   Frank Williams, vice chairman of the state Elections Board, said
it would be about 10 days before the final tallies would be
certified.
   ``We're pretty well completed. We just have to recalculate the
changes on the tabulation sheets,'' he said.
   Of 1,806 machines, only about 10 had any changes discovered
during the recount, he said. ``That's par for the course,'' Williams
said.
   The recount, which was expected to take three days, began
Wednesday and went more quickly than expected, he said. Officials
from both DiPrete's and Sundlun's campaigns hovered around elections
officials as they opened the back of each machine and read the
meters.
   ``I knew at about 11 o'clock on election night that it was
over,'' Haupt said. ``But I saw that Bruce wanted to know for
absolutely sure that he lost, so that's why I asked for a recount.''
   Sundlun lost to DiPrete by a 2-to-1 margin in 1986 but this year
Sundlun parlayed repeated questions about DiPrete's ethics into the
close race.
   Haupt said the Sundlun campaign office would be closed next
Tuesday.
   DiPrete's spokeswoman could not be reached for comment.
</TEXT>
