<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HospitalKidnapping     11-18 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hospital Kidnapping,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman who Helped Police Recover Baby Given $27,500 Reward</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Acqunetta is cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who tipped police on the
whereabouts of a newborn abducted from a hospital by a woman posing
as a nurse will receive a $27,500 reward, police said Thursday.
   The woman, who requested anonymity, called the Police
Department's hot line Monday and directed police to the Hot Springs
home of Acqunetta Rushon Smith, where the missing baby, Christopher
Michael Jones, was found. The 6-week-old premature infant was taken
from Doctors Hospital on Nov. 1, three days after he had been born
to Annette Thomas-Jones.
   ``The concerned caller that gave us the tip that allowed us to
recover the baby is very deserving of the reward and we'll see that
she gets that reward,'' said Little Rock Police Chief Louis Caudell.
   The reward consisted of $10,000 contributed by Doctors Hospital;
$10,000 from ``USA Today: The Television Show;'' $2,500 from
Arkansas Easter Seals; $1,000 from St. John's Baptist Church, the
parish of the baby's parents; $1,000 from Little Rock Children's
Clinic; $1,000 from Protecting Arkansas Children Together; $1,000
from the Little Rock Police Crimestoppers Program; and two $500
contributions from anonymous donors.
   Ms. Smith, 32, was arrested Monday. She pleaded innocent and
innocent by reason of insanity Wednesday in Pulaski County Circuit
Court pleaded innocent and innocent by reason of mental disease or
defect to a charge of permanent detention or restraint.
   Caudell wouldn't comment on the case because of a gag order
imposed by Circuit Judge Floyd Lofton.
</TEXT>
