<1ST_LINE>r p PM-DemocraticChiefs     11-18 0647</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Democratic Chiefs,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Party Leaders Want Kirk To Remain National Chairman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic state party leaders are doing a
post-mortem on yet another presidential election defeat and
appealing to Paul G. Kirk Jr. to serve another term as national
chairman to avert a potentially divisive contest for his job.
   Also on the minds of Democratic leaders are questions about
whether the party needs to re-examine its method of nominating
presidential candidates after its fifth defeat in the last six
national elections.
   ``I don't think we ought to go leaping off any cliffs,'' said
Kathy Vick, a former Louisiana Democratic Party chair.
   ``One thing I'm going to resist and resist as forcefully as I can
is the over-reaction, over-analysis, over-revisionist theory of
politics,'' said Kirk.
   Much of the attention at a two-day meeting of the Association of
State Democratic Chairs beginning today will be on Kirk, who has
refused to say whether he would serve another four-year term. His
term expires in February.
   At least five people who'd like to succeed Kirk planned to attend
the meeting at a resort outside the Arizona capital.
   They include Rick Wiener, the Michigan Democratic Party chairman,
who is president of the state chairs association; Ron Brown, a
Washington attorney who was a top adviser to Jesse Jackson in the
final weeks of his presidential campaign; and three former
congressmen, Jim Jones of Oklahoma, Michael Barnes of Maryland and
Jim Stanton of Ohio.
   When Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis carried only
10 states while losing to Republican George Bush, it still was the
best showing by a Democratic nominee since 1976.
   The Democrats have been on the losing side in five of the last
six presidential elections but have controlled the House for 33
years and have been the majority party in the Senate for 27 of those
33 years.
   While Dukakis was losing, the Democrats added one Senate seat and
three House seats.
   Several state party officials, who had thought 1988 would be a
Democratic year, have been sharply critical of the Dukakis campaign.
   ``The worst campaign of this century,'' said Bob Slagle, chairman
of the Texas Democratic Party.
   Slagle criticized Dukakis for failing to respond quickly and
strongly enough to attacks by the Bush campaign.
   ``We never gave people a reason to vote for us,'' said James
Ruvolo, the Ohio party chairman.
   Kirk has said that party leaders who have asked him to stay on
the job have cited his success at promoting unity among differing
factions.
   ``I'm going to listen to the counsel of a number of the leaders
and elected officials in the party who have said, `Don't say you
won't stay on until we have an opportunity to chat with you about
it.' So, that's my plan.
   ``I owe it to them to visit with them and hear what they have to
say.''
   Kirk ruled out staying on for a partial term.
   At the same time, Kirk dismissed predictions that a fight to fill
the chairmanship would be divisive.
   ``I don't foresee in any circumstances the so-called
blood-letting and the division within the party,'' he said.
   Brown, who has served as deputy party chairman and counsel in the
past, is opposed by activists who believe his election would give
Jackson too much power.
   Brown conceded his chances would depend on reminding party
officials that ``I wasn't born in May (when he joined the Jackson
campaign) and that I did have a life before then.''
   He said many of the people ``who are raising the Jackson
connection are the same ones who were telling me how glad they were
and how wonderful it was'' that he had agreed to be Jackson's
convention manager.
   At the time, Democratic Party officials expressed relief that a
party establishment figure like Brown was going to play a prominent
role advising Jackson.
</TEXT>
