<1ST_LINE>d a BC-Opera     11-18 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Opera,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Soprano Sings `Butterfly'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Japanese soprano, Yoko Watanabe, sang the title
part as the Metropolitan Opera performed Puccini's ``Madama
Butterfly'' for the first time this season on Thursday night.
   Miss Watanabe made her Met debut in the same role in 1986. She is
enormously effective in the part. Her voice is big but she can make
it seem small, befitting a demure personality. She sounded as fresh
at the end of the opera as at the beginning.
   Miss Watanabe's voice isn't emotional or lushly beautiful but she
delivered the story of love and betrayal by singing the music very
well. She made an affecting Madama Butterfly. The audience responded
with enthusiastic applause.
   Myung-Whun Chung from Korea, who also made his Met debut in 1986,
was conducting this opera for the first time at the Met. He
impresses as a sensitive conductor who knows what he's doing.
   Brenda Boozer of Atlanta sang Suzuki, Butterfly's maid. They were
well cast, both slender young women with attractive voices with
vibrato. They blended well. Sondra Kelly, who has been singing with
the Connecticut Opera, made her Met debut as Kate Pinkerton, a
walk-on. Later this season she will sing in ``Die Walkuere.''
   Giorgio Lamberti has the right kind of focused tenor voice to
sing U.S. Navy Lieutenant Pinkerton. Leo Nucci of Italy sang U.S.
Consul Sharpless. Nucci's voice and deportment seem more impressive
each time he's heard. One paid more attention to Sharpless than
usual, as always happens with medium-size parts when they're well
sung. Fortunately for audiences here, Nucci is singing in four
operas at the Met this season.
   The production dates from 1958, in the old Metropolitan Opera
House. A couple of makeshift wings, which surely could be improved
on, attempt to make it look wide enough for this stage. But it's
still two beautiful sets, of the garden of Butterfly's house and the
interior.
</TEXT>
