<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Baltics Bjt   11-18 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baltics, Bjt,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lithuanians Debating Challenge To Moscow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lithuanian lawmakers convened to debate a challenge
to Moscow's authority, and residents of neighboring Latvia today
marked their republic's pre-Soviet independence in another
outpouring of Baltic nationalism. This week in Estonia, the third
Soviet Baltic republic, the parliament declared Estonia's
sovereignty in all matters but defense and foreign affairs. It
passed a constitutional amendment requiring Estonian approval of any
new Soviet law.
   In Lithuania, hundreds of demonstrators converged Thursday on the
parliament building with banners and flags, according to Veleya
Terleckiene. The demonstrators carried flags of formerly independent
Lithuania and banners supporting Lithuanian autonomy, said Ms.
Terleckiene, the daughter of Anastas Terleckas, a leader of the
separatist Lithuanian Liberty League.
   Lithuanians watched on live television as their legislators
convened a session expected to take up a declaration of Lithuanian
as the official language and other laws following Estonia's example.
   Alexander Gelbaf, deputy editor of the official newspaper
Sovietskaya Litva, said in a telephone interview that the parliament
took up only budgetary matters Thursday. He said the constitutional
questions related to relations with the central government would be
debated beginning today.
   Ms. Terleckiene said the entire republic, including members of
the Communist Party, supported initiatives of the grassroots
Lithuanian People's Front being debated in parliament.
   Meanwhile, in Latvia, residents planned demonstrations and
rallies for today, the 70th anniversary of the birth of their
short-lived independent nation.
   The three Baltic republics of Lithuania, Latvia, and Estonia were
independent countries between the world wars. The Soviet Union
annexed them in 1940 after a pact with the Nazis.
   The United States backed the Baltic nationalists Thursday. State
Department spokesman Charles Redman said in Washington: ``The United
States does not recognize the forcible incorporation of the Baltic
states. ... The people of the Baltic states have been denied their
basic human rights.''
   It is not yet clear how Kremlin authorities will deal with the
latest outburst of Baltic nationalism. On Thursday, they called
Estonian leaders to Moscow to discuss Wednesday's challenge to
central control, but no date has been set for the meeting.
   The Kremlin has shown signs of impatience with the Baltics.
Politburo member Alexander N. Yakovlev, believed to be President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's closest adviser, said in an interview last
month that the republics will not be allowed to take any major steps
toward independence.
   The Estonian parliament made its challenge under the banner of
the reform effort Gorbachev calls perestroika. The challenge
underscores Gorbachev's problems with rising ethnic feelings that
could spread to other areas.
   Thousands of Baltic people have joined grassroots nationalist
groups. Some say privately their ultimate goal is secession from the
Soviet Union.
   Baltic nationalists have been angered by amendments to the
national constitution proposed by Gorbachev. They say the changes
would shift the little power they now hold to Moscow and eliminate
their constitutional right to secede.
</TEXT>
