<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TreasuryAuction     11-18 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasury Auction,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yields on 30-Year Bonds Hit Nine-Month Low</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yields on 30-year Treasury bonds fell in the
latest auction to the lowest level in nine months.
   The average yield Thursday was 9.10 percent, down from 9.17
percent at the last auction on May 12.
   It was the lowest rate since 30-year bonds averaged 8.51 percent
on Feb. 4. The bonds will carry a coupon interest rate of 9 percent
with each $10,000 in face value selling for $9,897.00.
   A total of $9.03 billion in bonds were sold out of bids totaling
$21.6 billion.
   The Treasury Department normally auctions 30-year bonds every
three months, but had to cancel the August sale and postpone the
November sale for a week because it previously had sold nearly as
many of the bonds as Congress had authorized.
   But tax legislation signed by President Reagan on Nov. 11 lifted
the limits, paving the way for Thursday's auction.
</TEXT>
