<2ND_LINE>PM-Hospital Unions,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Health Care Workers' Unions Agree to Merge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two unions representing the majority of
organized health care workers in privately owned hospitals and
nursing homes have agreed to merge.
   The 70,000 members of the National Union of Hospital and Health
Care Employees will be asked in January to approve a plan to merge
with the 875,000-member Service Employees International Union. Both
unions belong to the AFL-CIO.
   ``There's a need for us to consolidate resources and our ability
to win strikes, too,'' Jerome P. Brown, the Hospital Employees
union's secretary-treasurer, said Thursday.
   The industry is changing rapidly in terms of chains taking over
nursing homes and hospitals becoming subsidiaries of holding
companies ``in all types of other businesses,'' he said.
   ``With cost containment pressures coming from the government and
health plan providers, the people who are getting it in the neck are
the workers,'' he said.
   SEIU President John Sweeney said the Hospital Employees would
continue as ``an autonomous national local'' within his union.
   ``When added to the new bargaining unit rules we've finally pried
from the NLRB, the combined strength we now have means we will have
the clout to successfully do battle with the giant conglomerates
gobbling up the hospital industry,'' Sweeney said.
   The Hospital Employees, with a membership that is more than 50
percent black or Hispanic, was the only major union to endorse Jesse
Jackson's presidential candidacy this year.
   It broke off from the Retail, Wholesale and Department Store
Union in 1984 and has been seeking a merger partner ever since.
   Local 1199 of the Hospital Employees union and its 75,000 members
in New York City voted to remain a part of the retail clerks union.
   The merger was announced just seven weeks after the National
Labor Relations Board issued proposed new regulations that would
make it much easier for unions to organize hospital workers. Only
about 10 percent of the nation's health care workers belong to
unions.
</TEXT>
