<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Canada-US Bjt   11-18 0621</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canada-US, Bjt,0638</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>How Canada Will Negotiate Its U.S. Trade Pact Depends On Who's
Talking</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   How will Canada negotiate with its powerful
southern neighbor after Monday's election decides the fate of the
Canada-U.S. free trade agreement? That depends on which candidate
for prime minister is talking.
   Opposition Liberal Party leader John Turner, who wants to cancel
the deal, says he will tell President-elect George Bush that
President Reagan out-negotiated Prime Minister Brian Mulroney on the
agreement signed in January.
   In a crowd-pleasing routine that has been polished through weeks
of campaigning to place the Liberals in a dead heat with the prime
minister's Progressive Conservative Party, Turner imitates
Mulroney's responses to President Reagan's requests.
   ``Yes, sir, Mr. President,'' Turner replies submissively to each
point with a crisp salute. He charges the prime minister wants to be
``governor of the 51st state.''
   Mulroney resorts to sarcasm as well in his increasingly biting
attacks, describing a potential meeting next year if his rival
becomes prime minister.
   ``Imagine Mr. Turner going to Washington to say, `Hey, President
Bush _ I just tore up the free-trade accord and now if you have 15
minutes, we'll negotiate an acid-rain treaty.
   ``You know what the president would say?'' Mulroney asks. ``He'd
say exactly what your mother-in-law would say _ `Hey, this guy can't
be serious.'''
   Canada claims half the acid rain falling in eastern Canada
originates in the United States, making it one of the most
troublesome issues between the two countries.
   The free trade agreement has been approved by the U.S. Congress
but needs final Canadian parliamentary approval. The socialist New
Democratic Party led by Ed Broadbent also opposes the deal, so only
a Conservative majority victory ensures the agreement will start
taking effect Jan. 1 as scheduled.
   The relationship with Washington attracted special attention
Thursday because of Reagan's speech on international trade in
Washington in which he spoke favorably of the Canadian agreement.
   ``As far as the United States is concerned, the Free Trade
Agreement is an example of cooperation at its best. It is a
testament to the commitment of our two governments to the principles
of the open market and to economic cooperation,'' Reagan said.
   Turner immediately described the speech as intervention in
Canadian affairs.
   ``As a Canadian, and with no anti-American sentiment at all, I
resent the intervention into our election,'' the Liberal leader said
during a campaign stop in Quebec.
   Turner also said the speech was very similar to language used by
Mulroney, adding that such phrases ``could have been written by Mr.
Mulroney and perhaps they were.''
   The Conservatives have denied reports they sought any support or
extra assurances on the agreement from Washington to calm down
Canadian opposition to the pact.
   Broadbent, whose party is expected to finish third with a key
position of influence if the Conservatives or Liberals fail to win a
majority, said Reagan's speech could harm Mulroney's chances.
   ``It will remind every Canadian how close Brian Mulroney is to
Ronald Reagan,'' Broadbent said on a campaign stop in Edmonton,
Alberta. ``It will remind every Canadian the Americans got virtually
everything they wanted in this deal.''
   The Canadian Press news agency said in its report from Washington
on the speech that Reagan ``offered passing praise'' for the deal,
``keeping his remarks as innocuous as possible in a bid to avoid
accusations of trying to influence the outcome of Monday's Canadian
election.''
   U.S. officials have not said whether any retaliation is planned
if Canada decides against the agreement. The two nations already are
each other's largest trading partner, with the $150 billion passing
between them each year making it the world's largest trading
partnership.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881118-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-88 0215EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-Afghans     11-18 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Afghans,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Officials Say Afghan Deputy Foreign Minister Defected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghanistan's deputy foreign minister and a
senior diplomat who accompanied Afghanistan's prime minister on his
mission to the United Nations defected last week, according to U.S.
officials.
   The officials said on condition of anonymity Thursday that
Afghanistan's deputy foreign minister, Abdul Ghaffar Lakanwal,
sought political asylum in the United States.
   Authorities say Lakanwal is the highest-ranking member of the
Soviet-backed regime to have defected since Soviet troops entered
Afghanistan in 1979.
   Sources at the United Nations and with the U.S. government could
only identify the other defector as a senior diplomat whose name was
given as Kamal. But the Washington Post, in today's editions,
identified him as Sayed Kamaluddin.
   The Post quoted unidentified U.S. officials as saying Lakanwal,
43, came to New York to attend the U.N. General Assembly session in
late October to prepare for the visit of the Afghan prime minister,
Mohammed Sharq. He then flew to Washington alone on Nov. 7 and went
to the State Department, seeking asylum, the officials were quoted
as saying.
   Two days later, Kamaluddin, who was part of the Afghan U.N.
delegation and deputy director of the Afghan foreign ministry's
department for internal conferences, defected in the same manner as
Lakanwal, the newspaper said.
   The Post cited unidentified State Department officials as saying
the families of Lakanwal and Kamaluddin were outside Afghanistan and
seeking to join the men in the United States.
   The Justice Department's Immigration and Naturalization Service
has made no decision whether to grant Lakanwal and Kamaluddin
political refugee status, the newspaper reported.
   One official was quoted as telling the Post there was a third
lower-ranking Afghan government official who also has sought asylum
in the United States since July, but the newspaper did not identify
that person.
   Lakanwal's career had been in decline, said Rosanne Klass, a
former New York Times reporter who wrote ``Afghanistan, The Great
Game Revisited.'' He was Agriculture and Land Reform minister from
1981 to March 1987, when he was dropped from the Cabinet.
   No spokesmen were immediately available at Afghanistan's U.N.
mission.
</TEXT>
