<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     11-18 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Recovers Slightly; Stocks Hit Record High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar recovered slightly in Tokyo Friday after
a heavy beating the previous day, and stock prices set another
record high.
   After opening at 122.15 yen, up 0.63 yen from Thursday's 121.52
yen finish, the dollar edged up, closing the week at 122.40 yen, up
0.88 yen. It ranged between 122.07 and 122.60 yen during the day.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues finished the week at 29,180.20 points, up 103.39
points or 0.36 percent.
   Dealers attributed the dollar's rebound to overnight
dollar-buying by central banks. They said the Bank of Japan
continued actively to buy dollars Friday when the currency was
trading at around 122.10-122.15 yen.
   The intervention Friday followed comments by Japan's Finance
Minister Kiichi Miyazawa that Japan and other major monetary
countries are poised to intervene in the market if the American
currency continues its nosedive against the yen.
   The dollar has fallen a hefty 4.36 yen since the start of the
month.
   Speaking during a regularly scheduled press conference, Miyazawa
said the currency stabilization agreement among the seven major
industrialized nations was still intact.
   ``The dollar also rose marginally because market participants
felt it has taken a strong beating from the yen recently,'' said a
dealer with a major Japanese bank.
   ``The dollar may rise slightly next week, but the trend is
downward till the end of the year,'' the dealer added, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the rally was led mainly by active
dealings on steel issues which in turn focused attention on other
large-capital stocks, the dealer said.
   ``The strong activity reflects confidence in Japanese economic
fundamentals,'' he said.
</TEXT>
