<DOCNO> AP881118-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-88 0232EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SexHormones     11-18 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sex Hormones,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canadian Study Shows Women's Abilities Vary With Hormone Levels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Women can talk more fluently and move their hands
more skillfully when their sex hormones are at high levels,
according to a study believed to be the first linking human
performance to sex hormones.
   The research, on 200 women during their menstrual cycle and
post-menopausal women on estrogen-replacement therary, is by Doreen
Kimura of the University of Western Ontario in London, Ontario.
   It shows women perform significantly better in verbal fluency and
fine-motor muscular control when their estrogen and progesterone
levels are high.
   Kimura's study also showed that women's ability to perform
spatial tasks is enhanced by lower hormone levels.
   The researcher said similar patterns probably occur in men, whose
sex hormone testosterone fluctuates daily.
   Kimura, who spoke Wednesday at a news briefing during the annual
meeting of the Society for Neuroscience, compared women's spatial
cognition and verbal and motor abilities during times of peak and
low hormone levels.
   The levels rise and fall during the course of a woman's menstrual
cycle. The peak estrogen phase begins just before ovulation and
extends until a week to 10 days before menstruation. A drop in
hormone levels occurs during menstruation.
   Spatial tasks that Kimura tested involved identifying a shape in
a complex pattern. Tongue-twisters tested verbal skills, and
fine-motor tasks included rapid changing of hand postures.
   Men generally do better on such spatial problems, but women on
average score better on the verbal and fine-motor tasks.
   In the low-hormone phase, it might take a woman three seconds
longer to repeat a tongue-twister correctly than during her peak
level, the researcher said.
   ``With motor-tasks, women say, `Gosh, I'm really clumsy this
week,''' said Kimura.
   She said her study supports the idea that male-female cognitive
differences are influenced by sex hormones acting on the brain. She
said she is now studying how men's abilities might vary according to
the level of testosterone.
   ``It's easier to identify these things in women, but my guess is
they can happen also in males,'' said Kimura.
   She acknowledged that the study suggests there may be optimal
times for women to perform certain tasks, such as taking
standardized academic examinations.
   ``We really don't know enough yet,'' she said. ``It may be in a
couple of years we'll know enough about it to say there are
significant enough effects that these can be factors in test scores
and performance.''
   Kimura stressed that abilities vary greatly among individual men
and women, with some women better at tasks in which men generally
excel.
   ``There's an enormous overlap in the ability patterns between men
and women,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881118-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-88 0249EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-B1B-Crash 2ndLd-Writethru a0458 11-18 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-B1B-Crash, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0458,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Washington</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with quotes from Rapid City, other details; Picks up
8th graf pvs, `The Air...'
^B-1B Bomber Crashes in South Dakota</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RAPID CITY, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A B-1B bomber crashed near Ellsworth Air
Force Base in western South Dakota, the second accident involving
the long-range strategic jet in two weeks, authorities said early
Friday.
   The B-1B crashed on the runway as it came in for a landing at
about 1:30 a.m. EST, officials said. There was no immediate word on
the extent of injuries to the crew.
   ``From monitoring the ambulance traffic, they say they were going
to Ellsworth base hospital with four or five patients. We don't know
if they're dead or alive,'' said Lt. Fred Brown of the Rapid City
Police Department.
   However, Navy Lt. Cmdr. James Kudla, a spokesman for the Defense
Department in Washington, said, ``Right now at least it looks like
there were no fatalities.''
   The crash comes two days after officials reported that the Air
Force had inspected and cleared more than two-thirds of the B-1B
bombers grounded following a crash last week that destroyed one of
the long-range planes in Texas.
   Brown said the B-1B crashed on the runway as it came in for a
landing at Ellsworth, which lies on the eastern edge of Rapid City.
He said it did not hit any buildings and no one on the ground was
known to be injured.
   ``Witnesses saw four people eject from the airplane before it
crashed,'' Brown said. ``It is possible that it came in too low and
hit a power pole.''
   ``Ellsworth has told us it was carrying a six-man crew,'' he
said, adding that the jet normally carried four.
   Witnesses reported a downed power line and airplane parts
scattered in the landing area, he said. Power was reported out in
Box Elder, a town south of the base.
   On Nov. 8, a B-1B crashed and burned in a field near Dyess Air
Force Base, Texas. It had been the second accident to claim one of
the new bombers in 14 months. In that crash, the crew of four
managed to eject and survived.
   That crash was the third in four years since B-1 aircraft began
flying as the nation's first new long-range bomber in more than 25
years.
   Strategic Air Command spokesman Lt. Col. George H. Peck said
Tuesday that 63 of the 85 B-1B's located at SAC bases had been
inspected as of Tuesday without any problems being detected.
   The Air Force has refused to speculate on the cause of the Texas
crash, although a fire had been observed by witnesses around the
plane's left two engines before the crash. SAC's grounding order
specified a mandatory inspection of electric, fuel and hydraulic
fluid lines.
   In addition to Ellsworth and Dyess, the bombers also have been
deployed to Grand Forks AFB, N.D., and McConnell AFB, Kan.
   The Air Force has been criticized over the past two years for its
handling of the B-1B program, primarily because of acknowledged
problems in developing the bomber's radar-jamming gear. However, the
service insists the plane is the best long-range bomber in the world.
</TEXT>
