<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NRC Staff Calls For Removal Of Obstacle For Seabrook Low-Power
License</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission says a key
financial issue has been resolved and should no longer be an
obstacle to granting a low-power operating license for the Seabrook,
N.H., nuclear plant.
   The commission ordered Seabrook's owners in September to
``provide reasonable assurance'' that ``adequate funds'' are
available to decommission the plant if the NRC issues a 5 percent
power testing license but eventually refuses to grant a full-power
commercial license.
   The request came because of ``unique and unusual circumstances''
surrounding the financial status of Seabrook. Public Service Company
of New Hampshire, the plant's lead owner, in January became the
first major electric utility to file for bankruptcy protection since
the Depression.
   In a report made available Thursday, NRC staff counsel Gregory
Alan Berry said the owners' decommissioning plan, submitted last
month, was adequate and recommended that the commissioners remove
that regulatory obstacle, one of just two remaining in Seabrook's
quest for a testing license.
   ``The plan ... provides reasonable assurance that funds would be
available to decommission Seabrook Station after low-power operation
if a full-power authorization is not granted,'' Berry wrote. ``Ample
funds are available.''
   The other remaining issue, whether the plant is financially
qualified to run the reactor, also is pending.
</TEXT>
