<HEAD>Immigrations Board Says IRA Member Can Pursue Efforts to Avoid</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Deportation
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Immigration Appeals Board has ruled that
Joseph Doherty of the Irish Republican Army, wanted for the killing
of a British soldier, should be allowed to proceed with legal
efforts to avoid deportation from the United States.
   Doherty's attorney, Mary Pike, received a copy of the opinion
Thursday. The board had made its decision Monday.
   Under the 3-2 ruling, Doherty is entitled to a hearing before an
immigration judge where he could present claims for political asylum
and withholding of deportation. Doherty would have to show a
well-founded fear of persecution to substantiate an asylum claim.
   On June 14, then-Attorney General Edwin Meese III refused a
request by Doherty to be deported to Ireland instead of to Britain.
That order was appealed.
   The government may appeal the latest ruling to Attorney General
Dick Thornburgh.
   Doherty has been held in a federal jail _ the Metropolitan
Correctional Center in lower Manhattan _ for five years while courts
weighed whether the slaying was a political act, for which he could
not be extradited to Britain.
   Doherty was convicted in 1981 of killing a British Army captain
in an ambush on a British convoy in Belfast. In the closing days of
his trial, Mr. Doherty escaped from a prison in Northern Ireland and
fled to the United States, where he was arrested in 1983.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Summer Drought Effects Still Felt on Many U.S. Waterways</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The summer drought is not over for the nation's
waterways, according to government scientists.
   A report released Thursday showed that nearly 40 percent of
streams in the lower 48 states had below-normal flow during October.
   ``When will the drought be over? I don't know,'' Tom Ross,
supervisory hydrologist at the U.S. Geological Survey, said in a
statement.
   Precipitation was well above average in September in much of the
country and above average in the East in October. Ross said
precipitation through February in mountain areas and through the
spring in the Southeast would determine whether flow moved closer to
normal.
   Monitoring stations on 53 percent of western streams reported
below-normal October flow. Forty-six percent of Great Lakes streams
were below normal but only 28 percent of those in the Northeast.
   The ``Big Three'' rivers _ the Columbia, Mississippi and St.
Lawrence _ averaged a combined 324 billion gallons per day, 22
percent below normal but well above the record low of 257 billion
gallons per day in October 1936.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Local Reliance on Federal Aid Is Dropping</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Census Bureau says state and local
government reliance on federal aid last year sank to its lowest
level in more than 20 years.
   From a high of 18.7 cents per dollar of state and local
government revenue in 1978, the federal contribution withered to
13.6 cents in 1987. It was the lowest since 1966, when Lyndon
Johnson was gearing up the Great Society programs and the federal
contribution was 13.5 cents per dollar.
   Total federal aid actually has risen throughout the period _ from
$70 billion in 1978, to $113 billion in 1986 to $115 billion in
1987. But it is increasing at a slower rate than other state and
local government revenues.
   While the federal contribution grew at an average of 5.7 percent
a year from 1978 to 1987, the amount raised by state and local taxes
grew an average of 8.5 percent a year.
   Last year, state and local taxes grew 8.6 percent to $405.1
billion, while federal aid increased only 1.7 percent. Revenue from
all sources totaled $842.6 billion.
   Henry Wulf, a Census Bureau analyst, said the federal share
likely will slip again in future years because state and local
governments will be increasing spending to upgrade
``infrastructure'' items such as sewers and roads.
</TEXT>
