<HEAD>$500 Million Pledged in Flood Assistance To Bangladesh</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Governments and financial organizations
have pledged $500 million in flood relief and reconstruction to
Bangladesh, less than one-half of the $1.13 billion requested by
Bangladesh and the United Nations.
   The United Nations made the announcement Wednesday. About $200
million of the $500 million already has been contributed for
short-term flood relief and long-term reconstruction and
rehabilitation.
   Early in September, Bangladesh was ravaged by the worst floods of
this century. The floods killed hundreds of people and inundated
much of the countryside of the Asian nation, one of the world's
poorest.
   Contributions were announced by numerous U.N. organizations and
other world bodies. They included $182 million from the United
States, $130.5 million from Canada and $95 million from the
International Monetary Fund.
