<HEAD>Soviet Union Recognizes Palestinian State</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union today recognized the declaration
of an independent Palestinian state, saying Palestinians have shown
great realism and had the right to their own homeland.
   ``Faithful to the fundamental principle of freedom of choice, the
Soviet Union recognizes the proclamation of the Palestinian state,
being guided by the realization that a comprehensive settlement will
lead also to the practical completion of the historic process of
creating this state,'' said First Deputy Foreign Minister Alexander
Bessmertnykh.
   Bessmertnykh told a hastily called news briefing that while
proclaiming an independent state, Palestinians had displayed ``a
great deal of responsibility and realism'' during their
deliberations earlier this week.
   The Palestine National Council, the policy-making body of the
Palestine Liberation Organization, on Tuesday declared an
independent Palestinian state and said it conditionally accepted a
U.N. resolution affirming Israel's right to exist.
   The Soviet Union's recognition comes at a time when it is moving
toward closer diplomatic ties with Israel after years of support for
its Arab enemies.
</TEXT>
