<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon-Kidnap     11-18 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Kidnap,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Militia And PLO Search Sidon For Swiss Kidnap Victim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sunni Moslem militiamen and PLO guerrillas
searched this port city today for signs of a Swiss delegate of the
International Committee of the Red Cross who was kidnapped a day
earlier by gunmen.
   Joint patrols combed the huge Ein El-Hilweh refugee camp and
nearby orange and banana groves on Sidon's southern outskirts amid
heavy donwpours for clues on the whereabouts of Peter Winkler.
   ``We've contacted everybody, all Palestinian and Lebanese groups
in Sidon, and so far there has been no word on Winkler,'' said
Winkler's Red Cross collegue, Gerard Bise. No group has claimed
responsibility for the abduction.
   However, police and the Popular Nasserite Organization that has
governed Sidon since the 1975 outbreak of Lebanon's civil war said
they believe he was kidnapped for a trade-off with Hussein Hariri, a
Lebanese Shiite Moslem aircraft hijacker held in Switzerland since
last year.
   Hariri, 22, a member of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, is accused
of hijacking an Air Afrique jetliner that was flying from Rome to
Paris and forcing it to land at Geneva on July 24, 1987. He also is
accused of killing a French passenger before he was overpowered and
arrested.
   No trial date has been set in Geneva.
   The fundamentalist Hezbollah, or Party of God, is an umbrella
group for pro-Iranian extremist factions holding most of the 14
foreign hostages, including nine Americans, in Lebanon.
   The longest held is Terry A. Anderson, 41, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press, who was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
   A police spokesman theorized the Fatah-Revolutionary Council
faction of Palestinian terrorist mastermind Abu Nidal kidnapped
Winkler ``on behalf of Hezbollah.''
   ``The two groups have long been allied. Hezbollah is believed to
have requested Abu Nidal's people to kidnap the Swiss for a possible
exchange for Hariri because Hezbollah does not maintain any presence
in the Sidon region,'' the spokesman said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   About 80,000 Palestinians reside in the predominantly Sunni Sidon
region, mainly in Ein El-Hilweh and the nearby Mieh Mieh refugee
camp. Previous attempts to find kidnap victims in south Lebanon have
not always succeeded.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
