<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Fuller-Resignation 2ndLd-Writethru a0476 11-18 0750</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fuller-Resignation, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0476,710</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing thruout</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bush's Longtime Chief of Staff Leaving in January</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush's right-hand man for the last four
years, Craig Fuller, said today that John Sununu's selection as
presidential chief of staff _ and not his _ shows Bush wants to
``bring in new people and energize the system.''
   Fuller, interviewed on the ``CBS Morning News,'' said he's not
upset that Bush passed him over in favor of Sununu, the governor of
New Hampshire.
   Asked if felt any sense of betrayal, Fuller replied ``none
whatsoever'' and added that Bush had ``chosen a fine man to head his
staff.''
   Fuller, the vice president's chief of staff for the last four
years, noted that Bush had said he wanted to ``bring a new team into
Washington'' and added:
   ``The selection of John Sununu shows that that commitment starts
right with the man standing next to him in the White House in the
chief of staff job. I think it is a time to bring new people in and
energize the system and let some of us who have been there
particularly for eight years go out and help in other ways and do
other things.''
   On Thursday, Fuller, the co-director of Bush's transition office,
called The Associated Press before Sununu's appointment was
announced to reveal that having been passed over for chief of staff,
he would quit working for Bush as of Jan. 20.
   Fuller said he informed Bush before the election that the only
post he would accept in the new administration was chief of staff.
   This morning, Fuller said that key jobs in the new administration
``are somehow viewed as contests and that's really not the way
George Bush made this selection.''
   ``I talked with the vice president in October during the campaign
and said that I thought he was going to be elected and if he was,
I'd really like to return to the private sector,'' Fuller said.
   ``I worked hard because I wanted to see George Bush elected,''
Fuller said. ``I got that, and I'm ready to move on to the next
phase of Craig Fuller's life.''
   Asked at a Thursday afternoon news conference whether he would
try to dissuade Fuller from leaving, Bush said, ``I'd like to
because I have such a high regard for him.''
   For his part, Sununu said he hopes Bush can ``succeed in twisting
(Fuller's) arm between now and inauguration day and keeping Craig in
a position of responsibility.''
   Fuller, 37, who succeeded Adm. Daniel Murphy as Bush's chief of
staff in February 1985, said earlier that he had told Bush he
``would be eager'' to the serve Bush in the same capacity if Bush
were elected.
   On Election Day, Fuller said, Bush ``indicated to me that he
wanted Sununu, and that if my wishes were to return to the private
sector, he'd understand. I said that I would think about it. ... He
knew I would be willing to do it (serve as chief of staff) if he
wanted me to do it.''
   Fuller said he was not interested in any job other than chief of
staff, and since he did not get it, ``I decided it was a good break
time after eight years. I got what I wanted, and that was George
Bush getting elected.''
   Fuller said he was upset with widespread news reports in recent
days, which said he had been jockeying with Sununu, 49, for the top
job, since he had promised the vice president he would remain quiet
about Bush's decision until Sununu's appointment was announced.
   With Thursday's announcement, Fuller said, he no longer felt
obliged to stay quiet.
   Fuller said he thought Sununu would ``do a good job,'' and said
``there's not a trace of bitterness at all. John Sununu is a good
friend ... and he's going to get every ounce of support from me.''
   Fuller, whose wife, Karen, is a White House secretary, said he
had no plans beyond Jan. 20, when Bush will be sworn in as
president, except to say the couple will take a trip to Africa in
March.
   Before coming to Washington as a member of President Reagan's
White House staff in January 1981, Fuller had been a vice president
and corporate secretary of Deaver & Hannaford Inc., a Los
Angeles-based public affairs consulting firm.
