<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Brady-Economy     11-18 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brady-Economy,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush Rdp</HEAD>
<HEAD>Treasury Secretary Doubts Deficit Fueling Currency Fall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady said today he
does not believe that concern over the U.S. deficit has caused the
fall in the value of the dollar or the declines on stock markets
since George Bush was elected president.
   Brady also said he does not expect interest rates to rise.
   ``Markets go up and down,'' Brady said on NBC-TV's ``Today''
show. ``The currency markets, which are down in the last six weeks,
are really at the same levels they were in January of last year. I
don't really worry about it very much.''
   Asked if the declines indicate a lack of confidence in Bush's
ability to overcome the deficit, Brady said, ``I just disagree. The
Bush deficit-reduction plan, which is called a flexible freeze, will
work. I think we have to give the vice president a little time to
put his team together.''
   ``I'm confident that things will work out just fine,'' said
Brady, who will continue as treasury secretary when Bush takes
office Jan. 20.
   But New Hampshire Gov. John Sununu, whom Bush has appointed his
presidential chief of staff, said in another interview that there is
``a little bit of nervousness out there.''
   Seeking to reassure the financial community, he added, ``I think
the world can feel comfortable that George Bush knows that strong
leadership in dealing with the deficit is the first priority of this
administration.''
   He was interviewed on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America.''
   Intervention by central banks pushed the dollar up early today in
Europe and Japan, after the dollar closed at a 15-year low against
the Japanese yen on Thursday. U.S. stock markets have fallen more
than 75 points since Bush was elected 10 days ago.
   Brady, said he sees no need for Bush to take action before his
Jan. 20 inauguration to allay the concerns of financial and currency
markets.
   ``I don't think the concern is that big a problem,'' he said,
adding that Bush would work with Congress to combat the deficit.
``I'm confident things will be worked out.''
   ``I don't see anything in the figures right now that would
indicate interest rates are going to rise,'' he said, noting low
unemployment, high economic production and continued economic
expansion.
   Brady said that although Bush has promised not to raise taxes, he
will find ways to cut the deficit.
   ``I think when the vice president gets into office ... you'll
hear from him very directly what he wants to do,'' he said.
   House Majority Leader Thomas Foley of Washington, also
interviewed by NBC, pledged support for the new administration in
dealing with the economy.
   ``It's fair to give the vice president a chance to appoint his
key financial advisers and budget director .... before there is any
discussion with Congress,'' he said. But he said Congress would like
to see a general outline of Bush's plan for approaching the budget.
   ``We're not going to initiate any revenues if the vice president
is going to oppose them,'' Foley said. ``There no danger that the
Democratic Congress is going to go knocking on President Bush's door
insisting on taxes. It's going to have to come from him.''
   Sununu said he expects that in the next few days Bush will
communicate directly with the congressional leadership ``to begin
the kind of interaction that necessary.
   ``I think Congress and the president are going to work
aggressively and quickly to deal with that issue.''
</TEXT>
