<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are the latest developments in
President-elect George Bush's preparations for taking over as chief
executive:
   _Bush flew this morning to Charlottesville, Va., for private
meetings with some of the nation's governors. He was to return for
lunch on Capitol Hill with House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas.
   _On Thursday, Bush had a breakfast meeting with British Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher and lunch with President Reagan. He also
had a chat with former Texas Sen. John Tower, who is rumored to be a
leading candidate for secretary of defense.
   _Among other names mentioned as possible candidates for top Bush
administration posts: Cleveland Mayor George Voinovich, to head
Housing and Urban Development; Donald Rumsfeld, for defense
secretary, and New York Rep. Jack Kemp, for labor secretary.
   _Bush endorsed Lee Atwater, his wily campaign manager, as the
next chairman of the Republican Party.
   _There was unusual turmoil in the Bush ranks when the
president-elect announced his selection of New Hampshire Gov. John
Sununu as chief of staff. Craig L. Fuller, Bush's vice presidential
chief of staff for four years and co-director of the transition,
announced that, having been passed over for the White House chief of
staff job, he would quit working for Bush as of Inauguration Day,
Jan. 20.
   _Bush's office confirmed that he plans to hold a get-acquainted
meeting Tuesday in Houston with Mexico's president-elect, Carlos
Salinas, who assumes office Dec. 1.
   _Bush said the Central Intelligence Agency in his administration
``will clearly be an intelligence agency. It will have no function
in policy at all,'' except to carry out certain covert actions.
