<NOTE>Eds: SUBS first item to CORRECT noun-verb agreement in 5th graf
pvs, `Madonna said ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pop diva Madonna, who got mostly poor reviews for
her Broadway debut in David Mamet's ``Speed-the-Plow,'' says there's
an album in her future but she hasn't given up on acting.
   ``I'm just letting my creative juices take me where they will,''
she said in an interview in December's Fame magazine.
   ``There aren't a lot of great movies to do, so that just works
out fine for me because I haven't done a record in at least two
years,'' she said.
   ``I'm going into the studio to record some stuff that's really
different. As long as I can write songs, I'll make records. When I
get tired of that, when it gets old or I don't have anything to say,
then I won't do it.''
   Madonna said the poor reviews of her acting do not discourage her
because she withstood the same criticism when she started her
singing career.
   ``In the beginning they thought that I was the flavor of the
month. A one-act Disco Dolly who was just going to pop in and pop
out,'' she said.
   ``They slandered me for the first two albums. Finally, on my last
album, they said, OK, she's talented. All right, she can write a
good song. Now I'm going through the same thing with acting and
movies.''
</TEXT>
