<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon-Israel     11-18 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Israel,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinian Guerrillas Attack Israeli Army Post In Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RASHAYA, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian guerrillas today attacked an
Israeli army post in south Lebanon with rockets and automatic fire,
and a security source said one guerrilla was wounded.
   The source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said a ``fierce
battle'' started at midday between the attackers and Israeli
soldiers manning the outpost in the hamlet of Kfarshouba near the
western slopes of Mt. Hermon.
   The source said that at least three guerrillas took part in the
attack. It was not immediately known to which faction they belonged.
   The outpost commands the northern edge of Israel's
self-proclaimed ``security zone'' in south Lebanon and overlooks the
terrain policed by the United Nations peacekeeping force, the source
said.
   ``Around 50 Israeli soldiers are searching the area for the
attackers,'' the source said. He gave no further details.
   Israel retained control of the 6-to-10-mile wide strip when it
withdrew the bulk of its occupation army from south Lebanon in
summer 1985. The zone serves as a buffer against guerrilla attacks
against northern Israeli settlements.
   The 5,800-strong U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon, drawn from nine
countries, patrols terrain north of the security zone.
</TEXT>
