<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CampaignWorkers     11-18 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Campaign Workers,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Campaigners Can Seek Employment Help From Dukakis
Administration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers laid off from Gov. Michael Dukakis'
campaign for president can turn to his administration's employment
program for help in finding new jobs. Unemployed George Bush workers
are welcome, too.
   State officials said it may be the first time the job program has
moved to help laid-off campaign workers.
   A total of 250 people lost their jobs at the Democratic campaign
headquarters.
   ``This is standard procedure,'' said Michelle Andrews, director
of communications for the state Employment and Training office.
``It's something we try to do whenever there's a sizeable layoff.''
   Officials plan to meet Tuesday with campaign workers to provide
job counseling, information on unemployment insurance benefits and
help in finding another job.
   ``That's incredible,'' said state House Minority Leader Steven
Pierce, a Republican. ``I thought they'd just go back to their state
jobs.'' He wanted to know if the same service would be offered to
workers laid off at Bush's Massachusetts headquarters.
   ``It's an interesting idea,'' Ms. Andrews said. ``But, yes,
certainly it's something we'd be glad to help out with.''
   Some Dukakis workers could be headed for state jobs. The posts of
chief of staff and secretary of administration and finance will be
open soon.
   But Kim Manolius, who is handling administration and finance
duties at the Dukakis campaign, said he doubted many campaign
workers would get state jobs.
   ``My understanding is there's a hiring freeze on,'' he said.
</TEXT>
