<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-88 1014EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea-Firebombing     11-18 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Firebombing,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Politicians Protest Attack on U.S. Army Complex</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Politicians today condemned an attack
by South Koreans on a U.S. military housing complex and called on
police to step up security around military housing areas.
   Forty young people wielding clubs and iron pipes and throwing
firebombs attacked the military family housing compound Thursday
night, wounding two U.S. servicemen and damaging or destroying nine
military vehicles and passenger cars, authorities said. The
attackers fled when riot police arrived, and there were no immediate
arrests, they said.
   Gen. Louis C. Menetrey, commander of U.S. Forces in Korea, issued
a statement today calling the attackers ``thugs'' and ``cowardly
criminals'' and said manpower would be increased at the housing
complex and additional security precautions taken immediately.
   Anti-U.S. sentiment has been rising in South Korea in recent
months, and radical students have demanded the ouster of the 42,000
U.S. troops stationed in South Korea under a mutual defense pact.
   Witnesses said the attackers, yelling ``Yankees Go Home'' and
``Drive Out American Imperialists,'' overwhelmed three guards and
stormed the back gate of the Hannam Village complex, one mile from
the 8th U.S. Army headquarters near central Seoul.
   The first serviceman injured was a military policeman on duty.
Witnesses said about 10 young people grabbed him, dragged him behind
the guard house and wrestled him to the ground, beating him with
clubs. Two South Korean guards were shoved out of the way, they said.
   A U.S. Army statement said the second U.S. serviceman was injured
when a pipe thrown at his car shattered the windshield as he was
leaving the compound.
   The names of the two victims were not released.
   A military spokesman said no dependents of service personnel were
injured, but that more than $15,000 in damage was caused.
   The complex, which houses about 2,500 family members of United
States service personnel, was attacked twice in October by radical
students who tore down the American flag and burned it.
   Suh Chung-won, spokesman for the opposition Reunification
Democratic Party, and Kim Joong-wie, spokesman for the governing
Democratic Justice Party, both condemned the raid. Kim said the
government was asking police to take measures to prevent a
recurrence.
   The Seoul office of Pacific Stars and Stripes, the U.S. military
newspaper, said it had been besieged by telephone calls from angry,
frightened residents of the residential complex demanding more
security.
</TEXT>
