<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-88 1014EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Quayle-Senate     11-18 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle-Senate,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marilyn Quayle Says She's Not a Candidate to Fill Husband's Senate
Seat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marilyn Quayle, wife of Vice President-elect
Dan Quayle, today removed herself from the list of possible
candidates to fill her husband's U.S. Senate seat.
   In a statement released by the vice president-elect's transition
office, Mrs. Quayle said she had told Indiana Gov. Robert Orr that
she is not interested in succeeding her husband.
   Quayle, who was elected to the vice presidency Nov. 8, announced
Monday that he would step down as Indiana's senator prior to Jan. 3
to give Republican incumbent Orr _ rather than incoming Democrat
Evan Bayh _ the opportunity to appoint a successor.
   Mrs. Quayle, a lawyer, was among the names mentioned as a
possible replacement.
   ``I appreciate the confidence and support I've received from so
many people in Indiana and around the country,'' Mrs. Quayle said in
the statement. ``However, I have informed Governor (Robert) Orr that
I am not interested in being appointed to fill my husband's seat in
the U.S. Senate.''
   Orr met with Mrs. Quayle on Thursday in Washington. She
emphasized that her responsibilities as the wife of the vice
president and the mother of three school-age children would not
allow her enough time for the Senate job, said Jim Carroll, a
spokesman with the transition office.
   Mrs. Quayle is the second person this week to withdraw from the
list of possible candidates. Mitch Daniels, an Indianapolis lawyer
who served in the Reagan administration, said Wednesday he informed
Orr that he was not interested in the job.
   Daniels was assistant to the president for political and
governmental affairs until his resignation Jan. 31, 1987.
   Other candidates mentioned for the post are Indiana's Lt. Gov.
John M. Mutz, who failed in his bid to succeed Orr, and U.S. Reps.
Dan Coats and Dan Burton, both Republicans.
</TEXT>
