<HEAD>Three Ex-Rhodesian Security Men Sentenced to Death For Murder</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with men sentenced to death.
Pickup 5th graf pvs, ``There were...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN EDLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three former Rhodesian security force men
were sentenced to hang today after being convicted on murder charges
stemming from a bomb attack on a house owned by the main guerrilla
group fighting South Africa.
   The death sentences for the three _ Kevin Woods, 35, a former
member of the security police, Michael Smith, 34, a one-time soldier
in the Rhodesian light infantry, and Phillip Conjwayo, 54, formerly
with the Rhodesian police special branch _ will automatically be
appealed.
   Judge president Wilson Sandura found the trio not guilty of
alternative lesser charges of terrorism or sabotage.
   The state accused the three men of setting off a car bomb with a
remote control device outside a house owned by the African National
Congress in Bulawayo on Jan. 12, killing an unemployed Zambian who
helped with the attack.
   There were no other casualties in the attack, which the state
said was ordered by South African intelligence officers.
   The African National Congress has several houses and offices in
Zimbabwe. The Harare government denies the ANC also has military
bases in Zimbabwe. The group's targets have frequently been bombed
or attacked by troops, allegedly from South Africa, since Zimbabwe's
independence from Britain in 1980.
   Woods and Smith, whites who fought black nationalist guerrillas
in the seven-year war that transformed white-governed Rhodesia into
black-ruled Zimbabwe, described the ANC as a terrorist organization.
   During the trial, state witnesses claimed coded messages were
exchanged between Pretoria and Woods through portable computers.
   The state alleged that Woods, Smith and a third man were behind
two other bomb attacks on ANC targets in Harare in 1986. They will
be tried separately on those charges, which also carry the death
penalty.
</TEXT>
