<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Rice,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Donna Rice Refuses To Speak To Journalist Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donna Rice, the Miami model whose association
with Gary Hart ended his 1988 presidential campaign, canceled an
appearance before a group of journalists today after spotting
cameras waiting for her.
   Ms. Rice said in a handwritten statement moments before her
slated appearance that she had expected her meeting with the Society
of Professional Journalists-Sigma Delta Chi to be private and
off-the-record.
   ``As you are probably aware, for the past year and a half, I have
purposely avoided capitalizing on my notoriety, and except for three
specific interviews, I have declined all media offers,'' she said in
the statement.
   ``When the society's invitation was received, I felt that today
might be an opportunity to quietly and candidly share with you some
of my experiences and observations.
   ``However, it was my original understanding that this panel
discussion was private, and essentially off the record. But when I
arrived a few minutes ago and I saw the cameras, lights and tape
recorders, I realized this wasn't the forum I anticipated.''
   James Plante, national president of SPJ-SDX, said he believed
that Ms. Rice knew her appearance at the Albert B. Sabin Cincinnati
Convention Center would be on the record.
   Plante, an administrator with NBC News in New York, said SPJ-SDX
general counsel Bruce Sanford, who arranged Ms. Rice's appearance
about three weeks ago, had assured Plante that the session would be
on the record.
   ``She was uncomfortable about the cameras,'' said Plante, who
spoke with Ms. Rice moments before her decision to avoid the session.
   ``She wanted to share her ideas about what's happened in her life
with the group privately, but she didn't want to do it in front of
the cameras.''
</TEXT>
