<HEAD>City's Christmas Decorations Tainted By Asbestos Dust</HEAD>
<DATELINE>McALESTER, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city's Christmas decorations have to
be thrown out because they were contaminated by potentially
cancer-causing asbestos dust, but officials today said money has
been donated for replacements.
   Wanda Bass of the First National Community Development Corp. gave
the city a check for $2,500, which will be matched by the city,
officials said.
   The decorations were stored with other city Parks Department
material in the old Navy Reserve center.
   An inspection of the building this year revealed old insulation
was releasing asbestos particles into the air. Asbestos has been
identified as a potential cancer-causing substance when inhaled.
   Mel Priddy, head of the Parks and Recreation Department, said
cleaning the lights and other Christmas decorations would require
more labor than they were worth.
   ``Several items from the same room as the decorations have been
removed and cleaned, but it would probably be a very complicated
process to clean the tinsel,'' he said.
</TEXT>
