<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-88 1105EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LandslideWarnings     11-18 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Landslide Warnings,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Geological Survey Develops Landslide Warning System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MENLO PARK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An agency trying to predict earthquakes
has developed a system to give warnings of another geological
hazard: landslides, which 25 to 50 Americans and cause up to $2
billion in damage each year.
   The experimental system so far has been used only in the San
Francisco Bay area.
   But it is meant to demonstrate the possibility of issuing such
warnings elsewhere in the nation so people in slide-prone hilly
areas can evacuate if necessary, U.S. Geological Survey geologist
Raymond Wilson said Thursday.
   Wilson likened landslides to ``a runaway freight train going
through a neighborhood.''
   ``It's a national problem,'' said David Keefer, leader of the
agency's landslide research group. ``Total U.S. landslide damages
are estimated at somewhere between $1 billion and $2 billion a
year,'' with 25 to 50 Americans killed annually.
   ``Landslide damages (in the United States) are larger on an
annual basis that earthquake damage or volcano damage,'' he added.
   They spoke at the Geological Survey's Geohazards '88 symposium,
which drew about 250 scientists and public officials. The two-day
symposium focuses on the hazards posed by earthquakes, landslides,
volcanoes and water pollution.
   The warning system was tested successfully on Feb. 14, 1986, when
a severe rainstorm prompted the Geological Survey and National
Weather Service to warn that mudslides were possible during a
six-hour period for much of the Bay area.
   Similar warnings were issued in Marin, Napa and Sonoma counties,
north of the Bay, for a 60-hour period beginning Feb. 17, 1986.
   Eight of 10 known landslides during that storm occurred during
the two warning periods, the scientists said, although they added it
wasn't possible to know if lives were saved by the alerts.
   The weather service transmitted the warnings to newspapers and
radio and TV stations in its regular forecasts, special weather
statements and flash flood warnings.
   The Bay area has been relatively dry since 1986 and no warnings
have been issued since then, he added.
   The agency depends on 60 Bay area rain gauges that automatically
relay measurements to the Geological Survey and the Weather Service,
and on reports from nearly 400 volunteers who have backyard rain
gauges.
   The Geological Survey developed the warning system after a storm
in 1982 dropped as much as 24 inches of rain in 34 hours, triggering
18,000 landslides in nine Bay-area counties, said geologist Earl
Brabb. In all the years before 1982, geologists had mapped 70,000
landslides in the same counties, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
