<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-BoYang     11-18 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Bo Yang,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Controversial Taiwanese Writer Meets Mainland Fans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A controversial Taiwanese author who has attacked
both the mainland communist government and the rival Nationalists on
Taiwan was mobbed by young fans during his first trip to the
mainland in 39 years.
   Bo Yang visited the northwestern city of Xian last week to
collect about $2,000 in royalties for three books and visit a
daughter he hasn't seen since fleeing to Taiwan in 1949, the
official China News Service said in a report seen in Beijing today.
   More than 300 young fans surrounded Bo and clamored for his
autograph when he went to a Xian bookstore to sign locally published
copies of his books, the report said.
   Bo was born Guo Yidong in Kaifeng, Henan province. He fled to
Taiwan when the communists took over the mainland in 1949 and was a
harsh critic of the communists in the 1950s. But in the 1960s he
attacked Taiwan's Nationalist government, which then jailed him for
nine years as a communist spy.
   Critics on Taiwan and the mainland criticized him for his 1984
book, ``The Ugly Chinaman,'' a critique of Chinese culture.
   Five editions were printed in the mainland in 1986 and sold
quickly among young intellectuals before the book was banned in 1987.
   Bo arrived on the mainland Oct. 20 and has visited Shanghai and
Beijing.
</TEXT>
