<1ST_LINE>u a BC-Theater 1stLd-Writethru a0815 11-18 0816</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0815,0828</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Rumors,' A New Play by Neil Simon, Opens on Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS four grafs of other reviews; No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You can't accuse Neil Simon of shortchanging the
audience on plot in his latest comedy, ``Rumors,'' which opened
Thursday at Broadway's Broadhurst Theater.
   There are gunshots, a car crash, several marital spats, group
therapy by telephone and enough household accidents to fill the
emergency room at Bellevue.
   With his autobiographical trilogy of ``Brighton Beach Memoirs,''
``Biloxi Blues'' and ``Broadway Bound'' complete, Simon has returned
to the more machine-gun style of comedy writing he perfected in
plays like ``The Odd Couple'' and ``The Sunshine Boys.''
   ``Rumors'' isn't in that class, but it does offer some slam-bang
humor, particularly in a delirious first act.
   The playwright calls ``Rumors'' a farce, and you'll know that as
soon as the curtain goes up on designer Tony Straiges' opulent
two-story suburban living room. There are seven doors, three
upstairs and four down, just waiting to be opened and slammed shut.
   We're at a 10th anniversary party for a couple named Charlie and
Myra. Everybody's done up in tuxedos and evening dresses, and the
food is in the kitchen waiting to be prepared. But where are the
hosts? Well, Charlie's upstairs in the bedroom after shooting
himself in the ear. Myra can't be found, although no one seems to
suspect foul play.
   The guests, who include Charlie's lawyer, tax accountant,
pyschoanalyst and a would-be state senator as well as their wives,
try to pretend that nothing is wrong. For much of Act 1, their
pretense is amusing, particularly when carried out by such masters
of desperation as Ron Leibman, the harried accountant done in by
whiplash from that auto accident, and Christine Baranski, the
lawyer's wife who can't quite get over her nicotine habit.
   Miss Baranski is a vision of comic neurosis. Dressed in a poufy
pink miniskirt (a witty design by Joseph G. Aulisi), she frantically
puffs her way through the play with a conviction that is supremely
funny.
   The weird thing is why these guests are so secretive about
Charlie's and Myra's difficulties and why they want to keep things
hush-hush, even from each other. Their deceptions cause all the
panic on stage, and yet they are not explained convincingly.
   Still, if you ignore the logic, you can savor director Gene Saks'
brilliant job of orchestrating the partygoers' maniacal behavior.
There are Joyce Van Patten's contortions as she drops to the floor
without warning. She explains that she has a bad back and never
knows when spasms might occur.
   Mark Nelson, Miss Baranski's cautious lawyer husband, spends much
of the play misinterpreting conversation. He was sitting too close
when one of those gunshots went off.
   Andre Gregory, his fingers bandaged after a particularly nasty
kitchen burn, has a tough time serving drinks with his singed
digits. Jessica Walter, nursing a bruised lip from the battered BMW,
tries to calm her hysterical husband, the volatile Mr. Liebman. And
Lisa Banes smolders sexily as the pent-up wife of the politician,
played with the right degree of pomposity by Ken Howard.
   Simon certainly keeps his story spinning well into the second
act. The problem is getting the plot to stop. He introduces a
policeman (Charles Brown) who wants this frantic crowd to explain
what has been going on. Liebman is chosen to tell what happened and
in a wild tour de force makes up a tale that the policeman agrees to
accept because he likes it.
   Liebman's concocted story doesn't end the play. It just sets up
an unconvincing ending. That's something that shouldn't happen in a
farce, surely one of the most difficult things to write. After all
that running around, the strands of the plot should be tied up
neatly. In ``Rumors,'' they are covered up by the final curtain. But
until that unsatisfactory conclusion, there is much to cheer _ and
laugh at _ in ``Rumors.''
   In other reviews:
   Frank Rich in The New York Times wrote: ``Maybe I've led a
charmed life, but I can't recall hearing this many toilet jokes
since the ninth grade. ... Mr. Simon may have been too long away
from his original calling; a lot of his gag machinery is rusty.''
   In the Daily News, Howard Kissel called the play ``scattershot''
and said it seemed as if it were written by a side of Simon that
``turns out comedies with no soul, where every other line is
intended to get a laugh, as if to meet some abstract quota.''
   But Clive Barnes in the New York Post said, ``Broadway has
something to cheer about again! ... Totally frivolous, this maze of
mendacity is light, frothy and fun. It is as significant as a cream
puff and just about as nourishing. But beautifully baked and
cunningly filled.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881118-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-88 1123EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-MideastMoves 2ndLd-Writethru a0471 11-18 0740</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mideast Moves, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0471,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: The PLO's Moves Get Tepid U.S. Reception</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs pvs grafs 8-9, Indeed, to update with Soviet recognition.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>An AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To Israel's great relief, the latest moves by
the Palestine Liberation Organization were given a tepid reception
by the Reagan and soon-to-be Bush administrations.
   The White House detected some ``positive elements'' in the latest
session of the PLO's quasi-legislature and the State Department
found some encouraging signs.
   But the Reagan administration did not pick up chairman Yasser
Arafat's invitation to use the policy statement adopted Tuesday in
Algiers by the Palestine National Council as a vehicle for seeking
concessions from Israel.
   And from inside the Bush camp came the judgment that the PLO had
taken ``a slight step forward'' in the right direction under
pressure from Palestinians on the West Bank and in Gaza.
   But, an anonymous Bush foreign policy aide told The New York
Times: ``They're still operating on the basis of the lowest common
denominator. To meet them and reward them would send the wrong
signal.''
   Bush, meanwhile, said ``the jury is still out'' and added
ambiguously: ``There may be reason to be less fully optimistic about
it.''
   Israel, in the throes of trying to form a new government, already
had dismissed the PLO moves as irrelevant. So the U.S. reaction must
have been a welcome relief.
   However, the Soviet Union, following in the path of some two
dozen Arab and Third World countries, recognized the PLO's
declaration of independence.
   That kept the heat on Israel at week's end, and it could be
turned up if the West Europeans decide the PLO has gone far enough
to warrant concessions from Israel.
   William B. Quandt, the National Security Council's Middle East
specialist under former President Jimmy Carter, says the PLO has
made a significant move, ``inadequate as it may be.''
   In an interview Thursday, the Brookings scholar said ``we ought
to make a statement that invites another move.''
   He has studied the texts in Arabic and compared them to the
Palestine National Council's statements last year. Quandt finds a
number of differences.
   In 1987, for instance, the Council reinvoked the PLO charter that
calls for dismantling Israel as a Jewish state. Not this time.
   The Council last year rejected U.N. Security Council resolution
242 as a basis for a peace conference. This time it was endorsed.
   Last time, all U.N. resolutions dealing with Israel, including
the one in 1947 that provided for a much smaller piece of Palestine,
were cited as a basis for negotiations. This time, Quandt said, the
resolutions were cited to support ``self-determination'' for the
Palestinians.
   ``They don't deal with recognition the way I would like,'' Quandt
said. For instance, the Council did not say if the Palestinians got
their own state they would be willing to live side-by-side with
Israel.
   ``What they haven't quite bit the bullet on is to say `We're
ready to negotiate with Israel on the basis of 242, instead of going
to a peace conference on that basis,'' the former U.S. official
said. ``That would remove some ambiguity.''
   In any event, the Council has not met the three-part U.S. test
for recognition, and Israelis of varying political stripes did not
revise their abhorrence of the PLO and terrorism.
   The Council's most significant move was to declare its readiness
to have peace talks held under U.N. Security Council resolution 242.
Adopted after the Arabs were routed by Israel in the 1967 Six-Day
war, it affirms the right of states in the region to live within
secure borders.
   Recognition of Israel is not specified in the resolution, only
implied.
   The two other parts of the U.S. test are that the PLO explicitly
recognize Israel and that it renounce terrorism. The Council did not
recognize the Jewish state and asserted force could be used by
guerrillas in Israel and on the West Bank and in Gaza.
   Whatever the PLO's motives, which could range from an
unwillingness to play all their cards before there is a peace
conference to unrelenting hostility to Israel, the failure to meet
the test keeps the United States from responding to Arafat's
challenge.
   ``We feel that the ball is now in the American court,'' he said
Tuesday in Algiers.
   Clearly, the Reagan and Bush administrations don't agree.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Barry Schweid has covered U.S. Middle East
diplomacy since 1973.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
