<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ProtestAccident     11-18 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Protest Accident,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Recommends Discipline For Crew Of Train That Maimed Protester</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy is recommending that the civilian
crewmen on the munitions train that maimed an antiwar demonstrator
last year receive 10-day suspensions.
   The union representative for the three crewmen, James Wright of
the American Federation of Government Employees, accused the Navy of
making the crew scapegoats for the incident at the Concord Naval
Weapons Station.
   S. Brian Willson lost his lower legs after sitting on the tracks
in front of a moving train at the base 40 miles east of San
Francisco. He was part of a group of demonstrators protesting
American involvement in Central America.
   The crewmen were cleared of any criminal wrongdoing but have been
on disability leave ever since, claiming they were traumatized by
the incident.
   They have 30 days to appeal the Navy's recommendation, which was
signed by Capt. Joseph Micelli of the Naval Sea Systems Command in
Washington. A Navy spokeswoman Thursday declined to comment on the
proposed suspension.
   Brakeman Bob Mayfield, who received his letter Wednesday, said he
and the other crew members would fight the suspensions.
   A lawyer for Willson, A.J. Kutchins, said the Navy's action
``certainly gives the lie to statements in the press that these men
were merely innocent victims of Brian Willson, who had the nerve to
get himself run over.''
   Willson is suing the crew and Navy officials; the crew has
countersued Willson and the same Navy officials.
</TEXT>
