<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Bush-Cabinet 2ndLd-Writethru a0545 11-18 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Cabinet, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0545,540</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts graf 7, I am very, with Voinovich quote.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush is whittling away
at the list of vacancies in his new administration, but there are
still so many top openings that the name-guessing game is the
hottest thing in town.
   Bush picked John Sununu, the retiring New Hampshire governor, as
his chief of staff on Wednesday, and chose Lee Atwater, his election
campaign manager, as chairman of the Republican National Committee.
   Word of the latest appointments leaked out before they were
officially announced, but many decisions on who's in and who's out
are tightly held by the inner circle of transition aides.
   Bush is known to dislike palace infighting, and some hopefuls are
keeping out of the public eye. Deborah Steelman, for example.
   ``She's lying low,'' a friend said of Steelman, 33, one of Bush's
key domestic campaign advisers. She's been talked about for a
high-ranking job somewhere, possibly at the Department of Housing
and Urban Development.
   Cleveland Mayor George Voinovich, who lost his bid to unseat
Democratic Sen. Howard Metzenbaum this month, has emerged as a
leading candidate to head HUD.
   ``I am very pleased with all the rumors flying around that I'm
being considered for something in Washington, but the fact of the
matter is that I have made no contact whatsoever,'' Voinovich said
earlier this week. But he said he would listen to any job offers
made to him by Bush.
   Donald Rumsfeld, a candidate for defense secretary, uttered what
has come to be a common refrain around town. ``I'm not in the habit
of accepting things that haven't been offered,'' he said. Even so,
he's interested in the post he held in the Ford administration.
   New York Rep. Jack Kemp, a loser to Bush in the GOP presidential
primaries, is being pushed by conservatives for a good job in the
administration.
   Business groups are touting the former football quarterback for
labor secretary to replace Ann Dore McLaughlin, or even HUD
secretary, replacing Samuel Pierce.
   Bush has ordered staffers to keep their mouths shut, though he's
indicated he is considering people for important posts in his
economic team and soon will turn to national security posts. Two
Cabinet jobs already have been filled: James A. Baker III as
secretary of state and Nicholas Brady as treasury secretary.
   The latest thinking is that former Texas Sen. John Tower's stock
is still high to take over the Defense Department. He has good
relations with Congress and he knows the subject matter: He used to
chair the Armed Services Committee, and he was a member of the U.S.
delegation to superpower arms talks in Geneva.
   Other possible Pentagon chiefs are Paul H. O'Neill, chairman of
the Aluminum Co. of America, and retired Air Force Lt. Gen. Brent
Scowcroft, onetime head of the National Security Council.
   Some new names surfaced Thursday for transportation secretary,
but they're viewed as longshots. They include John Riley, head of
the Federal Railroad Administration, and Allan McArtor, head of the
Federal Aviation Administration.
   Still seen as contenders are Jim Burnett, a member and former
chairman of the National Transportation Safety Board, New Jersey
Gov. Thomas Kean and Rep. Guy Molinari, R-N.Y., who ran Bush's
campaign in New York.
   Craig Fuller, co-director of the Bush transition office, had been
talked about for the transportation job, but he announced on
Wednesday that he will leave government after failing to win the
White House chief of staff post.
</TEXT>
