<2ND_LINE>PM-Wedtech-Biaggi, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0572,0559</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Biaggi Sentenced to Eight Years for Wedtech Conviction</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to raise quote, PICKS UP 4th graf pvs,
`Biaggi, 71 ...'; SUBS 11th graf pvs, ``I'm still ...' to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today sentenced former U.S. Rep.
Mario Biaggi to eight years in prison for racketeering in the
Wedtech scandal.
   In a tearful plea to U.S. District Judge Constance Baker Motley,
the former 10-term congressman maintained his innocence and pleaded
for leniency for his co-defendant and eldest son, Richard.
   ``I appeal to you as a father,'' a sobbing Biaggi said. ``Do what
you want with me. My time is done. Don't hurt Richard.'' The younger
Biaggi was to be sentenced later in the day.
   Biaggi, 71, sat slumped in his chair but showed no emotion while
Motley sentenced him.
   He was convicted Aug. 5 of turning Wedtech Corp., a now-defunct
South Bronx defense contractor, into a racketeering enterprise that
paid out millions of dollars in bribes to public officials for help
in winning no-bid contracts.
   The Bronx Democrat, who resigned from office a day after his
conviction, already has been sentenced to 2{ years in prison for
obstruction and taking an illegal gratuity in an unrelated case but
remained free on appeal.
   The judge said today's sentence would run concurrently with the
prvious one. Biaggi was ordered to report to authorities on Jan. 8.
   Biaggi was the first of five defendants in the Wedtech trial to
be sentenced today. He faced a maximum sentence of 146 years in
prison and $7 million in fines.
   In a final plea, the white-haired Biaggi _ dressed in a navy-blue
pinstriped suit and leaning heavily on the cane he has used since he
was wounded in his days as a New York City police officer _ said the
five-month trial and the month of ``devastating publicity'' before
his indictment were punishment enough.
   ``There wasn't a day I didn't suffer,'' Biaggi said. ``I died a
little bit every day. I started to die some time ago.''
   ``I'm still of the belief, I always have been, that I am
innocent,'' he said. He added, ``The worst possible punishment your
honor could administer would be to put my son in prison.''
   The judge received some 170 letters, including 37 from Republican
and Democratic congressmen, urging leniency and recounting Biaggi's
many contributions over the years.
   Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., chairman of the Ways and Means
Committee, wrote that Biaggi's resignation was ``a powerful
punishment in and of itself.'' Biaggi had averted impeachment and
removal by his colleagues.
   Biaggi, a former hero police officer in New York City, was
convicted of extorting cash and stock, once worth more than $3
million, from Wedtech in exchange for his political clout. He also
was convicted of filing false financial disclosure statements and
tax returns to cover up his illegal profits.
   At least 19 people have been convicted of crimes ranging from
racketeering to illegal lobbying in the Wedtech scandal. They
include a former top White House aide, two former Maryland state
senators and two Teamsters officers.
   Biaggi was convicted in 1987 on charges of taking an illegal
gratuity to use his clout on behalf of a shipyard.
</TEXT>
