<1ST_LINE>r a AM-IRSSpeech     11-18 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-IRS Speech,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Professor Claims IRS Canceled Speech On Congressional Contributions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A law professor says his speech at an Internal
Revenue Service conference was canceled because he refused to cut
references to campaign contributions accepted by members of
congressional tax reform committees.
   The IRS, however, says that wasn't the reason Richard Doernberg's
invitation to deliver the speech was rescinded.
   Doernberg, an expert on tax reform at Emory University, said he
was to give the speech at the agency's sixth annual research
conference, held in Washington on Thursday and Friday.
   He said he planned to discuss his research showing that members
of the tax reform committees get 31 percent more campaign money than
other congressmen from companies and political action committees
lobbying for tax breaks.
   Doernberg said he refused to alter his speech, and on Nov. 4 he
was notified by Roger L. Plate, head of the IRS's research division,
that his invitation was being rescinded.
   Plate was attending the conference and could not be reached for
comment, but IRS spokesman Wilson Fadely said Thursday that
Doernberg's speech was canceled because it contained no new
information.
   ``We were looking for people that were coming up in research with
new approaches,'' he said. ``That was the type of forum it was.''
   Doernberg said he doesn't believe that.
   ``They had my articles when they called me up to invite me,'' he
said. ``They knew what I was going to say.''
</TEXT>
