<1ST_LINE>u a PM-AbortionProtest     11-18 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Abortion Protest,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than 100 Arrested In Anti-Abortion Protest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED STYCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today arrested more than than 100
anti-abortion demonstrators blocking the doors to a Planned
Parenthood clinic.
   Some protesters were carried and a few dragged by police to buses
and police vans.
   Deputy Chief John Sturner said those arrested would be charged
with trespassing, and most would be issued citations to return to
court at a later date.
   The protesters began standing in front of the doors around 8
a.m., an hour before the clinic was scheduled to open.
   Thomas Webber, executive director of Planned Parenthood of
Minnesota, said he asked police to remove the protesters so
employees and people with appointments could enter. ``It's a
violation of law,'' Webber said. ``It's unconscionable.''
   The arrests ended around 11 a.m. and the clinic opened a
half-hour later, although about 30 protesters continued to march on
the sidewalk.
   Brian Gibson, associate director of Pro-Life Action Ministries of
St. Paul, said the protest was inspired by Operation Rescue, an
anti-abortion group that showed up in force in Atlanta during the
Democratic National Convention in July.
   ``This is a big day for abortions at Planned Parenthood and it's
our intention to stop the killing of babies,'' Gibson said.
   No abortions had been scheduled during the morning at the clinic;
people appointments later in the day were referred to other clinics,
Webber said. ``They (protesters) really haven't accomplished
anything,'' he said.
   About 1,300 people were arrested in several demonstrations in
Atlanta by Operation rescue. Hundreds more have been arrested in
other demonstrations orchestrated around the country by the
organization.
</TEXT>
