<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChildAttacked     11-18 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Child Attacked,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Sold 10-Year-Old's Sexual Favors, Police Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman earned money to buy crack by
holding down a 10-year-old girl while a school bus driver sexually
assaulted her, police said.
   Dorothea Tate, a 35-year-old mother of six, was jailed Wednesday
along the driver, Eugene Howard, 48, on $50,000 bail each, police
said.
   ``Tate was profiting from the 10-year-old,'' said Lt. Frank
Lagan. ``She was the pimp.''
   Lagan declined to describe Tate's relationship to the girl,
except to say they knew each other previously. He also refused to
say when or where the crimes took place and how much Howard
allegedly paid Tate.
   Tate was charged with sexual assault, promoting prostitution and
risking injury to a minor. Howard, who was previously convicted of
indecent exposure, was charged with sexual assault and risking
injury to a minor.
   Howard's criminal record came as a shock to some parents and
school officials.
   ``If he has a previous incident with police he shouldn't be
involved with children,'' said Lynn Holdt, president of the parents
group at an elementary school in Darien whose students were driven
by Howard. ``I know it's difficult to hire bus drivers but that's no
excuse.''
   Darien Superintendent of Schools James Loughran said the school
system was reviewing the incident with Laidlaw Transit Co., Howard's
employer.
</TEXT>
