<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     11-18 0749</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0744</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY44,CS1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jerry Lee Lewis, Ray Charles and five other legends
of American rock and soul music fired up Romans with an
internationally televised concert to raise funds to vaccinate
African children.
   Lewis pounded the piano keys with his heels as he did in the
'50s, and Charles interrupted a world tour to play two ballads
before a rapt audience of 10,000 Thursday at Rome's sports palace.
   Little Richard pranced atop a grand piano while crooning a medley
of his hits.
   James Brown bounced around a stage of steel girders and
construction gear, singing ``I Feel Good.'' Fats Domino, wearing a
shocking pink jacket, revived ``The Fat Man'' and ``Blueberry Hill.''
   Bo Diddley and B.B. King, a last-minute replacement for Chuck
Berry, also were part of the show, which will be broadcast early
next year on Home Box Office.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former heavyweight boxing champion
Muhammad Ali arrived Friday for a tour of refugee camps housing
southern Sudanese displaced by war and famine.
   Ali, an American Moslem, is to meet on Saturday with Prime
Minister Sadek el-Mahdi. He leaves Tuesday for Uganda's capital,
Kampala, where international relief organizations have mounted an
airlift to starving people in the south.
   Relief officials say 1.3 million people have fled civil war in
the area this year. More than a quarter of a million people are said
to have starved in the last five years on the way to neighboring
Ethiopia or to northern Sudan.
   Culture and information minister, Aballa Mohamed Ahmed, met Ali
at the airport along with Abdul-Rahman Swareddahab, board chairman
of the Islamic Dawa Organization, a religious advocacy group.
Swareddahab headed the junta that overthrew President Gaafar Nimeiri
in 1985.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   These are hard times for Jimmy Swaggart.
   The beleaguered evangelist, whose encounters with a New Orleans
prostitute led to his ouster from the Assemblies of God, now is
parting with his Grumman Gulfstream II jet.
   Jimmy Swaggart Ministries is selling its jet to a Texas company,
according to records filed with the Federal Aviation Administration.
   According to FAA records, Tyler Jet Aircraft Sales of Tyler,
Texas, is buying the jet. Although no selling price was disclosed, a
similar plane was on the market recently for $5.25 million.
   The sale comes when Swaggart's ministry and Bible college are
struggling. On Sept. 29, Swaggart put a halt to nearly $13 million
in construction projects at the ministry's Baton Rouge complex.
Nearly three-fourths of the students enrolled at the Jimmy Swaggart
Bible College did not return.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donna Rice, the Miami model whose association
with Gary Hart ended his 1988 presidential campaign, found more
cameras than she had bargained for when she showed up for a meeting
with a group of journalists.
   Ms. Rice said in a handwritten statement moments before her
scheduled appearance that she had expected her meeting with the
Society of Professional Journalists, Sigma Delta Chi to be private
and off-the-record.
   ``As you are probably aware, for the past year and a half, I have
purposely avoided capitalizing on my notoriety, and except for three
specific interviews, I have declined all media offers,'' she said in
the statement.
   Ms. Rice said she thought the meeting could offer an opportunity
to candidly share her experiences.
   ``But when I arrived a few minutes ago and I saw the cameras,
lights and tape recorders, I realized this wasn't the forum I
anticipated,'' she said.
   James Plante, national president of SPJ,SDX, said he believed
that Ms. Rice knew her appearance at the Albert B. Sabin Cincinnati
Convention Center would be on the record.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Wyeth beamed at the opening of an
exhibition of his paintings in Manhattan when a great American
artist unexpectedly turned up to admire his works: his father,
Andrew.
   ``When he came, Jamie said, `Oh, my God, my father's here. How
wonderful,''' said Warren Adelson, the director of Coe Kerr Gallery.
``It was a surprise. He didn't know. I guess Andrew didn't want to
outshine him.''
   Several hundred people attended the opening Thursday night on the
Upper East Side.
   An exhibition of 115 works by James, his father, and his late
grandfather, N.C. Wyeth, opens Sunday in Brandywine River Museum in
Chadds Ford, Pa., where both James and Andrew Wyeth live. It is the
final stop of a 1{-year tour that also included stops in the Soviet
Union, Italy, Japan and England.
</TEXT>
