<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-88 1447EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Canada-Turner Bjt   11-18 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Turner, Bjt,0607</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`L-Word' Leader Goes On Attack; Reinvigorates Election Campaign</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whatever the outcome of Monday's election, it will
be remembered for the remarkable resurgence of Liberal Party leader
John Turner and his relentless attack on the free trade agreement
with the United States.
   Turner, lambasted for increased deficits when he was finance
minister and hiring goofs during a 79-day stint as prime minister,
has struck campaign pay dirt with an attack that portrays Canada as
a U.S. colony if the trade deal passes.
   His forceful charge to Prime Minister Brian Mulroney during a
televised debate _ ``You sold us out!'' _ invigorated a flagging
Liberal campaign and set the tone for its final days.
   Turner's nightmare vision of a weakened Canada has catapulted the
Liberals into a dead heat with Mulroney's Progressive Conservative
Party, according to polls.
   On Thursday, Turner told voters the deal would let United States
overwhelm Canada and turn it into a ``branch plant.''
   Only a Conservative majority government now will ensure that the
trade agreement starts Jan. 1 as scheduled. The agreement is to
phase out all remaining tariffs between the two countries over a
10-year period.
   The socialist New Democratic Party, expected to finish third
Monday, also opposes the trade agreement Mulroney signed with
President Reagan in January.
   The 1988 campaign already stands in sharp contrast to 1984, when
the Conservatives devastated the opposition to win 211 of the House
of Commons' 282 seats. The Liberals _ with Turner at the helm _ fell
from the 147 seats they won in 1980 to 40.
   In 1984, Turner inherited the Liberal Party leadership from
Pierre Trudeau and served as prime minister through the election. It
was the second-shortest term as prime minister ever in Canada.
   He was depicted as a fumbler for handing out patronage
appointments at the wrong time. A book about Turner _ ``Reign of
Error'' by Ottawa journalist Greg Weston _ has been a best seller
throughout the campaign.
   But Turner survived three internal challenges since the 1984
election to stay on at the top of the Liberal Party.
   Turner, 59, was born in England but came to Canada as a child.
His parents were an English journalist and a Canadian miner's
daughter.
   He first ran for Parliament in 1962 and in 1972 was promoted by
Trudeau to finance minister.
   His Conservative opponents delight in calling him the father of
the Canadian deficit, for in three years as finance minister,
government spending soared 80 percent and the deficit quintupled to
$5.4 billion.
   ``How are you going to pay for it?'' hecklers shout to his
campaign promises.
   The weekly Maclean's reported that the Liberal decision to focus
on free trade was made in early October when Mulroney seemed headed
for an easy victory.
   In campaign stops now, Turner refers to the pact as ``the issue
of the century for our country.''
   ``This election is a referendum on Canada's future,'' he says.
   The Liberal leader argues that the free trade agreement can
affect Canada's extensive social and health care programs.
   He insists his message is not anti-American and that relations
with the United States won't be disrupted if Canadians decide
against proceeding with the trade agreement.
   ``I am saying that the Americans are realists; they are
pragmatists,'' he was quoted as saying. ``They are not only our
largest customer, we are their largest customer.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
