<2ND_LINE>AM-Democrats, Bjt,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Say They Won't Knuckle Under to GOP's `Pit Bull' Politics</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Note EMBARGOED material, grafs 14-18</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Party officials, trying to avoid a
leadership fight of their own, Friday denounced President-elect
George Bush's choice for Republican Party chairman as a practitioner
of ``a pit bull style of politics.''
   ``If Lee Atwater is going to be the next Republican chairman, I
think we know what the next election cycle is going to look like,''
said Texas Democratic Party chairman Robert Slagle.
   Atwater managed the Bush presidential campaign against Democrat
Michael Dukakis. Many Democrats blame him for the negative tone of
the Republican campaign.
   ``We are ready to take on Lee Atwater and those who would create
a pit bull style of politics,'' said Rick Wiener, the Michigan
Democratic Party chairman.
   The choice of Atwater gave the Democrats a chance to lash out at
a Republican instead of each other as they met for the first time
after their fifth defeat in the last six presidential elections.
   The occasion was a meeting of the Association of State Democratic
Chairs, and the principal order of business was not on the agenda _
it was to convince Paul G. Kirk Jr. to serve a second four-year term
as national party chairman.
   ``Keep Kirk,'' read big red and white buttons worn by many state
party officials.
   The chairman, sounding reluctant to stay on for another term, has
said he would listen to appeals from party officials before making
his final decision.
   At least five party activists, including three former
congressmen, intend to run for the job if Kirk decides not to stay.
   One of them, former Rep. James Stanton of Ohio, wore a ``Keep
Kirk'' button and told reporters, ``If he's a candidate, I support
him. If he's not, I'm a candidate.''
   Stanton was the least well-known contender in a field that
included Wiener, former party official Ron Brown, and former Reps.
Michael Barnes of Maryland and Jim Jones of Oklahoma.
   Brown was convention manager for Jesse Jackson, and much of the
opposition to him appeared based on his tie to the longtime civil
rights leader.
   FOLLOWING MATERIAL EMBARGOED FOR 3:45 P.M. EST
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Kirk warned the Democrats not to ``rush to pick up sides and
divide among ourselves _ region against region, left against right,
constituency against constituency.''
   Despite Bush's 40-state victory in the presidential election,
Kirk said, ``There is no Republican majority in America's city halls
or its legislative bodies. There is no Republican majority of
governors.
   ``There is no Republican House. There is no Republican Senate.
There is no Republican realignment. And there is no Republican
mandate.''
   He urged his party to ``take prudent stock of the factors that
might have improved our chances in this election. We should not
oversimplify, but we must not overreact. ...
   ``Should we fall into the trap of thinking we must change
everything we've done in order to win the next presidential
election? I say no.''
   END EMBARGOED MATERIAL
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The choice of Atwater was the main topic of conversation at a
breakfast meeting of Southern party chairs.
   ``I don't intend to get out-muscled,'' said Slagle. ``I don't
intend to let them play that kind of game with us and win it. If we
have to sink to their level to protect democracy and to break them
of sucking eggs then I'm perfectly willing to do it.''
   Slagle said he would urge Democrats to undertake thorough checks
of the backgrounds of Republican candidates in order to retaliate
against GOP attacks on Democrats.
</TEXT>
