<2ND_LINE>PM-Switzerland-Blast, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0597,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Explodes Outside Aeroflot Office, Two Americans Among Injured</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 1 graf for 8th graf pvs, ``Less than...'' to CORRECT name
of group claiming responsibility. Pickup 9th graf pvs, ``The
doorman...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded today outside a building housing
the Geneva office of the Soviet airline Aeroflot, and officials said
five people were injured, including two American women.
   Four of the people, including one of the Americans, were
seriously injured in what one witness described as a bloodbath on
the crowded downtown street.
   Geneva police spokesman Marcel Vaudroz said that aside from the
59-year-old and 22-year-old American tourists, the victims were a
34-year-old Italian man, a 60-year-old French woman and a
21-year-old French man.
   He declined to provide their names.
   He said the younger U.S. woman was released from the hospital
after treatment for shock.
   The injured were passers-by, an Aeroflot employee said.
   Police said the bomb, hidden in a trash can, went off at 4:30
p.m. in front of the building which also houses two Arab banks, a
French bank and a jewelry store.
   Less than three hours after the blast, an anonymous caller to
French-language Swiss television in Geneva claimed the attack in the
name of a Socialist Nationalist Front, the television station
reported on its nightly news broadcast. It quoted the caller as
saying the movement opposed communist, capitalist and Jewish
interests.
   The doorman of a luxury hotel on the same block said, ``First I
heard a loud explosion, like a cannon shot.''
   The large front window of the Aeroflot office shattered and
people screamed, witnesses said. Police arrived 30 seconds after the
blast.
   ``On the sidewalk in front of the office there was a bloodbath,''
said the hotel doorman, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   At least one traffic light was damaged by the explosion, and
police blocked off two lanes of the four-lane avenue, further
snarling rush-hour traffic.
   Geneva hospital spokesman Louis Ody said five victims were
admitted to the hospital, four of them in serious condition with leg
wounds and burns.
   The bombing was under investigation, officials said.
</TEXT>
