<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CollegeBats     11-18 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-College Bats,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Begin Rabies Shots After Evicted Bat Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was funny for a while _ muscle-bound
athletes at the University of Central Florida gym frightened by
dive-bombing bats that everybody said were harmless.
   But when one of the bats died, tests showed it had rabies.
   Thirteen people have begun a series of rabies shots because of
their handling or otherwise coming into contact with the
sparrow-like, 1-ounce bats or their droppings. The series of five
shots is administered over 28 days.
   Several workers said Thursday that the gym is still infested with
bats.
   University and Orange County health officials are looking for
anyone else who came in contact with the hundreds of creatures that
fluttered in and out of the gym building for weeks after being
displaced in late October from their nests in its ceiling.
   Officials stressed that chances are remote of contracting rabies,
an infectious disease of the central nervous system characterized by
choking, convulsions and inability to swallow liquids.
   ``Just the same, we don't take chances with rabies,'' said Howard
Schwadron, environmental health director for the county health
department.
   The bat that died had been injured and was being cared for by an
unidentified student.
   ``We haven't had these bats attacking people and biting them or
scratching them,'' said Dr. John Langdon, UCF Health Center
director. ``These bats aren't aggressive at all. It's people's own
recklessness.''
   Because bats lick their skin much the way cats do, their fur can
get wet with rabies-infected saliva, and that's why county officials
advised the student and maintenance workers who had handled the
injured creature to get the shots.
</TEXT>
