<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Oman     11-18 0663</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oman,0683</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sultan Marks Renaissance of Nation</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MUSCAT, Oman (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sultan Qaboos Bin Said, ruler of this once
hermit-like Arab state, on Friday marked the 18th anniversary of the
``renaissance'' that began when he ousted his despotic father and
thrust Oman into the 20th century.
   Since Qaboos deposed his father, Sultan Said Bin Taimur, in a
bloodless palace coup July 23, 1970, this Kansas-sized nation on the
rim of the Persian Gulf has been transformed from one of the world's
most backward countries into a burgeoning modern state.
   Sultan Said, a traditionalist who had ruled since 1932, kept Oman
in the Dark Ages. Despite the discovery of oil in 1964, he banned
schools, radios, music, dancing, spectacles and even trousers and
books in an attempt to keep the 20th century at bay.
   Said also virtually banned foreigners, allowing in only those
whose visas he personally authorized.
   There were only a few miles of paved road and 15 telephones in
the country. The gates of the old walled city of Muscat, little
changed since the 15th century, were locked at night and strangers
risked being shot on sight.
   Now, with help from Oman's modest oil revenues, Qaboos has built
a thriving nation with nearly 2,000 miles of highways, nearly 700
schools and other educational centers, 130 hospitals and clinics and
a development plan aimed at building a diversified ecis is a test. This
is only a test.
</TEXT>
