<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Baker-State     11-18 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baker-State,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Shultz Meets With Baker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz met Friday
with James A. Baker III, his designated successor, on transition
issues at the State Department as well as preparations for the visit
to New York next month of Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Shultz and Baker had talked over the telephone and at various
functions in the last few days, but this was their first
``substantive discussion'' of foreign policy, said a U.S. official
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Shultz and Baker had lunch in the James Monroe Room, the
secretary of state's private dining room. They made no statements to
reporters.
   Before the meeting, Shultz spoke to a group of Soviet and
American mayors, telling them that progress in U.S.-Soviet relations
had produced ``a different atmosphere around the world.''
   He said that ``there are still many problems between us, and
there are others we have resolved.'' Shultz took no questions from
his audience.
   Shultz welcomed President-elect George Bush's selection of Baker
last week and said of his prospective successor: ``He will hit the
ground running.''
   Baker has a broad background in international economics and close
personal ties to Bush.
   Among the issues that will carry over to the new administration
are arms control negotiations with the Soviet Union, the
Arab-Israeli dispute, the suspended Soviet troop withdrawal from
Afghanistan and negotiations to establish Namibia as an independent
state in Africa while removing Cuban troops from Angola.
   President Reagan and Bush plan to meet Dec. 7 with Gorbachev over
lunch at the Metropolitan Museum of Art during the Soviet leader's
trip to the United Nations. Shultz will fly to Brussels afterward to
brief the foreign ministers of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization.
</TEXT>
