<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-88 1713EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DrunkenDrivingFlap     11-18 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drunken Driving Flap,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NAB Says Federal Drunk Driving Panel Stacked Against Beer, Wine Ads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Association of Broadcasters on
Friday charged that a drunken driving workshop coordinated by the
surgeon general's office has a built-in bias against beer and wine
advertising.
   The NAB, in a letter to Surgeon General C. Everett Koop, said
many members of the workshop panels are strong opponents of beer and
wine ads.
   The panels ``are stacked against those groups most affected by
any recommendations,'' NAB said.
   The workshop, billed as part of the Health and Human Services
Department's initiative against alcohol-related problems, is
scheduled to take place Dec. 14-16 in Washington. It is sponsored by
the departments of Health and Human Services, Defense, Education,
Justice and Transportation.
   HHS said the purpose of the workshop was ``to develop a
comprehensive plan to bring drunk driving under control and to
eliminate it as the leading cause of death among young Americans.''
   The NAB, which opposes a prohibition on beer and wine
advertising, said it was invited to participate in a panel on
``advertising and marketing.'' But NAB President Edward O. Fritts
told Koop the group would not participate ``unless your plans are
significantly reshaped to include all legitimate points of view.''
   Jim Brown, a spokesman for Koop, said the office was preparing a
formal response to NAB's complaints, but he said, ``in setting up
the workshop, we tried to involve people from all areas in the
problem of drunk driving, including advertising agencies and sports
complexes.'' He declined, however, to list the participants of the
advertising panel.
   NAB said, however, that most of the 10 people it was told would
be on the advertising panel oppose or have indicated concern about
beer and wine advertising. Missing from their list of panel
participants are major league sports, sporting arenas, the alcohol
beverage industry, advertising agencies, individual broadcast
stations and the broadcast networks, NAB said.
   NAB also said workshop organizers rejected panelists from groups
that support radio and TV anti-drunk driving public service
campaigns and oppose the outright ban of responsible beer and wine
advertising.
   Besides advertising and marketing, a draft of the workshop plan
includes panels on data collection, education, legal issues,
enforcement, alcohol-service policies, injury control, youth,
treatment and citizen advocacy.
   In his letter, Fritts said that as presently constructed, the
workshop would not contribute to the discussion on drunken driving.
   ``At best, this workshop is designed to politicize the emotional
tragedy of drunk driving. At worst, it is a total abuse of the
policy-setting process,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881118-0107 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-88 1725EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AngolaTalks     11-18 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola Talks,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angola Ratifies Provisional Geneva Accord</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Angolan government on Friday formally
approved a provisional framework for an eventual pullout of Cuban
troops from Angola and independence for South-West Africa, the
Angolan news agency ANGOP said.
   In a report released in Lisbon, the official news agency said the
government ``approved the results of four-party talks in Geneva,
along with a calendar for the complete, gradual withdrawal of Cuba's
internationalist troops.''
   Cuba has about 50,000 troops in Angola.
   Negotiators from Angola, Cuba and South Africa, under U.S.
mediation, agreed Tuesday in Geneva to submit a timetable to their
respective governments for the redeployment of Cuban troops to the
north of Angola and their ultimate pullout, which could lead to
peace in southern Africa.
   All sides agreed to hold a final round of talks in the Congo
capital of Brazzaville at an unspecified date once the provisional
plan is ratified by the governments, the negotiators said.
   Earlier Friday, the Portuguese news agency Lusa said the Cuban
government in Havana also ratified the proposed timetable.
   During the peace talks, which have been held intermittently since
May, South Africa made agreement on a Cuban withdrawal a
precondition for implementing independence plans for South-West
Africa, or Namibia, a territory Pretoria has ruled for 73 years.
   Namibia, which lies between Angola and South Africa, long served
as a base for South African army raids into southern Angola to help
support rebels of the National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola, also known as UNITA.
   UNITA guerrillas have been fighting to force the Marxist-oriented
government in Luanda to share power since shortly after Angola
gained independence from Portugal in 1975.
   Cuban troops arrived in Angola at that time to back government
forces fighting UNITA.
   South Africa withdrew all its troops from Angola to Namibia in
August, as part of a cease-fire agreed on in an earlier round of
talks.
   UNITA, not a party to the talks, does not recognize the
cease-fire and reports of clashes between government and rebel
forces continue to reach Lisbon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
