<2ND_LINE>AM-Guyana-American,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Cult Leader Seeks Pardon in Guyana</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERT WILKINSON</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American fugitive David Hill, the black
power cult leader serving a 20-year prison term for manslaughter,
has asked President Desmond Hoyte for a pardon because of poor
health.
   Hill, who calls himself Rabbi Edward Washington, was admitted to
Georgetown Hospital on Oct. 15 after suffering a stroke that has
left him paralyzed on his right side. He also suffers from diabetes
and high blood pressure and had a mild heart attack in April.
   His House of Israel followers say his condition is worsening and
he is seeking a pardon for his 1986 manslaughter conviction on
humanitarian grounds.
   ``Members of the House of Israel seek the support of all
forgiving men and women and Guyanese of good will to join in an
appeal on humanitarian grounds to President Desmond Hoyte for him to
grant Mr. Washington a pardon,'' said a statement issued Thursday.
   There was no immediate government reaction.
   Hill fled to this English-speaking country on the northern coast
of South America in 1971 after jumping bail in Cleveland on nine
extortion charges.
   Hill set up a commune in Guyana's sparsely populated interior
near Jonestown, where the Rev. Jim Jones and 912 of his Peoples
Temple followers died in a suicide-massacre on Nov. 18, 1978.
   He established close ties with the leftist government of the late
President Forbes Burnham and incurred the wrath of opposition
parties, which accused the cult of breaking up strikes and political
meetings.
   After Burnham's death in 1985, new President Desmond Hoyte
ordered an investigation of the cult, leading to the jailing of Hill
and two others for ordering the killing of a cult member.
   The House of Israel teaches that Jesus Christ was black and
blacks are the true Hebrews. It has no connection with Judaism or
the state of Israel.
</TEXT>
