<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon     11-18 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Peacekeeping Convoy Fired on by Israelis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TYRE, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli armored personnel carrier on
Friday fired on a French military convoy belonging to the U.N.
peacekeeping force in southern Lebanon, a U.N. officer said.
   An Israeli military spokesman said the army had no reports of
incidents in the area. ``Everything is quiet,'' the spokesman said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   A security source in south Lebanon said there was firing in the
area but it was unclear if it was directed at the convoy.
   The U.N. officer, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said there
were no casualties among the 18 French soldiers in the convoy's
three vehicles.
   He said the incident occurred at 6:30 p.m. as the convoy _ a tank
and two jeeps _ was crossing through the western entry point to
Israel's self-declared security zone north of the Israeli-Lebanese
border.
   The officer said the convoy was returning from the southern port
of Tyre to the border town of Naqoura, headquarters of the U.N.
Interim Force in Lebanon, or UNIFIL.
   More than 150 UNIFIL soldiers have been killed and 250 wounded
since the 5,800-strong force was deployed in south Lebanon in 1978.
   Israel held onto the 6-to-10-mile deep security zone when it
withdrew most of its forces from Lebanon in June 1985 after a
three-year occupation.
   Israel contends that the enclave, which overlaps with UNIFIL's
operating area in south Lebanon, serves as a buffer against
cross-border guerrilla attacks into northern Israel.
   In another development in southern Lebanon on Friday, Palestinian
guerrillas attacked an Israeli army post with rockets and automatic
fire, and a security source said one guerrilla was wounded.
   The source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said a ``fierce
battle'' started at midday between the attackers and Israeli
soldiers manning the outpost in the hamlet of Kfarshouba near the
western slopes of Mt. Hermon.
   The source said that at least three guerrillas took part in the
attack. It was not immediately known to which faction they belonged.
   ``Around 50 Israeli soldiers are searching the area for the
attackers,'' the source said. He gave no further details.
</TEXT>
