<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Currency     11-18 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Currency,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaragua Fights Inflation With Larger Bills, Coins</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rampant inflation fueled by war and
natural disaster forced Nicaragua to issue banknotes and coins of
higher value Friday, the government said.
   Unofficial estimates put the annual inflation rate at 10,000
percent. There is no official rate.
   ``The fiscal deficit, produced by the war and aggravated by
Hurricane Joan and accelerated devaluations, have influenced the
issue of money,'' Barricada, the official newspaper of the ruling
Sandinista party, said Thursday.
   The new 5,000-cordoba note issued Friday, worth $2.50, is five
times as large as the biggest bill that was in circulaton. Barricada
also said a new, 500-cordoba coin, worth about 25 cents, was being
issued.
   When it was first issued in February as part of a massive
devaluation, the 1,000-cordoba note was worth $100. Today it is
worth 50 cents.
   The leftist Sandinistas inherited a bankrupt nation when they
took power in a 1979 revolution. Dictator Anastasio Somoza took most
of the money in the treasury with him when he was ousted.
   The economy has been further battered by seven years of war with
the U.S.- backed Contra rebels. President Daniel Ortega says the war
has cost Nicaragua $12 billion in direct and indirect costs, such as
lost production and export earnings.
   Hurricane Joan dealt Nicaragua another blow when it swept ashore
Oct. 22, destroying homes, crops, ranches, bridges and roads and
leaving tens of thousands homeless. Ortega has said the storm caused
$828 million in damage.
   The political opposition claims many of the economic problems
stem from Sandinista corruption and mismanagemant.
   The government issued a series of new bills last year that went
up to 50,000 cordobas, which at the time was worth about $2.
   The currency was discontinued in February and the cordoba was
devalued to a rate of 10 to the dollar.
   The official rate for the cordoba on Thursday was 2,000 to the
dollar. The rate used for imports was 500 to the dollar.
</TEXT>
