<1ST_LINE>u s AM-CAR--AtlantaJournal500 Bjt   11-18 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CAR--Atlanta Journal 500, Bjt,0504</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE HARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Motorsports Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAMPTON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rusty Wallace, still hoping to overtake Bill
Elliott in the battle for the Winston Cup title, buried the Atlanta
International Raceway qualifying record Friday as he took the pole
for the season-ending Atlanta Journal 500.
   Wallace drove his Pontiac Grand Prix to a fast lap of 179.499
mph, well above the previous track mark of 176.623 set in March by
Geoff Bodine in qualifying for the Motorcraft 500.
   That sizzling lap on the newly-paved 1.522-mile, high-banked oval
also was more than 2 mph faster than the 177.125 mph turned in by
Wallace's closest pursuer and close friend Dale Earnhardt in a
Chevrolet Monte Carlo.
   ``I should have gone a little faster in turns one and two,'' said
Earnhardt, the two-time defending Winston Cup champion. ``But we're
ready. Right now, the car is good enough to race.''
   Seven driver bettered the old record on Friday in nearly perfect
weather conditions _ sunny, cool and nearly windless.
   Brett Bodine, Geoff's younger brother, was third at 177.177,
followed by Mike Alexander at 177.125, Ricky Rudd at 177.068, Geoff
Bodine at 176.880 and Ken Schrader at 176.794.
   Fifty-one cars made one-lap qualifying efforts on Friday, with
the top 20 locking in starting spots for Sunday's 500-mile race. The
rest of the 40-car field will be filled in another session of time
trials on Saturday.
   One of the drivers still trying to earn a starting position is
Elliott, who was a disappointing 22nd on Friday at 174.452.
   The Dawsonville, Ga., driver is the defending champion in this
race and had started no worse than 10th here in 16 races dating back
to November, 1980.
   Elliott, who will clinch his first Winston Cup championship
Sunday if he finishes 19th or better, no matter what Wallace does,
said his poor qualifying effort on what he considers his home track
surprised him.
   ``I don't know what happened, but I was only a second off Rusty's
time,'' Elliott said. ``It could have been worse.
   ``Starting in the middle of the pack can be tough because you
never know what's going to happen back there,'' he added. ``But you
can have a flat tire at the start of the race and wind up back
there, too. That's just something you have to deal with in the
race.''
   Wallace, who knows his only chance to overcome Elliott's 79-point
lead going into Sunday's race is to do well and have the leader
falter, said, ``Basically, I think we're ready to go. We tested here
'til we wore everything out last week.
   ``We know we've got to do everything. We want to win the pole,
lead every lap, win the race and then stand back and see where we
stand.''
   Also among the drivers failing to qualifying among the top 20 on
Friday were Benny Parsons and Cale Yarborough, a pair of former
Winston Cup champions who have announced their retirement as drivers
following this event.
   Parsons was 26th at 174.181, while Yarborough was 34th at 173.387.
</TEXT>
