<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ReedSentencing     11-18 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reed Sentencing,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reed Sentenced On Extortion Conviction, Removed From Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY REEVES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alabama NAACP President Thomas Reed was
sentenced Friday to four years in federal prison for taking a
$10,000 bribe, a ruling that instantly removes him from his seat in
the state Legislature.
   ``The victim of crimes in this case is the public,'' U.S.
District Judge Joel Dubina told Reed.
   The judge said Reed, 60, had developed a trust with the public
during his five terms in office, but ``gave away that trust for a
small amount of money.''
   ``You used your power ... to line your pockets,'' Dubina told
Reed, convicted of taking cash in exchange for trying to help a
murderer win early release.
   ``Judge, I know I'm not guilty,'' said Reed, who in 1970 became
one of the first two blacks elected to the Alabama Legislature.
   Dubina commended Reed for his legislative and civil rights work,
his educational background, business success and 40-year marriage.
He then sentenced Reed to four years in prison on one extortion
count and three years on another, with the sentences to run
concurrently. A $100 court charge also was assessed.
   Both the prosecution and defense called the sentence fair, but
U.S. Attorney Jim Wilson said the term was ``a little stiffer than
we were thinking it would be.''
   Reed was convicted of taking $10,000 from Columbus, Ga.,
businessman Bobby Gene Chesser. Prosecutors said the money was in
exchange for Reed's attempt to win an early release from prison for
Chesser's nephew, Anthony Dennis Chesser, serving a 40-year sentence
in the murder of his wife.
   The charges against Reed carried a maximum penalty of 25 years in
federal prison and a $500,000 fine.
   Dubina ordered Reed to report to prison on Jan. 3 but allowed him
to remain free on bond. One of Reed's attorneys, Bill Baxley,
indicated he would seek a court order allowing Reed to remain free
while the case is appealed.
   Baxley said he was confident the verdict would be overturned,
with Reed eventually returning to his position in the state House.
</TEXT>
