<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-FoxTheater     11-18 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Fox Theater,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The Glitter of What Once Was Grand Shines Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The glitter of a bygone era is re-emerging from
the dust and neglect of time as the Fox Theater reopens Saturday.
   Singers Smokey Robinson, Billy Eckstein and Hall & Oates will be
featured in a show Saturday celebrating the reopening of the theater
that underwent $8.1 million in restoration work.
   The Count Basie Orchestra, magician Harry Blackstone and
Detroit-born comedian Dave Coulier also will perform in the
5,100-seat theater that was called a ``temple of amusement'' when it
first opened in 1928.
   ``I'm amazed that we've taken the Fox this far,'' said Ray
Shepardson, a theater consultant. ``It not only looks like 1928, it
is 1928.''
   In the theater's early years, a children's dancing school was run
from the Fox and promoter Bennie Davis ran a talent revue nightly
from the huge stage.
   Shows at 2 a.m. were held during World War II for the night-shift
workers at war plants, and Dean Martin and Jerry Lewis performed six
shows a day during a stint at the Fox in 1951.
   But in the following years, the prestige of the Fox began
slipping, and the building began having problems. While the Fox
remained structurally sound, its roof leaked, the carpeting was
badly worn and electrical systems needed improvement.
   All that has been fixed, and new owner Mike Ilitch is putting
headquarters for his Little Caesar International pizza company in a
10-story office building next to the Fox in downtown Detroit. The
theater and office building are expected to key a major
redevelopment of the area.
   Inside the theater, marble-looking pillars actually are plaster.
Gold on sculptures actually is aluminum and the carpet patterns are
injected rather than woven in.
   But that doesn't bother a lot of people.
   ``Who cares that the Fox is all fake and fraud,'' said Audley
Grossman, curator of performing arts at the Detroit Institute of
Arts. ``It's truly a palace with a sense of opulence and fun.''
</TEXT>
