<HEAD>Atwater Promises Quick GOP Start On 1990 Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lee Atwater, tapped by President-elect George
Bush to take over the Republican National Committee, said Friday
that the party will start work immediately on the 1990 campaign.
   ``There's all kinds of races going on,'' Atwater noted, saying he
especially wants to start recruiting for the midterm congressional
elections.
   While the Republicans have captured the White House in five of
the last six elections, they have not been able to gain control of
Congress. All of the House and one-third of the Senate seats are up
in 1990.
   The Republican National Committee meets in January to pick a new
chairman to succeed Frank Fahrenkopf, and Bush's endorsement
virtually guarantees that Atwater will be elected.
   Atwater, who managed Bush's campaign, said he has started making
peace with the other Republicans who ran for the party's
presidential nomination.
   Two of those candidates, television evangelist Pat Robertson and
Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole of Kansas, were especially critical
of Atwater during the campaign and accused him of underhanded
tactics.
   Atwater said he spoke to Robertson on the telephone Friday, and
characterized the conversation as ``good.''
   Dole is out of the country.
   Atwater said he plans to launch a program to recruit more blacks,
Hispanics and Asians to join the party, but he did not specify how
this would be carried out. GOP leaders for years have said they want
more minorities to become Republicans, but so far that has not
happened.
   Joining Atwater at the news conference was Sen. Strom Thurmond,
R-S.C., who hired him as an intern in his Senate office a decade ago.
   Thurmond praised Atwater as a ``keen political analyst, and he is
an outstanding strategist.''
