<2ND_LINE>AM-Boas Sentenced,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boas Gets Probation, Work Detail, $100,000 Fine In Teen Prostitute
Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former city official on Frida was placed
on three years' probation and fined $100,000 for his role in a
teen-age prostitution ring.
   Roger Boas, who as chief administrative officer ran the city for
10 years under two mayors, also was ordered to spend six months on
work detail.
   Boas, 67, was named in an 87-count grand jury indictment Oct. 3
that named 13 other alleged patrons and operators of the brothel. He
pleaded guilty to seven counts of statutory rape in exchange for the
dismissal of 12 counts of having unlawful sex with a minor.
   Boas will serve no time behind bars as long as he participates in
the alternative work program. He also must continue to undergo
counseling and cooperate with authorities in the ongoing
investigation of the prostitution operation.
   ``I feel sadness for everyone affected,'' Boas said. ``I will
serve my sentence and pay my debt to society and try to put this
tragedy behind me and my family. I will then do my utmost to be a
responsible, worthwhile citizen.''
   Boas was included in the investigation after one of the teen-age
prostitutes spotted a Boas campaign poster and recognized his face.
He was running for mayor at the time.
   The indictments stemmed from a 16-month police probe during which
five prostitutes testified they had sex with Boas.
   The charges covered 2{ years that included Boas' final 15 months
as the city's chief administrative officer and his 1987 mayoral
campaign. He finished third in last year's primary.
   Superior Court Judge Timothy A. Reardon called Boas' crimes
``unquestionably reprehensible.''
   He cited several factors he took into account when sentencing
Boas, including Boas' age, lack of a criminal record, former public
service and his ``obvious remorse ... and the public embarrassment
and humiliation'' the crimes brought to Boas and his family.
   Boas, who is married and has four children, left the courtroom
after sentencing without speaking to reporters.
   Boas had faced a maximum of three years on each of the felony
counts of statutory rape. He was ordered to appear Dec. 7 to receive
instructions on the sheriff's alternative work program, which
typically involves public clean-up and gardening chores.
</TEXT>
