<HEAD>Reagan Updates Crisis Guidelines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan signed an executive order
Friday, updating a similar document issued in 1969, aimed at
spelling out for federal departments and agencies precisely what
their responsibilities would be in a national security crisis.
   The focus of the executive order, initially issued by
then-President Richard Nixon, concerns the ``prudent measures'' that
federal agencies can take during a military attack, natural disaster
or technological emergency.
   The executive order, however, does not get into responsibilities
assigned the military, the foreign policy establishment and the
intelligence community, in such a crisis scenario.
