<HEAD>Health Minister to Succeed Parliament President Who Quit After Nazi
Speech</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governing party on Friday nominated
the health minister to replace Philipp Jenninger, the Parliament
president who quit last week after a speech on the Nazi era caused a
furor.
   The Christian Democratic Union of Chancellor Helmut Kohl
announced its nomination of Health Minister Rita Suessmuth. Final
approval is expected next week.
   Jenninger was forced to step down after he angered Jews and
others at home and abroad with a speech Nov. 10 that described Adolf
Hitler's initial appeal to Germans in the 1930s.
   The legislative leader said Hitler was immensely popular 50 years
ago and that at the time many people felt Jews should be ``put back
in their place.''
   The speech was part of ceremonies commemorating Crystal Night,
the pogrom in Germany that signaled the start of the Holocaust.
