<HEAD>Romania, Hungary Feud Over Diplomat's Detention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police in Romania detained a senior
Hungarian diplomat accused of distributing ``hostile'' leaflets, an
official Hungarian report said Friday.
   The incident marked a further deterioration of relations between
the two communist countries, both of which belong to the Warsaw
Pact. In June, Romania closed the Hungarian consulate at Cluj-Napoca
and expelled the staff.
   Hungary's support of about 1.7 million ethnic Hungarians in
Romania has been at the center of the tensions. Hungary says the
minority suffers discrimination.
   A Hungarian Foreign Ministry communique said police in Romania
stopped Hungarian commercial counselor Karoly Gyorfi on Monday while
he was driving a car with diplomatic license plates, the official
Hungarian news agency MTI reported.
   The communique said Gyorfi, attached to the Hungarian Embassy in
Romania, was first accused of driving a stolen car, then of causing
an accident, and finally questioned about spreading inciting
leaflets, the news agency said.
   It said he was released after six hours. A Romanian employed at
the Hungarian Embassy who was in the car was detained along with
Gyorfi and released on Thursday, the report said.
   Foreign Minister Ioan Totu of Romania told the Hungarian
ambassador on Tuesday that the ministry had reached ``the
irrefutable conclusion that the Hungarian diplomat had spread
inciting, hostile leaflets,'' MTI reported. No details about the
nature of the leaflets were given.
   Totu asked Hungary to recall its diplomat, but Hungary made no
announcement that it would do so and denied the accusations.
</TEXT>
