<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-88 2055EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Rinderpest     11-18 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rinderpest,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Announces Vaccine To Rid Third World Cattle of Rinderpest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new vaccine that Third World farmers can use
to save cattle from the infectious disease, rinderpest, is ready for
field trials in Africa, the U.S. Agency for International
Development announced Friday.
   AID Administrator Alan Woods estimated it could prevent losses of
from $100 million to $250 million a year.
   ``In much of the developing world, cattle ... constitute the
family savings,'' Woods told reporters.
   Rinderpest is a highly infectious disease that usually kills
cows, buffalo and some other animals in a week or less.
   Woods said the disease was brought from Italy in the late 1930s
to Ethiopia, which Italian forces then occupied, and spread into
Africa and Asia. It has not been a problem in the United States
because vaccines already exist.
   However, use of the vaccines overseas had been restricted because
the vaccines had to remain refrigerated. That often is impossible in
remote areas of Third World countries.
   Woods said his agency invested less than a million dollars in a
cooperative venture with the University of California, Davis, to
produce a vaccine that does not need refrigeration.
</TEXT>
