<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Kovach-Fellowship     11-18 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kovach-Fellowship,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Atlanta Constitution Editor Named Nieman Fellow</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bill Kovach, who resigned earlier this
month as editor of The Atlanta Journal and the Atlanta Constitution,
was named a Nieman Fellow at Harvard University on Friday, the
school announced.
   Kovach, 56, will join the class of 13 fellows in the prestigious
program established in 1938.
   Kovach, a former Washington bureau chief for The New York Times,
was credited with revamping and invigorating the Atlanta papers
during the nearly two years he was there. He resigned Nov. 4 after a
management disagreement, partially over control of the Cox newspaper
chain's Washington bureau.
   ``Bill Kovach will grace the Nieman program, as he has and will
continue to grace journalism,'' Nieman curator Howard Simons said in
a statement. ``We are lucky, pleased and proud to have him.''
   Kovach began his career as a reporter with the Press Chronicle in
Johnson City, Tenn., and later worked for The Nashville Tennesseean.
   The 13 other Nieman fellows were named in May and began studying
this fall.
   The Nieman Foundation was establised through a bequest of Agnes
Wahl Nieman and pays for one year of study for mid-career
journalists.
</TEXT>
