<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ComputerVirus     11-18 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Computer Virus,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Convenes in Syracuse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegations that a Cornell University
graduate student created a ``virus'' that jammed a nationwide
network of computers are being investigated by a federal grand jury,
a prosecutor said.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Andrew Baxter confirmed the investigation
Thursday but declined to say when the panel began hearing evidence
or if anyone had been subpoenaed to testify.
   Robert T. Morris Jr., 23, is suspected of unleashing the virus on
a computer communication network earlier this month, disrupting
6,000 computers nationwide.
   Morris' friends have quoted him as saying he didn't intend any
harm.
   The virus program transmitted copies of itself from computer to
computer along the InterNet computer network, crashing an estimated
6,000 computers nationwide. It also instructed the infected
computers to make copies of the virus, filling memory space and
keeping the machines busy.
   The virus caused at least $97 million in damage, because of
interrupted work on computers that had to be shut down, and in the
work need to resuscitate the computers, the director of the Computer
Virus Industry Association said Thursday.
   ``Our calculations of the damage it caused are very conservative.
The real cost is probably well over $100 million,'' said John
McAfee, computer virus consultant and director of a Santa
Clara-based group of 11 companies that markets computer programs to
fight viral programs.
   ``The analogy there is the cost of conducting a massive search
for thousands of hidden bombs and then disabling them,'' McAfee said.
   ``Just the time that the programmers spent conferring with each
other, either in meetings or over the telephone, as they tried to
share knowledge in combatting the infection was estimated ... at
least 12,000 (hours),'' McAfee said.
   No charges have been filed.
   The FBI is conducting a criminal investigation to determine if
statutes on wire fraud, malicious mischief or unlawful access to
stored communications may have been broken. The FBI has subpoenaed
computer tapes and other records at Cornell's computer science
department.
   Baxter declined to say if anyone other than Morris is the target
of the grand jury investigation in Syracuse.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
