<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     11-18 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethnic Violence Frightens Election Officials; Won't Take Part in
Balloting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of election officials will not
participate in Saturday's balloting in Northeastern Province because
they fear attacks by both Tamil and Sinhalese militants, according
to government sources.
   Election Commissioner Chandrananda De Silva said the number of
polling booths had been reduced from 567 to 324 because of the lack
of staff. He said only 300 members of the 2,200 people scheduled to
oversee the voting were available for duty.
   He gave no reason why the others would not work but government
sources, speaking with condition of anonymity, said violence was
expected.
   The elections are for 35 members of a semiautonomous
administrative council responsible for governing the Tamil-dominated
province.
   The establishment of such councils was a key part of the
India-mediated accord signed in July 1987 to end the five-year-old
war by Tamils demanding their own homeland.
   Tamils, most of whom are Hindus, accuse the Buddhist Sinhalese
majority of discrimination. Tamils are a majority in northeastern
Sri Lanka but comprise only 18 percent of the island country's
population of 16 million.
   Both the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, the largest Tamil
rebel organization, and Sinhalese activists have called for a
boycott of Saturday's election.
   The Liberation Tigers say an administrative council does not meet
their demands for autonomy and Sinhalese militants claim the 1987
pact grants too many concessions to the Tamils.
   Presidential elections are scheduled for Dec. 19 and the campaign
has been scarred by violence.
   Four people were killed and at least 70 were wounded Thursday
when Sinhalese extremists hurled bombs at a rally addressed by Ossie
Abeygoonasekara, the candidate of a coalition of three leftist
parties.
   Abeygoonasekara was not injured but the coalition's previous
leader, Vijaya Kumaranatunga, was assassinated in February. Police
blamed the killing on members of the People's Liberation Front, a
Sinhalese organization.
   Top contenders in the presidential contest are Prime Minister
Ranasinghe Premadasa of the United National Party and former Prime
Minister Sirimavo Bandaranaike of the Sri Lanka Freedom Party. Mrs.
Bandaranaike was Kumaranatunga's mother-in-law.
   The People's Liberation Front has waged a violent campaign in an
effort to force President Junius R. Jayewardene to resign before the
elections. It claims he and his United National Party will not
conduct a fair election.
   The front has threatened to kill anyone supporting the 1987
accord, and since the agreement was signed, more than 550 government
officials and supporters have been killed.
   Some Tamil organizations have accepted the agreement and have
entered candidates in Saturday's election despite threats by the
Liberation Tigers.
   Troops of an Indian peacekeeping force have been stationed in the
Noratheastern Province after the Liberation Tigers rejected the
peace plan.
</TEXT>
