<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Subway,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Victims of British Subway Fire Remembered</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City residents placed red roses and wreaths Friday
at the entrance to King's Cross subway station where a fire one year
ago killed 31 people in the worst disaster in the 120-year history
of the system.
   Reports of smoke brought firefighters back to the station Friday.
But it proved to be a false alarm.
   About 60 people took part in a prayer service for the victims and
their families Friday evening at the nearby Blessed Sacrament Roman
Catholic Church.
   Outside King's Cross station, more than 70 friends of musician
Ivan Tarrasenko, one of the victims, staged a noisy tribute to their
mentor with an assortment of percussion instruments. They used
sticks to beat drums, metal rails, and even traffic cones.
   A dropped match started the fire at the end of evening rush hour
in one of London's busiest subway stations. An official inquiry said
haphazard staff response and complacency among managers contributed
to the disaster.
   Many of the bouquets and wreaths Friday paid tribute to Colin
Townsley, a 45-year-old firefighter who died trying to rescue
passengers.
