<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-US     11-18 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-US,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Shamir Seeks Compromise on Conversion Issue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said Friday he
seeks a compromise to avoid alienating U.S. Jews from Israel over
religious demands that he outlaw non-Orthodox conversions to
Judaism, a U.S. congressman said.
   Shamir's remarks to a group of congressmen and American Jewish
fund-raisers came after a group representing millions of Jews in the
United States and Canada announced at a conference in New Orleans
this week a new offensive against attempts to change the ``Who is a
Jew'' law in Israel.
   The group is the Council of Jewish Federations, which says it
represents 95 percent of the 5.5 million to 6 million Jews in North
America.
   ``All members of the Jewish community are considered members of
the Jewish people. We do not want to prefer anybody or exclude
anybody,'' Shamir was quoted as saying by Rep. Jim Courters, R-N.J.
   ``Everyone who considers himself a Jew is a Jew. We are looking
for a solution, a solution that will not give Jews in America reason
to take warning.''
   Courters said Shamir did not elaborate.
   He said Shamir spoke after Courters and fund-raisers of the
United Jewish Appeal told the Israeli leader they were ``concerned
about the redefinition of who is a Jew.''
   ``Most American Jews take exception to it,'' Cliff Sobel of the
United Jewish Appeal delegation told a reporter after the meeting.
   Harry Wall, director of the Israel office of the Anti-Defamation
League, said he considered Shamir's comments a change in Shamir's
earlier assurances to religious parties that the law would be
changed.
   ``A corner has been turned here toward mitigating this dispute,
this highly emotional issue,'' Wall said.
   Shamir, who heads the right-wing Likud bloc, earlier promised
four key swing parties of the ultra-Orthodox bloc that he would
support their bid to change Israel's Law of Return in exchange for
their support in a governing coalition.
   The Law of Return guarantees citizenship to any Jew who
immigrates. The religious parties want the law to disqualify persons
converted to Judaism by non-Orthodox rabbis.
   Most of the American Jewish community belongs to non-Orthodox
streams of Judaism, namely the Conservative and Reform movements.
</TEXT>
