<HEAD>Late-Season Tropical Depression Heading Toward Jamaica</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to UPDATE with 5 p.m. EDT position.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rain and flash flooding were possible in
Jamaica as a poorly organized tropical depression headed slowly
toward that island nation, ravaged two moths ago by Hurricane
Gilbert, forecasters said Friday.
   The late-season depression had top winds of 35 mph and was
centered about 250 miles southwest of the Jamaican capital of
Kingston, the National Hurricane Center reported. It was moving west
at about 5 mph, and little strengthening was expected over the next
24 hours.
   The Atlantic hurricane season began in June and ends Nov. 30. The
season usually peaks in September.
