<HEAD>Vinich Won't Ask For Recount In U.S. Senate Race, Concedes To
Wallop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUDSON, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat John Vinich said Friday he will not
ask for a recount of votes cast in Wyoming's tight U.S. Senate race
and conceded the election to incumbent Malcolm Wallop.
   The state senator from Hudson said he spoke with Secretary of
State Kathy Karpan and decided a recount would confirm Wallop's
victory.
   Wallop won his third six-year Senate term by 1,332 votes of the
approximately 180,000 ballots cast.
   ``The only way we could verify any absentee vote or ... voting
machine problems would be to file a suit with the state against the
counties and state,'' Vinich said. ``I ran for office to serve the
people of Wyoming and not to sue the state.
   ``The issues are more important to Wyoming than putting the state
through that kind of pain.''
   Wallop's spokesman said the incumbent was pleased with the news.
