<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon-Kidnap     11-18 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Kidnap,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO and Militias Search for Kidnapped Red Cross Official</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO guerrillas and local militiamen scoured
a crowded refugee camp, tramped through fruit groves, stopped cars
and frisked passengers Friday looking for a kidnapped Swiss official
of the Red Cross.
   One militia leader said they believe 32-year-old Peter Winkler,
who was abducted Thursday, was being held nearby.
   No group has claimed responsibility for Winkler's abduction.
   ``Despite the lack of any information on Mr. Winkler, we believe
he is still in the Sidon region,'' said the official of the Sunni
Moslem militia Popular Nasserite Organization, who identified
himself only by the code-name of Abu Yahya. ``We will do our best to
find him.''
   Three gunmen grabbed Winkler from a Red Cross car in Sidon. He
heads the city's office of the International Committee of the Red
Cross, which provides relief to victims of Lebanon's civil war, now
in its 14th year.
   ``Mr. Winkler should be rescued. The Red Cross shouldn't be under
any threat,'' said Abu Yahya.
   His group's militiamen, armed with assault rifles and
rocket-propelled grenade launchers, searched cars and frisked their
passengers Friday at all entry points to Sidon, which lies about 25
miles south of Beirut. Their leftist militia controls the city.
   In heavy rain, joint patrols of the Palestine Liberation
Organization and local militiamen combed the crowded Ein el-Hilweh
refugee camp and nearby orange and banana groves on Sidon's southern
outskirts.
   Police and the leftist Moslem militia said they believe he was
kidnapped for a trade with Hussein Hariri, a Lebanese air hijacker
held in Switzerland.
   Hariri, a 22-year-old Shiite Moslem who belongs to the
Iranian-backed group called Hezbollah, hijacked an Air Afrique
jetliner on a flight from Rome to Paris in July 1987. He forced it
to land at Geneva airport and killed a French passenger before he
was overpowered and arrested.
   A police spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, suggested
Friday that the terrorist group led by Abu Nidal, who has been
linked to many terrorist attacks worldwide, may have kidnapped
Winkler at Hezbollah's request.
   The fundamentalist Hezbollah, or Party of God, is an umbrella
group for pro-Iranian extremist factions believed to hold most of
the 14 foreign hostages in Lebanon, including nine Americans.
Longest held is Terry Anderson, chief Mideast correspondent for The
Associated Press, who was captured March 16, 1985.
   The PLO joined the search for Winkler after blaming the abduction
on enemies of its newly proclaimed state of Palestine. The group
joined the leftist Moslem militia, four leftist parties, and the
mainstream Shiite Amal militia in a statement Friday denouncing the
latest kidnapping.
</TEXT>
