<1ST_LINE>r i AM-HelsinkiReview     11-18 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Helsinki Review,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US-French Disagree Over French Decision To Review Position</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIOREL URMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and France disagreed
Friday about France's decision to review NATO positions on a new
forum for conventional arms reduction talks, which Washington says
delays progress toward negotiations.
   Gilles Curien of France rejected American and other Western
claims that the French review was blocking progress. He leads his
country's delegation at the Vienna follow-up conference to the 1975
Helsinki agreements on European security and cooperation.
   Warren Zimmermann, chief U.S. delegate, said at a news briefing:
``We hope the French government is not going to put (previous NATO)
agreements into question. Because if there was a question of taking
another look at those agreements which took us such a long and
difficult time to reach, then I think we would be inevitably forced
into a long delay at the conference.''
   In Paris, President Francois Mitterrand said France remains
``very open and does not wish to be an obstacle to the immediate
negotiations. It will, rather, complain of the numerous obstacles
posed by others, so little pressed to discuss these matters.''
   Senior diplomats in East and West had expressed confidence in the
past week that talks between the 16 North Atlantic Treaty
Organization and seven Warsaw Pact countries on a new mandate for
conventional arms control talks could be concluded this year.
   The negotiations are designed to replace the Mutual and Balanced
Force Reduction talks, which have dragged on without agreement in
Vienna for nearly 15 years.
   Current talks involve only seven NATO nations and four Warsaw
Pact countries, and focus on central Europe. The new talks, in
addition to involving more nations, would cover all Europe from the
Atlantic to the Ural Mountains.
   Informal talks between the 23 member countries of the two
alliances began in February 1987 as the result of security
negotiations in the review conference, at which the United States,
Canada, Soviet Union and all European countries except Albania are
represented.
   The Vienna meeting is one of several review conferences held to
review compliance with the Helsinki agreements. It began in November
1986.
   Curien said in a speech to delegates Friday that his government's
decision to review the mandate talks was made because the
negotiations are ``a major political preoccupation for Europe's
future.''
   ``We attach the greatest importance to the fact that military
affairs should not be separated from other areas of the (Helsinki
agreements), such as human rights, because the whole (process)
represents a single and unique idea for Europe's future,'' he said.
   Earlier this week, a Western official told reporters conventional
arms control is so vital to Western security that it should be
negotiated on its own merits, not in relation to other Helsinki
issues.
   He said making the talks dependent on future Helsinki review
conferences, as France wants, could jeopardize the balanced approach
the West seeks in that forum to the three main issues of security,
human rights and economic cooperation.
   Curien said the current review in Paris grew out of a need for
``clarifications'' in the conference texts, in which ``certain
paragraphs are ambiguous or at least they can give rise to various
interpretations.'' He did not elaborate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881118-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-88 2140EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Fertility     11-18 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Fertility,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Researchers Find Peak Fertility in November</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Women are more likely to become pregnant in
November than in any other month, says a report on fertility
published Friday.
   A study of 259 conceptions by artificial insemination at a
British hospital showed twice as many conceived in November,
December and January as in June or July, with the rate peaking in
November.
   Results echoed previous findings that natural conceptions peaked
at about the same time of year, said the report published in the
British Medical Journal.
   ``Seasonal variations in rates of natural conception in women is
well documented,'' it said. ``The peak lasts from early winter to
early spring. We found that conceptions resulting from artificial
insemination were similarly distributed.''
   The study conducted at the Jessop Hospital for Women in
Sheffield, northern England, looked at the women's conception rates
in 1974-1982.
   Doctors who did the research wrote said in their report that
seasonal variations in conception had to result from one or more of
five factors: frequency of sexual intercourse; rate of ovulation;
quality of semen; quality of the egg after ovulation, or receptivity
of the womb lining _ ``endometrial'' receptivity.
   Frequency of intercourse was irrelevent in this case, they said,
because the women's partners were infertile and artificial
insemination was used. The researchers said the ovulation rate was
``unimportant'' because only confirmed periods of ovulation were
included in the data.
   Sperm might have been the key because there was a seasonal
variation in its quality, the authors said, but added that the time
of maximum sperm count and volume was in Febuary and March _ too
early in the year to produce a November peak in fertility.
   ``By exclusion, therefore,'' the report said, ``we suggest there
is seasonal variation in the quality of the egg or endometrial
receptivity, or both, and that the time of highest quality is early
winter.''
   It did not say definitively why quality should be higher in early
winter, but suggested it could be linked to the production of extra
sex hormones, which are released in greater quantities in winter
months.
   The doctors who wrote the report said it should ``speak for
itself'' and declined comment. They are Eftis Paraskevaides,
registrar of the gynecology department at North Manchester General
Hospital; George Pennington, consultant chemical pathologist at the
Jessop Hospital, and his assistant, Sandra Naik.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
