<HEAD>Bomb Wrecks Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Masked men carried a bomb into a
Londonderry office Friday and ordered the occupants out before the
blast wrecked the building, police said.
   In Belfast, police defused a bomb planted under a footpath used
by school children.
   No injuries were reported in either incident. There were no
immediate claims of responsibility, although suspicion fell on the
outlawed Irish Republican Army, which is fighting to drive the
British from the Protestant-led province and unite it with the
heavily Roman Catholic Republic of Ireland.
   The staff of a tax office in Londonderry were organizing
fund-raising events for a children's charity when three masked men
burst into the building, carrying a bomb they had brought in a
hijacked Post Office van, police said.
   The men ordered the staff out and then fled themselves, police
said, and minutes later the device exploded, wrecking the building.
   Belfast police said a bomb containing up to four pounds of
explosive was found under a footpath at Grosvenor Road, near a
nursery and primary school.
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary said young children use the path on
their way to school.
