<2ND_LINE>AM-AT&T Outage, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0668,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>East Coast Phone Service Disrupted as Cable Severed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to restore editor's note; new thruout to UPDATE
with quotes, problem corrected, details; no pick up</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Telephone service and computer systems along the
entire East Coast were disrupted Friday when a primary transmission
cable was severed by a construction crew in New Jersey, AT&T
announced.
   The accident in the Brown Junction railroad yard in Sayreville,
N.J., forced rerouting of thousands of calls which ordinarily use
the cable, said AT&T District Manager Jim Nelson.
   ``It's almost like a highway, in that you have to go along it to
get from say, New York to Florida,'' said Nelson. ``This is a major
blockage, affecting the whole East Coast.''
   In addition to affecting phone service, several private customers
using phone line transmissions _ including The Associated Press _
experienced service problems Friday afternoon, said Nelson.
   The disruption in service meant many callers either got a
recording telling them to dial again or a busy signal, said Nelson.
   Harry Baumgartner, a spokesman for AT&T in Basking Ridge, N.J.,
said the damage was caused by a back hoe that inadvertantly severed
a three-inch, light-guide cable.
   He said there was no way to estimate how many millions of
customers were affected.
   ``The blockage affected people in varying degrees across the
nation, with the effects concentrated on the East Coast,'' he said.
``The closer you got to the site of the broken cable the more likely
you were to have trouble completing calls.''
   Baumgartner said the problems had been cleared up by 6:30 p.m.
EST except in several New Jersey counties near the break.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
