<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Cattle-Feedlots     11-18 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cattle-Feedlots,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Feedlot Cattle Inventories Down From Last Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cattle being fed for the slaughter market as of
Nov. 1 in the seven major beef states totaled 7.92 million head,
down 5 percent from a year ago but 5 percent more than inventories
of two years ago, the Agriculture Department said Friday.
   The placement of new cattle and calves in fattening pens last
month was reported at 2.48 million head, down 5 percent from a year
ago but up 3 percent from two years ago.
   Marketings of ``fed'' cattle in August totaled 1.6 million head,
down 5 percent from a year ago but up 1 percent from two years ago.
   As of Nov. 1, feedlot inventories were smaller than a year
earlier in Arizona, Colorado, Iowa, Kansas, Nebraska and Texas.
California showed an increase. The seven states produce about
three-fourths of the nation's beef.
   State feedlot cattle inventories are listed here for the seven
states. The first number is the number of cattle, in thousands, as
of Nov. 1, and the second number is the percentage of a year
earlier.
</TEXT>
