<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Theater-Awards     11-18 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Theater-Awards,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Classic Tops London Drama Awards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A National Theater revival of Tennessee Williams'
``Cat On A Hot Tin Roof'' won two out of seven awards at the 33rd
Evening Standard Drama awards Friday.
   But no best musical award was made, reflecting what has been an
exceptionally weak season for London musicals.
   Lindsay Duncan, who played Maggie the Cat, and Eric Porter, who
portrayed Big Daddy, were named best actress and actor for their
performances in the 1955 Williams play set in the deep South.
   Howard Davies directed the National's production and is due to
stage a Broadway revival of the same play, with Kathleen Turner next
year.
   The National itself won a special award in honor of its 25th
birthday last month. Diana Rigg, who gave the award to the theater's
new artistic director, Richard Eyre, led a lineup of presenters that
included Paul Scofield, Rex Harrison, Janet Suzman and Irish actor
Milo O'Shea.
   The Irish play ``Aristocrats,'' a decade-old work by Brian Friel
that made its belated London debut in June, was named best play. The
best comedy award went to Peter Shaffer's Broadway-bound ``Lettice
and Lovage,'' which opens at New York's Plymouth Theater in February.
   Timberlake Wertenbaker was cited as most promising playwright for
``Our Country's Good,'' which ended a limited run at the Royal Court
Theater Nov. 12.
   Deborah Warner was named best director for ``Titus Andronicus,''
her staging of Shakespeare's difficult play by the Royal Shakespeare
Company.
</TEXT>
