<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-18 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow in the Southwest; Rain in the Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Up to 11 inches of snow fell in parts of the Southwest on Friday,
and rain and thunderstorms increased over Arkansas and the
Mississippi Valley as southerly winds continued bringing moisture
from the Gulf of Mexico.
   Crested Butte, Colo., reported 11 inches of new snow overnight,
and 5 inches fell at the south rim of the Grand Canyon in Arizona.
   Snow advisories were posted Friday afternoon for the southern
mountains of Colorado, the northeast quarter of Arizona and the
northern and western mountains of New Mexico.
   Over an inch of rain fell in 30 minutes over parts of Little
Rock, Ark., while other thunderstorms produced pea-size hail at
Sulphur Springs, Texas.
   Rain fell from eastern Texas across most of Arkansas, southern
Missouri, southern Illinois, western Kentucky, western Tennessee and
northern Mississippi.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. EST
included 2.5 inches at Little Rock, almost 2 at Hot Springs, Ark.,
and more than half an inch at Jonesboro, Ark.
   Heavy snow was expected over much of the central Plains as an
upper level disturbance over Arizona moves northeast. A winter storm
watch was posted through Saturday for the Texas and Oklahoma
panhandles and portions of Kansas, where up to 8 inches of snow was
forecast.
   Snow also was forecast Saturday for eastern Nebraska, western
Iowa, much of Minnesota and northern Wisconsin. Occasional light
snow fell across portions of the Dakotas and western Minnesota.
   Winds up to 35 mph were reported over the mountains and deserts
of southern California. Partly cloudy skies prevailed across the
East Coast states.
   Temperatures ranged from the upper 40s to the 50s over southern
New England and the middle Atlantic Coast states. Readings were
mostly in the 60s across the Carolinas. In Florida, temperatures
were in the mid-to-upper 80s.
   Temperatures in the West were mostly in the 30s and 40s, and in
the 50s and 60s in the desert Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 10
degrees at Glasgow Mont., to 91 degrees at McAllen, Texas.
   The low in the nation Friday morning was minus 3 at Williston,
N.D.
   The forecast for Saturday called for showers and thunderstorms
from the southern plains across the Mississippi Valley to the lower
Ohio and Tennessee valleys and the Gulf Coast states.
   Rain was forecast from eastern Kansas across northern Missouri
and eastern Iowa to the Great Lakes. Rain showers will be scattered
from the upper Ohio Valley and the mid-Atlantic states. Snow will
fall from the Texas and Oklahoma panhandles across central and
western Kansas and through Nebraska, Iowa, Minnesota, Wisconsin and
Michigan.
   Skies are to be partly cloudy over the Rocky Mountains and into
California.
   Highs were to reach the 20s and 30s from the northern and central
Rockies across much of the Great Plains and upper Mississippi Valley
to northern Michigan. Temperatures in the 30s were forecast for
northern New England. Highs in the 60s and 70s will extend from the
south Atlantic coastal states across the Tennessee Valley.
   Highs will reach the 60s to lower 70s over the desert Southwest
and much of California.
</TEXT>
