<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-88 2141EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland     11-18 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Walesa and Advisers Confer, Secrecy Surrounds Movements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa met Friday
night with Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak, an activist
source said, but the results were not reported immediately.
   Government and Roman Catholic Church officials were unusually
secretive throughout the day about the meeting, which appeared to be
the latest effort to salvage stalled round-table talks between the
government and Solidarity.
   Kiszczak asked Walesa three weeks ago for a face-to-face meeting
to remove obstacles to the long-promised talks on the future of
Solidarity and on the broader issues of economic and political
reform. A week ago, he sent another message to Walesa but neither
side has made public the contents.
   The activist source, a member of the outlawed Solidarity,
confirmed a meeting had taken place and said the independent trade
union would have a statement Saturday morning. The source spoke
shortly before midnight and on condition his name not be used.
   The discussions were offered by the government during Poland's
worst wave of labor unrest in seven years.
   After accepting the offer, Walesa agreed to bring an end to the
last of the strikes.
   Walesa drove to Warsaw from his home in Gdansk on Thursday night
and conferred Friday with advisers and church officials before
meeting Kiszczak.
   Walesa's close adviser, historian Bronislaw Geremek, said Friday
that the only ``decisive'' issue blocking round-table talks was
whether the government would show a ``will to legalize Solidarity.''
   He said that if the government makes a positive sign, ``then it
seems the chance for the round-table will return.''
   Walesa, winner of the 1983 Nobel Peace Prize, has met three times
with Kiszczak about setting up the talks, the last time on Sept. 16.
   The official press quoted Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski
as saying the fate of the proposed talks could be made clear in
coming days.
   The official Communist Party newspaper Trybuna Ludu said Friday
the authorities were not to blame for failure of the discussions to
start as originally planned on Oct. 17.
   It accused the opposition of insisting that the government
concede beforehand on the major issue of relegalizing Solidarity,
banned after Jaruzelski imposed martial law in December 1981.
   The talks were promised Aug. 31 in a meeting between Walesa and
Kiszczak. But preparations broke down when the government objected
to the proposed participation of longtime Solidarity advisers Adam
Michnik and Jacek Kuron, who officials branded as too extreme in
their views.
   Walesa said he would tolerate no government interference in his
delegation.
   Other issues that were blocking the round-table appear to have
been resolved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
