<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     11-18 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Charges Filed Against Soldiers In Escape of Communist Rebel Leader</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Behn is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By YASMIN ARQUIZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven soldiers were charged Friday in
the escape of a rebel who commanded the communist army that has
fought to overthrow the government for 19 years.
   A prominent stage director said he received a summons from the
military to explain whether he was involved in the Nov. 12 escape of
Romulo Kintanar, 41, and Kintanar's wife, Gloria, 38.
   Military prosecutors charged former stockade commander Maj.
Robelito Comilang, two other officers and four enlisted guards with
negligence for letting the Kintanars leave their cells to attend
Comilang's birthday party at his quarters next to the stockade at
Camp Crame, headquarters of the Philippine Constabulary.
   When guards returned to take the couple back to their cells, they
had disappeared, the military says.
   An officer at the constabulary's Judge Advocate General's Office
said the seven could face dismissal from service or imprisonment if
convicted.
   The military said Kintanar was commander of the 25,000-member New
People's Army when he and his wife were arrested in Manila last
March. The military hailed the arrest as a major blow to the 19-year
insurgency.
   The Kintanars were awaiting trial on rebellion charges.
   Kintanar also was believed to have organized urban guerrilla
squads responsible for killing hundreds of police and soldiers in
Philippine cities since 1985.
   In a letter published Friday by The Manila Standard and the
Philippine Daily Inquirer, Kintanar said he and his wife have
``succeeded in rejoining our comrades and our people in the
countryside to actively contribute our humble share in our people's
continuing struggle for national freedom and social liberation.''
   Military sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said a
prominent stage director visited the stockade on Nov. 12 and allowed
the couple to flee in his car.
   Behn Cervantes told reporters that he was the director alluded to
by the military. He said he visited Mrs. Kintanar and other
prisoners at the stockade but left before the escape.
   ``They are using me as a scapegoat,'' Cervantes said. ``Why blame
me if their security measures are lax?''
   About 500 activists who joined a rally Friday at a central Manila
square marched on the presidential palace later. At the foot of the
bridge leading to the palace, they lit candles to symbolize the
disappearance of about 100 activists this year.
   Rally leaders denounced Corazon Aquino's government for allegedly
tolerating the same abuses practiced by ousted ruler Ferdinand
Marcos. Mrs. Aquino has ordered security officials to investigate
the disappearances.
   The left-wing New Patriotic Alliance, which says 15 of its
members have disappeared this year, released a statement urging Mrs.
Aquino and the congress to find the soldiers it believes caused the
disappearances.
   Police blocked the protesters on the bridge near the palace but
allowed them to hold a brief demonstration.
</TEXT>
