<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BRF--YellowstoneFires     11-18 0117</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Yellowstone Fires,0119</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow In Yellowstone Makes Summer Fires Officially Out</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Up to 30 inches of snow in
Yellowstone National Park has snuffed out the last of the fires that
raged through the nation's oldest park this summer, the park
announced Friday.
   The fires affected about 995,000 acres of the 2.2 million-acre
park. But only about 20,000 acres suffered ``high-intensity heat''
fires that scorch the earth so badly it does not renew itself.
   Crews have spent weeks replanting seedlings in burned-out areas,
taking measures to prevent erosion of hiking trails and doing other
rehabilitation work.
   Current snow depths range from 8 inches to 30 inches, said park
spokeswoman Joan Anzelmo.
</TEXT>
