<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-88 2213EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MissingTeen-Agers     11-18 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Missing Teen-Agers,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Car Plunged Through Gap; Searchers Find Case of Mostly Empty Beer
Cans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Concrete barriers that would have
prevented a car carrying four young people from plunging into a
river had been inexplicably moved, officials said Friday.
   Police also said 24 mostly empty beer cans were found inside the
car. None of the occupants, all of whom died, was of legal drinking
age, which is 21.
   The car was discovered at the bottom of Mill River on Thursday,
five days after the four friends from East Lyme disappeared during a
night out in New Haven.
   The accident occurred on a dark stretch of road that was shut
down last year because a 105-year-old swing-bridge was beyond
repair. The bridge was left open, parallel to the river, so boats
could pass by on either side.
   Mayor Biagio DiLieto said an investigation confirmed the 2-ton
barriers had been moved, leaving a gap wide enough for a car to pass
through.
   Autopsies determined the four had drowned, the state medical
examiner's office said. Results of blood-alcohol tests are expected
next week, but police said they did not know if they would be made
public.
   Police said they had not yet determined who was driving the car,
which belonged to Christy Stevens.
   Separate funeral services, beginning Saturday, were planned for
Miss Stevens, Laura Lagrotteria and Jill Sawyer, all 19, and Michael
Gallo, 20.
   Sawyer attended the University of Rhode Island, Gallo was a
student at Southern Connecticut State University in New Haven, and
Stevens was a student at Mohegan Community College in Norwich.
Lagrotteria worked at a pizza parlor in East Lyme.
   The blocks were out of place when the car went into the river,
but officials said the city did not learn until Wednesday, when a
police officer visited the site, that there was a gap large enough
for a car to fit through.
   The hole was closed that day.
   Police found the blocks out of position after an Oct. 22 car
accident at the site, but city officials said reports indicated the
gap was not large enough at that time for a car to fit through. The
accident was the third at the barriers since the bridge was closed
in August 1987.
   City officials said they are investigating why public works crews
put up wooden barriers after the accident but did not return the
blocks to their original position.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
