<DOCNO> AP881118-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-88 2230EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ReaganNuclear-Reax     11-18 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan Nuclear-Reax,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>McEachern: Executive Order A Foregone Conclusion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: With AM-Reagan-Nuclear</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WENDY MITMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's empowering a federal
agency to prepare and impose evacuation plans for nuclear plants
like Seabrook flouts the intent of Congress and faces certain legal
challenge, a Seabrook foe said Friday.
   Reagan on Friday signed the order giving the Federal Emergency
Management Agency broad new powers to submit evacuation plans for
nuclear plants which have been unable to obtain licenses because of
state or local opposition.
   ``I'm sure the intervenors in the (Seabrook) case will do
something about it, because Congress did not change the laws, and
clearly they did not intend that the federal government should usurp
state and local planning,'' said Jane Doughty of the Seacoast
Anti-Pollution League.
   The 2-year-old, $5.7 billion Seabrook reactor has no operating
license because Massachusetts towns within its 10-mile evacuation
zone and Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis have refused to
cooperate in emergency planning.
   Reagan's order lets FEMA develop an evacuation plan and submit it
to the Nuclear Regulatory Commission on behalf of the local
community. Until recently, states were required to submit an
evacuation plan in the NRC licensing process. Due to opposition to
Seabrook by Massachusetts and to the Shoreham plant on Long Island
by New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, the NRC has accepted but not approved
plans for both plants written by their utility owners.
   Both plans face legal challenges.
   Rep. Robert Smith, R-N.H., said the final version seems slightly
weaker than the wording in the original draft, ``much more
conciliatory.''
   He said he supports the thrust of the order, because he feels the
federal government must step in when state or local governments try
to block a plant's licensing.
   Gov.-elect Judd Gregg, former 2nd District congressman, and Sen.
Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., condemned the order when it was reported
earlier this year but they did not return calls from the Associated
Press seeking comment.
   Paul McEachern, a Seabrook foe who lost his bid as the 1988
Democratic gubernatorial nominee, said the order was a foregone
conclusion that the Reagan administration put the order on a back
burner until after the election.
   ``The circumstantial evidence is overwhelming that was the case,
that they would get it signed at the first appropriate time after
the election,'' McEachern said.
   ``The Nuclear Regulatory Commission has demonstrated it will
change any rule that gets in the way of licensing (Seabrook), and
with the election results, there is absolutely nothing that will
prevent this administratively from going on line. There may be legal
challenges, but that's all that remains,'' McEachern said.
   Seabrook spokesman Rob Williams said the order really does
nothing to hasten Seabrook's licensing. He said the plant's owners
already received NRC permission to develop their owns plans for
uncooperative Massachusetts communities, and New Hampshire has
cooperated all along.
   Those plans were tested earlier this year and received high marks
from FEMA, he said.
   ``I don't see this speeding licensing,'' Williams said. ``It is
welcome news really on the national level, because any plant that
faces that situation of non-participation like we faced now has
clear federal policy on how federal resources would be used in
planning.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
