<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Cambodia     11-18 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cambodia,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sihanouk Says Cambodian Settlement Talks Fail</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   AIX-EN-PROVENCE, France (AP) _ Cambodian resistance leader Prince
Norodom Sihanouk said the last round of talks toward a settlement in
his country had failed, a French news agency reported Friday.
   Sihanouk blamed Hun Sen, head of the Vietnam-installed government
in Phnom Penh, for creating an impasse in the talks, Agence-France
Presse reported.
   Sihanouk, who ruled Cambodia from 1941-1970, is head of a
resistance coalition fighting the government in Cambodia.
   AFP said he made his remarks late Thursday to a group of students
in this southern French town.
   Sihanouk met Hun Sen and Son Sann, representing the Khmer
People's National Liberation Front, at a hotel outside Paris Nov. 6.
The talks were part of efforts by the resistance movements and the
Cambodian government to reach an agreement on the future of Cambodia.
   Sihanouk accused Hun Sen of putting Vietnamese and Soviet
interests ahead of Cambodian concerns, AFP reported. The Soviet
Union backs Vietnam, which invaded Cambodia in 1978 and maintains
120,000 troops there.
   China backs the Khmer Rouge, held responsible for a reign of
terror in which a quarter of Cambodia's 8 million people died before
Vietnam invaded and ousted the government. Hun Sen's government,
picked by Vietnam, has not been recognized by non-communist nations.
   The Khmer Rouge is not taking part in the talks. Sihanouk has
said no settlement is possible without the Khmer Rouge, who were
invited to the last meeting, but who were eventually excluded
because the proposed envoy was rejected as too low ranking for a
summit.
   ``The discussions yielded no concrete results simply because Hun
Sen was defending the interests of Vietnam,'' Sihanouk was quoted as
saying, adding, according to AFP, that resistance groups and the
government were ``speaking two different languages''.
   Sihanouk said Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev and authorities
in Beijing now were key to settling the dispute, the agency
reported. China wants concessions in exchange for withdrawing its
support of the 40,000 Khmer Rouge guerrillas, the largest resistance
force. Moscow wants assurance that upon Vietnam's withdrawing its
troops in 1990 as expected the Khmer Rouge will not take power.
   ``I am counting on the two superpowers to convince Vietnam to
reach a peaceful political solution to the problem of Cambodia,''
Sihanouk was quoted as saying.
   Vietnam is not participating directly in the peace talks. AFP
said Sihanouk called on Vietnam to ``participate in an international
conference in Paris.''
   The meeting made no substantial progress toward settlement but
established a working commission based in Paris. The commission's
brief is to ``study all the possibilities for a political solution
to the Cambodian problem''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
