<HEAD>Carlucci: Brazil Pledges `Responsible' Arms Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Secretary of Defense Frank Carlucci
said Friday that Brazilian officials pledged to follow a responsible
policy of arms sales, especially to Libya.
   He arrived in Brazil Thursday for a four-day private visit. He
met Friday with President Jose Sarney and top military and civilian
Cabinet ministers.
   Carlucci told a news conference at the U.S. Embassy that he
discussed Brazilian arms sales to the Mideast and Libya.
   ``Brazil has assured us it will follow a responsible policy, and
we accept that,'' Carlucci said.
   He said America was willing to step up the supply of technology
to Brazilian arms manufacturers, but declined to elaborate.
   Brazil is a major arms supplier to the Third World. Middle East
and African nations are important clients.
   Carlucci described Brazil-U.S. military relations as
``excellent.'' However, Brazilian Navy Minister Adm. Henrique Saboia
called relations ``cool'' and said Carlucci's visit was aimed at
``warming them up a little.''
   Carlucci said the U.S. government was not concerned that Sarney
recently visited the Soviet Union, and that Brazil and the Soviets
agreed to exchange military attaches.
   ``The United States doesn't discourage relations of any country
with Moscow. On the contrary, the more the Soviets open to the West,
the more evident it is that their regime is a failure,'' he said.
