<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AirportSpill     11-18 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airport Spill,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fuel Spill Disrupts Operations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A broken jet fuel pipeline at the San
Francisco International Airport disrupted dozens of incoming and
departing flights and temporarily stranded scores of passengers
Friday afternoon.
   Incoming flights were diverted to airports throughout the West
Coast, and numerous departing flights were delayed several hours,
said airport spokesman Ron Wilson. Exact figures were not available.
   Contractors broke a 12-inch underground fuel line near the TWA
terminal about 4:30 p.m., effectively shutting off supplies to all
three terminals, Wilson said.
   ``Pilots are being advised that there is no fuel available,''
said Jennifer Donohue of the airport's public affairs department.
   Fuel service was restored about two hours later to most of the
airport, said Donohue, although delays were expected to continue
into the evening. At least four airlines faced flight delays late
into the evening because of cleanup operations and continued
difficulty in fuel delivery.
   About 50,000 gallons of fuel spilled and were contained a short
time later when the pipeline was shut off to stop it from spreading
into San Francisco Bay, said Donohue.
   Airport officials estimated there are 60 to 70 flights each hour
in and out of the airport on Fridays.
</TEXT>
