<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-88 2318EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NewCaledonia     11-18 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New Caledonia,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>51 Melanesians Freed In Paris and Noumea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty-one native Melanesians were released from
prisons in Paris and New Caledonia over a period ending Friday as
part of a plan approved by voters Nov. 6 outlining the future of the
French Pacific island territory.
   The statute calls for New Caledonia, 11,000 miles from Paris, to
hold a local referendum on independence in 1998.
   The Socialist government of President Francois Mitterrand hopes
the plan will bring peace to the islands, where nearly 40 people
have died in intercommunal violence since 1984.
   The law provided amnesty for any person charged with actions of a
political nature, except murder, before Aug. 20.
   In Paris, 26 militant separatists were released from jails
Thursday night. They had been held in connection with an attack on a
police outpost at Fayoue, New Caledonia, on April 22 in which four
gendarmes were killed and 21 taken hostage.
   They immediately left for New Caledonia aboard a special plane
provided by the government after being escorted to Orly Airport by
French police.
   French troops freed the hostages in an assault May 5 in which 19
people, mostly Melanesian separatists, died.
   In Noumea, New Caledonia's capital, 25 other Melanesians who were
held following violence last April and May were released late
Thursday night and early Friday morning.
   Authorities in New Caledonia are reviewing the files on a dozen
other Melanesians still held to see if they also will be freed under
the new law.
   The archipelego of New Caledonia has been torn by periodic
violence between native Melanesians, known as Kanaks, and white
European settlers.
   Kanaks, most of whom favor independence from France, make up 43
percent of New Caledonia's 145,000 inhabitants. The settlers, most
of whom want to remain French, comprise 37 percent. The rest of the
population is predominantly Polynesians and Asians, who mostly favor
France.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
