<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Iraq     11-18 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Iraq,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraqi Envoy to Britain Denies His Aides Spied</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq's ambassador to Britain, Mohammed Sadiq
al-Mashat, denied Friday that three expelled members of his staff
spied on Iraqi dissidents and compiled an assassination list.
   ``This is absolutely false,'' Mashat said in a British
Broadcasting Corp. radio interview. ``Our staff are law-abiding
citizens.''
   British newspapers and the BBC reported earlier Friday that the
expelled Iraqis monitored Iraqi dissidents. The Independent
newspaper said the dissidents included members of a clandestine
Iraqi Shiite Moslem terrorist organization, al-Dawa.
   The Foreign Office announced Thursday night that two diplomats
and the ambassador's driver were told on Oct. 18 that they had two
weeks to leave Britain. It said Iraq expelled three British
diplomats in retaliation.
   The Foreign Office accused the three and a fourth Iraqi diplomat
who was not allowed back into Britain of ``activities incompatible
with their status'' _the diplomatic phrase for spying.
   Mashat denied that his driver was expelled. He said the
non-diplomat ordered out was a receptionist who dealt with Arabs at
the embassy _ ``Just a simple employee who doesn't know English, who
doesn't know how to drive.''
   An unidentfied Iraqi dissident, also interviewed by the BBC,
charged Friday that Iraqi President Saddam Hussein was taking
advantage of the cease-fire in the Iran-Iraq war ``to liquidate
opponents.''
   He said exiles' families in Iraq received threatening phone calls
and were intimidated or pressured in other ways.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
