<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DigestBriefs     11-18 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Digest Briefs,0574</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<NOTE>Eds: This package does not contain the following items from the
News Digest: B1-B Crash; Soviet Palestine; India-Gorbachev; Bush
Rdp; Reagan-Drugs; Israel; Mideast Moves; Baltics; Buried Bodies;
Canada-US; China-Iron Rice Bowl; Homesteader Haven</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration is telling
aspirin makers to warn women not to take the popular pain killer
during the last three months of pregnancy lest they risk prolonged
labor and unnecessary bleeding.
   Aspirin products already must carry the standard warning: ``As
with any drug, if you are pregnant or nursing a baby seek the advice
of a health professional before using this product.''
   This additional wording would be required under the FDA proposal
issued Thursday: ``IMPORTANT: Do not take this product during the
last three months of pregnancy unless directed by a doctor. Aspirin
taken near the time of delivery may cause bleeding problems in both
mother and child.''
   A similar warning already is required for ibuprofen, the pain
reliever used in such products as Advil and Nuprin.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A study that found Seventh-day Adventists can
expect to live longer suggests that others who adopt the healthful
lifestyle of the religious group may also extend their life spans.
   Practicing Seventh-day Adventists abstain from smoking and
drinking alcoholic beverages, and many adopt a vegetarian or
near-vegetarian diet. This approach had a significant association
with life expectancy, said Jan W. Kuzma, a professor of vital
statistics at Loma Linda University in California.
   His study calculated life tables for a group of 27,514
Seventh-day Adventists _ 9,804 males and 17,710 females older than
age 30 who enrolled in a study in 1960. Kuzma followed up on that
study through 1985 by checking California death records and compared
the life expectancies to the general California population.
   Kuzma found that a 35-year-old male Seventh-day Adventist was
likely to live to be 82, nine more years than the average California
white male. For females, the advantage was 7.6 years longer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nationwide search for four young adults
ended with the recovery of bodies from a car in a river. But
questions remain whether the accident was a deadly combination of
underage drinking and a missing safety barrier.
   A car containing what authorities believed were the bodies of the
four young people was found Thursday in 15 feet of water on the
bottom of Mill River.
   The three women and one man, who were age 20 or younger, were
last seen by their parents Saturday night, when they left their
hometown of East Lyme for a night in New Haven.
   Police have determined the four spent at least part of Saturday
night drinking at a bar near Yale University. The legal drinking age
in Connecticut is 21. State police Detective Andre Trudelle said a
bar employee told authorities the four left the bar together about 3
a.m. Sunday.
   Their car apparently traveled down Chapel Street, went over a
concrete barrier that was in place Thursday and plunged into the
river, city police Lt. James Sorrentino said. The street has been a
dead end for years because the Chapel Street bridge is out of
service.
   Officials said the bridge pivots open on a center axis to allow
water traffic to pass and has been in its open position for years.
</TEXT>
