<1ST_LINE>a a AM-TabloidTV-Geraldo ADV21   11-18 0848</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tabloid TV-Geraldo, ADV 21,0867</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, Nov. 21, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Geraldo _ `A Rebel Forever'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tabloid TV, b0380</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In his penthouse office just off Times Square,
Geraldo Rivera shows off a catcher's mask given by a friend after
the televised brawl that broke his nose and sent his talk show
ratings soaring.
   Within hours, wasting no time in taking advantage of the
publicity surrounding his rearranged honker, he's taping a new
episode of ``Geraldo'' called ``Has TV Gone Too Far?'' He reruns
footage of the brawl and confronts a panel of TV critics, backed by
an audience that occasionally boos the critics.
   Rivera is a creature of irony.
   In 1986, when he opened Al Capone's secret vault on live
television, the vault was embarrassingly empty _ but the show was
the highest-rated syndicated special ever.
   Earlier this month, his NBC special on devil worship was thrashed
by critics for tastelessness. When the ratings came in, it was the
fourth highest-rated network show of the week.
   He's the butt of jokes and the object of satire. When he canceled
an appearance on NBC's ``Saturday Night Live'' because of his broken
nose, Dana Carvey as the ``Church Lady'' noted in the sketch,
``Geraldo Rivera couldn't be with us, so we have the next best thing
_ a monkey.''
   Rivera sighs. It seems he just can't have success and esteem, too.
   ``I always harbored a semi-secret desire to someday achieve peer
acceptance,'' he says. ``Certainly, during my years at ABC, I tried
to be as quiet as possible. I didn't do very much press at all. I
did as many kinds of Pentagon-type stories, waste-fraud-abuse
stories, I called them, `WFAs,' as I could possibly do. I devoted
all my attention to that non-flashy kind of stuff, and I still
didn't get that kind of acceptance.
   ``By the time I left ABC in December '85, I knew I'd be a rebel
forever _ the oddball. Now I don't think about it very much.''
   Rivera came on the scene in the 1970s, jumping into stories with
both feet, weeping over abused mental patients, getting chased by
security guards trying to expose the plight of migrant laborers.
   When he left ABC News, he said it was because the division's
president, Roone Arledge, had killed his ``20-20'' story about
Robert Kennedy and Marilyn Monroe.
   Since then, Rivera has had a series of controversial but
successful syndicated specials, and his year-old talk show defied
the odds by muscling into the crowded field headed by ``The Oprah
Winfrey Show'' and ``Donahue.''
   His flamboyance has earned him a place in the so-called ``tabloid
TV'' genre that includes ``The Morton Downey Jr. Show,'' and Fox's
lurid quasi-newsmagazines ``A Current Affair'' and ``The Reporters.''
   ``I haven't changed, just the labels change,'' says Rivera.
```Newspunks' was the last three months. Now it's `trash TV.' ... I
remember the days when I was the `advocacy reporter,' the
`confrontation reporter' and the `ambush reporter' _ I remember that
one was around for about a year. My main point is that I'm still
doing exactly the same thing I've always been doing.''
   When Rivera expanded from syndication into network television,
the critics pounced harder than ever.
   ``I'm convinced that very often what I do, if you put a different
reporter in and they said the same words, and you had exactly the
same images, and the program was exactly the same, the reviews would
be far more benign. I think that so many times, I get reviewed and
not what I do,'' Riversa says.
   ``I just think I've found what suits me. I feel a real sense of
populism. I'm not ashamed of it. I feel the audience often thinks of
me as their surrogate or as a friend.''
   So why, if he has such a following, doesn't he tackle weightier
subjects than skinheads and transexuals?
   ``We did a two-parter on the homeless six weeks ago,'' he said.
``We do a lot of stories on subjects that are not the flash or sex
topics. I don't do the ozone depletion. I don't do the little whales
trapped off Point Barrow. There's a lot of people who could do those
stories. There's a lot of people who could do the budget deficit
better than I could.
   ``I think that as we become more successful and as the program
evolves, you're going to see a richer mix. We already moved the
talk-show genre into a harder news area. We do a lot more in terms
of crime and punishment or drug abuse or those kinds of street
problems than talk shows have ever done, certainly than day-time
talk shows have ever done.''
   Critics aside, Rivera would seem to have no reason to change. He
says his talk show will gross about $25 million this year and has
gone from 70 stations when it premiered a year ago to 178 currently.
   ``Laughing all the way to the bank,'' he says. ``Isn't that the
truth?''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Nov. 21</NOTE>
