<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   11-18 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0578</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major central banks are riding to the dollar's
rescue in a united buying spree that has helped stabilized the
weakening currency, although analysts warned the recovery might be
short-lived because of acute concerns about the U.S. trade and
budget deficits.
   The coordinated worldwide buying of dollars Thursday by central
banks appeared to be the heaviest since the spring, and it lent some
support to the slumping stock market.
   Some economists also predicted the Federal Reserve would boost
U.S. interest rates to further defend the beleaguered dollar.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing construction in October posted its
biggest increase in eight months, the government has said in a
report taken as evidence that the Federal Reserve hasn't yet tried
to curb economic growth.
   The Commerce Department said Thursday that construction began on
new homes and apartments at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of
1.55 million units last month, up 7.2 percent from September.
   It was the highest level since April and the sharpest increase
since February.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Metropolitan Life Insurance Co. has sued RJR
Nabisco Inc., charging that the record $20 billion-plus
debt-financed takeover planned by Nabisco's management has
devastated the insurer's holdings in Nabisco bonds.
   The lawsuit announced Thursday by Met Life, one of the biggest
U.S. insurance companies, came one day after ITT Corp. sued RJR
Nabisco for related reasons.
   The suits reflect what appears to be a growing bondholder revolt
against the use of borrowed money in financing multibillion-dollar
corporate acquisitions.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holly Farms Corp. has moved to sidestep a
hostile takeover by rival poultry producer Tyson Foods Inc. by
agreeing to be acquired by ConAgra Inc. in a stock swap valued at
about $1 billion.
   The acquisition is subject to approval by shareholders of Holly
Farms and ConAgra, the companies said Thursday.
   Financial analysts said the ConAgra agreement does not push Tyson
out of the picture. It has been trying to acquire Holly Farms for a
month, and its most recent offer was valued at $941 million.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, seeking to give new impetus
to international trade negotiations, says he is dropping a demand
that other countries join the United States in phasing out
agricultural subsidies by the year 2000.
   An eventual elimination of government interventions into farm
markets remains the U.S. goal, Reagan said in a speech Thursday to
the U.S. Chamber of Commerce.
   But he acknowledged that talks under the auspices of the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade have bogged down, at least in part,
because of the U.S. demand for a fixed deadline for ending
agricultural subsidies.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Consumer Product Safety Commission is
ignoring the problem of dangerous crib toys, which injured or killed
at least 49 babies between 1973 and 1987, according to a consumer
group and the New York attorney general.
   The Consumer Federation of America and New York Attorney General
Robert Abrams filed a petition Thursday asking the commission ``to
determine ... that certain crib toys intended for use by children
present a mechanical hazard and therefore are banned hazardous
substances.''
   They defined crib toys as crib gyms, mobiles, activity boxes,
suspended stuffed toys, music boxes and other toys marketed for use
in cribs and playpens.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
