<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0558</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission has taken
a major step toward making advanced telephone services such as voice
mail and computer gateways available on a wide scale to average
consumers.
   But also on Thursday, the commission reopened a thorny issue that
earlier met vigorous opposition from the providers of these
electronic information services, who resisted an FCC proposal to add
hefty charges to their bills.
   Separately, the commission authorized construction of 13 domestic
communications satellites and launch of nine. It also authorized
construction and launch of 10 replacement satellites.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MasterCard International has announced the
appointment of Los Angeles banker Alex W. ``Pete'' Hart as president
and chief executive officer of the giant credit-card company.
   MasterCard said Thursday that Hart was elected by the board of
the bankcard association.
   Hart, a former executive vice president at First Interstate
Bancorp and a MasterCard board member, replaces eight-year veteran
Russell E. Hogg, whose resignation takes effect Friday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FDIC wants to sell 57.5 million shares of its
stock in Continental Illinois Corp., a move that would put a
majority of stock in the hands of the public for the first time
since 1984, the company says.
   Continental Illinois, the parent of Continental Illinois National
Bank & Trust, said Thursday it was asked by the FDIC to notify the
Securities and Exchange Commission about the public offering.
   Last month, Continental Illinois filed an SEC statement saying it
would buy 4.7 million shares held by the Federal Deposit Insurance
Corp. for an employee stock ownership plan.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers could live with a spending freeze
designed to erase red budget ink without new taxes if they were not
singled out for sacrifice, the leader of the nation's largest farm
group says.
   ``I'm not talking about eliminating federal programs or cutting
current outlays,'' Dean Kleckner, president of the American Farm
Bureau Federation, said Thursday.
   Kleckner, an Iowa farmer, is a member of the National Economic
Commission, which is seeking ways to reduce the deficit. He has been
mentioned as a possible Bush selection for secretary of agriculture.
 
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ray Cave is resigning as editorial director of
Time Inc. after 30 years with the magazine publishing company,
according to Time editor-in-chief Jason McManus.
   Cave has been editorial director, second highest editorial
position in the company, since April 1987. The resignation announced
Thursday is effective at year's end.
   Louis J. Slovinsky, a Time Inc. spokesman, said Cave, 59,
apparently was not satisfied with what sort of a role he could
expect over the next six year. Cave had told McManus he wanted to
work vigorously until at least age 65.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Blue-chip stocks staged a modest rally Thursday, but the rest of
the market remained in a slump. The Dow Jones average of 30
industrials rose 13.87 points to 2,052.45.
   The dollar's slide was stemmed by coordinated central bank
intervention. Gold prices dipped.
   Bond prices fell.
   Soybean futures prices plunged to their lowest levels in more
than six months. Grain, cotton, precious metals, oil, livestock and
meat futures all fell while copper futures rose.
</TEXT>
