<HEAD>Interest Rates on 52-Week Bills Highest in 3{ Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on 52-week Treasury bills rose
in the government's latest auction to the highest level for such a
sale in 3{ years.
   The Treasury Department sold $9.05 billion of the bills at an
average discount rate of 7.92 percent on Thursday, up from 7.57
percent at the last auction on Oct. 20.
   The rates were the highest since May 14, 1985, when the one-year
bills sold for 7.94 percent. The new discount rate understates the
actual return to investors _ 8.55 percent with a $10,000 bill
selling for $9,199.20.
</TEXT>
