<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-88 0943EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Inflation     11-18 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Inflation,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Annual Inflation Rises To 6.4 Percent From 5.9 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's annual inflation rate jumped to 6.4
percent in October from 5.9 percent in September, pushed up by
higher mortgage rates, the government said Friday.
   However, the gain was in line with forecasts by Chancellor of the
Exchequer Nigel Lawson and by analysts. The financial markets,
relieved by the news, had little reaction.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher has said fighting inflation,
which stood at 3.3 percent in January, is her No. 1 economic
priority.
   To curb prices, the government drove interest rates significantly
higher last summer, with the commercial banks' base lending rate
going from a 10-year low of 7.5 percent in June to the current 12
percent, and mortgage rates going up as well.
   The Department of Employment said its retail price index rose 1
percent in October from September after a 0.5 percent gain in
September from the previous month.
   The index, which uses a 1987 base of 100, stood at 109.5 in
October, compared with 108.4 in September, and 102.9 in October 1987.
   The department said the latest rise was mainly the result of
higher mortgage interest payments, following a round of
mortgage-rate hikes on Oct. 1 when the average rate of 11.5 percent
rose to 12.75 percent.
   Employment Secretary Norman Fowler said the index, excluding
mortgage interest payments, rose 5.1 percent in the year to October,
compared with an annual rate of 5.2 percent in September.
   ``Interest rates have had to be increased to constrain price
rises, but it will take time,'' Fowler said. ``The government will
continue to keep up the fight against inflation.''
   There were also price increases in clothing and footwear, motor
vehicles, motor vehicle insurance and beer, the government said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
