<DOCNO> AP881118-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-88 0953EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-WSJPublisher     11-18 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WSJ Publisher,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kann Named Publisher Of WSJ</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peter R. Kann, who won a Pulitzer Prize for
international reporting and was the founding editor and publisher of
the Asian Wall Street Journal, has been named publisher of The Wall
Street Journal, effective Jan. 1.
   Kann, 45, succeeds Warren H. Phillips, who remains chairman and
chief executive officer of Dow Jones & Co., the Journal's parent
company. Phillips, 62, who announced Kahn's appointment Thursday,
has held those positions since 1975.
   Kann joined the Journal in 1964 as a reporter after graduating
from Harvard. He became Vietnam correspondent in 1967 and covered
Southeast Asia from a Hong Kong base from 1968 to 1975. He won the
Pulitzer Prize in 1972.
   He helped launch the Asian Wall Street Journal before returning
to the United States in 1979 as assistant to the chairman of Dow
Jones.
   Kann also was named the Journal's associate publisher that year.
He was elected an executive vice president of Dow Jones in 1985 and
a director in 1987, the same year he was elected to the Pulitzer
Prize board.
</TEXT>
