<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-88 1018EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-BritishGas     11-18 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-British Gas,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Gas Posts 69 Percent Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Gas PLC said Friday its earnings sank 69
percent in the first half of its fiscal year because of weaker oil
prices.
   British Gas said it earnings for the six months ended Oct. 2
totaled 22 million pounds, the equivalent of $39.8 million, compared
with 71 million pounds, in the same period a year ago.
   The company's earnings translate to 0.5 pence per share, compared
with 1.7 pence in the same period of 1987.
   The decline, although large, was not as bad as some analysts had
expected. British Gas stock fell 2 pence a share to 161.5 pence on
London's Stock Exchange.
   British Gas Chairman Sir Denis Rooke said the company typically
makes a small profit or suffers a loss during the first half of its
financial year, with the great majority of its income generated in
the second part of the year, which falls during winter.
   Revenue rose 5.6 percent to 2.64 billion pounds from 2.5 billion
pounds.
   The chairman said the first six months were ``strongly
influenced'' by external factors, such as declining oil prices and a
consequent loss in gas sales. Nonetheless, Rooke said, there was
underlying growth in the volume of gas sales to both the domestic
and commercial markets.
   British Gas did not break out quarterly results. It is not
required to under British law.
</TEXT>
