<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures opened mostly higher today on the
Chicago Board of Trade in a modest recovery from Thursday's steep
decline. Grain futures opened mostly lower.
   The soybean market gained strength from improved European
soybean-oil and soybean-meal markets and from the Agriculture
Department's report of a moderate increase in export sales of U.S.
soybeans for the wek ending Nov. 10, analysts said.
   Soybeans came under extreme pressure Thursday and closed at their
lowest levels since mid-May. Traders have been disappointed in the
slow pace of export sales, and analysts said soybean prices had to
move lower to encourage more foreign buying.
   Corn and wheat futures opened mostly lower today in thin trading.
   ``It's a pretty featureless affair'' in the grain pits, said Dale
Gustafson, an analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in Chicago.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to 1{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.09 a bushel; corn was 1{
cents lower to \ cent higher with December at $2.58 a bushel; oats
were { cent lower to \ cent higher with December at $2.03{ a bushel;
and soybeans were { cent lower to 7 cents higher with November at
$7.22 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .25 cent lower to .13 cent higher with December
at 72.80 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .15 cent
lower with January at 82.65 cents a pound; hogs were .03 cent to .40
cent lower with December at 40.50 cents a pound; and frozen pork
bellies were .07 cent to .15 cent lower with February at 43.50 cents
a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly lower on Thursday.
</TEXT>
