<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-88 1319EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-UnitedStates     11-18 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-United States,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Reacts Coolly To Reagan Offer On Farm Subsidies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community reacted
coolly Friday to President Reagan's offer to soften the U.S.
position on agriculture subsidies at next month's world trade talks
in Montreal.
   A spokeswoman for the EEC Commission said the offer ``was not a
fundamental change'' in the U.S. desire to eliminate all farm
subsidies.
   Reagan said Thursday the United States would be flexible about a
deadline for abolishing farm subsidies. Until now, it had demanded
such subsidies be stopped by the year 2000.
   The Commission spokeswoman said the EEC seeks a reduction in farm
subsidies over the long term, not their complete elimination.
   Reagan's speech was seen here as an attempt to ensure progress at
the Montreal talks due to begin Dec. 5.
   The meeting will assess progress made to date in the four-year
Uruguay round of trade liberalization talks within the 96-nation
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
   That progress is to be discussed in weekend talks here between
the U.S. trade representative Clayton Yeutter, U.S. Agriculture
Secretary Richard Lyng and top EEC officials.
   On Friday, Yeutter and Lyng discussed other contentious trade
issues with their EEC counterparts, including EEC plans to ban
imports of hormone-treated meat from the United States as of Jan. 1
and U.S. objections to possible EEC subsidies for the Airbus
consortium.
   On Saturday the talks will focus on the Uruguay trade round of
the GATT talks. Yeutter is in Brussels after having meetings in
recent days in West Germany, France and the Netherlands.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881118-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-88 1616EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-InvestmentFraud     11-18 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Investment Fraud,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dean Witter Settles Case Charging Lost Millions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 30 investors who charged they lost
millions of dollars because of unauthorized high-risk investments by
Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. have settled with the brokerage firm,
officials said Friday.
   The out-of-court settlement late last week came shortly after the
resignation by the manager of Dean Witter's Boston office, who along
with a broker and the firm was the target of a lawsuit by a group of
39 investors.
   Complaints against two other firms, Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
and Merrill Lynch & Co., are pending, said Samuel Shafner, an
attorney for the plaintiffs.
   The investors had filed lawsuits in U.S. District Court here in
July against Anoop K. Barman, a broker allegedly responsible for the
bulk of the transactions, and against Dean Witter and Merrill Lynch,
where he worked from 1985 to 1987.
   Barman also worked for Shearson, and that firm is in settlemenmt
negotiations although it has not been sued, Shafner said.
   Terms of the settlement with Dean Witter were not disclosed. An
attorney for Dean Witter confirmed only that a settlement had been
reached.
   Shafner said two of the Dean Witter customers refused to settle
and that their cases likely would be decided by a securities
industry arbitration panel and not in court. Several other customers
still are negotiating with the brokerage giant.
   ``We're very, very pleased with all the settlement amounts with
those who settled and the aggregate,'' Shafner said.
   Despite the settlement, the state Securities Division is still
investigating whether Dean Witter violated the Massachusetts
Securities Act, said Paul Glickman, the division's chief of
enforcement.
   ``This will not change our investigation,'' he said. ``We expect
to continue.''
   Glickman confirmed that the probe focuses on whether the firm
entered into trades above the investors' financial capabilities and
mishandled millions of dollars and whether supervision was adequate.
The investigation began after several investors complained to the
state.
   The securities act contains regulations governing investments by
brokers in stock options that are beyond a customer's means. The
probe involves Dean Witter's Boston and Burlington offices and at
least five executives, including Boston manager Stephen J. Lozen,
who resigned last week.
   Lozen has refused comment on whether his departure was tied to
the charges.
   Dean Witter spokeswoman Beth Metzler said Lozen resigned for
personal reasons not related to the charges. ``It was a voluntary
decision on Steve's part to resign from Dean Witter,'' she said.
   Not all of the 39 investors are involved in the cases against
Shearson and Merrill Lynch. Shafner said settlement negotiations are
underway with Shearson while Merrill Lynch has been served with a
lawsuit in federal court.
   In the suit, Barman is accused of violating state and federal
securities laws, fraud, deception and mishandling accounts to try to
generate larger profits and commissions in risky index options
trading.
   Options are agreements that allow investors to buy or sell shares
of stock within a stipulated time for a certain price. Barman
allegedly traded in index options, which are based on a package of
shares that make up one of the major market indexes, after clients
specifically barred him from doing so.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881118-0211 </DOCNO>
