<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Coke-Mini-Machine     11-18 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Coke-Mini-Machine,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coke Rolls Out Microwave-Size Drink Machines For Small Office
Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coca-Cola Co., taking aim at a million offices
too small for a conventional Coke machine, has introduced an
alternative about the size of a microwave oven.
   Dubbed the ``BreakMate,'' the machine dispenses three different
soft drinks into cups in a programmed portion size. An on-board
carbon dioxide tank turns tap water into carbonated water, then the
machine mixes carbonated water with drink syrup, chilled by a small
refrigeration unit.
   The whole machine measures 22 by 11 by 18 inches and weighs 78
pounds. And if the boss is too cheap to spring for the Cokes, a
coin-operated version is available.
   Coke estimates that 1 million U.S. offices of 50 workers or less
don't have soft drinks on the premises, and the company hopes to
eventually sell an extra 20 million gallons of syrup each year _ or
about 2.4 billion drinks _ in the markets it cannot now reach.
   ``The objective is to put BreakMate wherever Coca-Cola is not
readily available to consumers,'' Coca-Cola USA President Ira
Herbert said in a statement this week.
   The company estimates that 20,000 units will be in place by the
end of the year, with more than 40,000 more installed in the United
States next year. Distributors are currently on line in 25 U.S.
markets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
