<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Canandaigua-Layoffs     11-18 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canandaigua-Layoffs,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canandaigua Wine to Lay Off 20 Percent of Work Force</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANANDAIGUA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canandaigua Wine Co. will lay off 20
percent of its workforce and close a bottling operation in Virginia
in an effort to end two years of falling sales and profits, company
officials said Friday.
   The company currently employs about 650 workers at three wineries
in New York, three in California, one in Patrick, S.C., and the
Petersburg, Va., facility, which will be closed by January, said
company spokesman Staford Krause.
   About 40 workers will lose their jobs when the bottling
operation, called Richards Wine Cellars, closes, Krause said. The
remaining 90 employees scheduled to be laid off have been notified
of the cutbacks.
   ``In effect the cutback has started and is pretty much
completed,'' Krause said. ``This is not going to be a staggering,
drawn-out thing.''
   He said the cuts involved all levels of the company including its
force of sales representatives around the country.
   Canandaigua Wine, the fourth largest winery in the country, has
suffered millions of dollars of losses because of slumping sales of
Sun Country Wine Cooler, the product that catapulted the company
into prosperity not too long ago.
   Sun Country's demise has been swift.
   In November 1985, fueled by skyrocketing sales of Sun Country,
Canandaigua reported record earnings of $9.5 million for the fiscal
year ended Aug. 31, 1985 and the company's stock soared to over $50
a share.
   Two years later, troubled by huge advertising expenditures and
falling Sun Country sales, the company reported a loss of $9.7
million for fiscal year 1987. The company reported a loss of $4.8
million for fiscal 1988.
   On the American Stock Exchange, Canandaigua Wine stock fell 12{
cents a share to $8.25 on Friday.
   ``We deeply regret the necessity of reducing our work force,''
said Chairman Marvin Sands. ``We are hopeful, however, that such
actions will help us keep costs in line ... and maintain the company
as a strong and vigorous competitor nationwide.''
</TEXT>
