<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     11-18 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Strengthens, Gold Weakens</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Central bankers rescued the dollar again Friday,
buying large amounts of the currency and at least temporarily
bolstering or stabilizing its value in the foreign exchange markets.
   Gold prices weakened. Republic National Bank quoted bullion at
$416.75 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, down from $419.75 at the same
time Thursday.
   The central-bank dollar buying marked the second straight day of
massive coordinated currency intervention by the United States and
its key trading partners. Traders said the dollar's weakness
reflected growing concern about the long-term implications of the
large U.S. trade and budget deficits.
   ``The dollar should be going down and the markets want it down,''
said Scott Greene, a currency trader in New York with Switzerland's
Bank Julius Baer & Co.
   ``It used to be America was the haven for security. When there
was a flight of capital it always would go into dollars. That
confidence is gone,'' Greene said. ``If the central banks weren't in
there, who knows how low the dollar would be now.''
   Others said the aggressive level of central-bank dollar buying
was only intended to stabilize the currency or ease its rapid fall
since the Nov. 8 election of George Bush to succeed President Reagan.
   Until and unless the Bush administration can create genuine
interest in the dollar as an attractive currency, money traders
said, it was highly likely the central banks would have to maintain
a strong presence in the market to keep the dollar from dropping
precipitously.
   In Tokyo the dollar rose 0.88 yen to close at 122.40 yen. Later
in London the dollar strengthened further to 122.65 yen. By 4 p.m.
New York time the dollar fetched 122.60 yen, up from 122.16 yen at
the same time Thursday.
   The dollar gained on the British pound in London, where it cost
$1.8160 to buy a pound vs. $1.8227 late Thursday. The dollar also
strengthened against the pound in New York, where sterling fetched
$1.8155 vs. $1.8287 late Thursday.
   Other late-dollar rates in New York vs. rates late Thursday
included: 1.7370 West German marks, up from 1.7230; 1.4600 Swiss
francs, up from 1.4470; 1.2300 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2307;
5.9365 French francs, up from 5.8915; and 1,292.00 Italian lire, up
from 1,283.75.
   Other late-dollar rates in Europe vs. late rates Thursday
included: 1.7360 marks, up from 1.7298; 1.4585 Swiss francs, up from
1.4518; 5.9340 French francs, up from 5.9075; 1.9610 Dutch guilders,
up from 1.9560; 1,293.75 Italian lire, up from 1,291.75; and 1.2343
Canadian dollars, up from 1.2335.
   Gold's retreat evidently stemmed from internal market pressures
rather than any outside news, dealers said.
   On the New York Commodity Exchange, gold for current delivery
fell $2.70 a troy ounce to $417.40. In London gold fell $4.25 an
ounce to $417.75; in Zurich it fell $3.20 an ounce to $417.80 and in
Hong Kong it fell $3.11 to $421.23.
   Silver dropped 10.7 cents a troy ounce to $6.08 on the New York
Comex. In London silver dropped 20 cents to $6.09.
</TEXT>
