<1ST_LINE>r f AM-OberweisSecurities     11-18 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oberweis Securities,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company's Lack of Funds Halts Securities Orders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAPERVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of Oberweis Securities Inc., a
Midwest discount brokerage firm, said Friday they hoped to have
enough capital to resume customer orders by next week.
   The brokerage firm, headquartered in this Chicago suburb, said
Thursday it had temporarily stopped accepting orders for securities,
although it continued to sell stock, carry out options and conduct
non-purchasing business for existing accounts.
   ``We can confirm for you the firm has ceased doing business,''
said Craig Dearborn, director of the National Association of
Securities Dealers Inc.'s Chicago office.
   Clark Galloway, manager of the company's Rockford branch, said
Oberweis needed an additional $600,000 and expected the money by
Monday at the latest.
   ``It's a one-day, two-day problem at the most,'' he said.
``Oberweis is solvent.''
   Under NASD rules, brokerages must keep reserves up to a certain
level to continue doing business. Galloway said he did not know the
dollar amount of the reserve requirement.
   Galloway said the capital problem was caused partly by the stock
market crash last year and partly because of a recent acquisition.
   Some securities acquired in the purchase of a Minnesota brokerage
have declined in the last week, pushing capital reserves to below
acceptable levels, he said.
   Barry Weber, a spokesman for the majority stockholder in
Oberweis, told the Chicago Tribune that company capital fell below
NASD requirements in part because misconduct by a former broker in a
Minneapolis office caused the firm hundreds of thousands of dollars
in losses.
   Weber is vice chairman to Ronald Alghini, a wealthy Chicago
investor who heads Phoenix Capital Corp., and who purchased a
majority stake in Oberweis in August, the newspaper said.
   At the time, Alghini said Oberweis would undergo immediate
restructuring and predicted the company, which had suffered lean
balance sheets in recent years, would be highly profitable by
December of this year.
   Weber declined to identify the individual he said was involved in
the losing trades, but said the broker was fired Nov. 4 after it was
learned that he and possibly others had established large and
unauthorized positions in four over-the-counter stocks, the Tribune
reported.
   The unauthorized trading came to light after the market turned
against the four positions, forcing the firm to use its capital to
cover the losses, the newspaper said.
   The trading reportedly involved selling stock short, an
arrangement in which the investor sells borrowed stock, hoping its
price would fall, the Tribune said.
   Officials of the company said Thursday that customers' accounts
were safe.
   ``There should be no repercussions,'' said Joe Warnelis, an
Oberweis investment executive. ``We are not shut down, but we have
voluntarily restricted the level by which we do business. We have
taken steps to bring in additional capital.''
   All accounts at Oberweis are insured up to $500,000 by the
Security Investors Protection Corp., which is similar to the Federal
Deposit Insurance Corp. for banks, said Michael Don, deputy general
counsel for the protection corporation in Washington.
   The protection corporation, which charges securities dealers $100
each to fund the insurance pool, will reimburse investors up to
$100,000 for cash accounts at a brokerage that goes bankrupt. A
total of $500,000 can be reimbursed for cash and securities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881118-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-88 1809EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     11-18 0853</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0884</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Silver Futures Slide To 20-Month Low</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Silver futures prices slid to a 20-month low on New York's
Commodity Exchange Friday, the fourth straight day of steep losses,
and analysts said the metal appeared to be headed below $6 a troy
ounce.
   ``It certainly looks like it's going to try,'' said Stephen W.
Platt, metal-markets analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in
Chicago.
   On other markets, other precious metals also retreated while
copper futures gained; livestock and meat were lower; grains and
soybeans were mixed; energy futures were mixed; and stock-index
futures advanced.
   Silver for delivery in December tumbled nearly 36 cents a troy
ounce in the four sessions ended Friday. Prices settled 11 cents to
14.1 cents lower on Friday alone with the December contract at $6.08
a troy ounce, the lowest Comex silver price since March 27, 1987.
   Metals experts cited a variety of factors for silver's sudden
decline but all agreed that supplies of the metal were more than
adequate and that the recent sharp rise in short-term interest rates
has had a depressing effect on demand from both the industrial and
the investment sectors.
   The dollar's weakness since the Nov. 8 presidential election
would ordinarily help prop up the precious metals because of its
inflationary implications.
   But ``the dollar going down hasn't been enough to offset the
negative influence of the interest rates going up,'' said Craig
Sloane, metals analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co. in New
York.
   Sloane said the silver market actually had been weakening
relative to gold for the last two months, even though both metals
had been trending higher since the start of October.
   But the general decline in the precious metals during the past
week ``kind of took away the camouflage,'' he said.
   ``Gold and silver have a little reversal in place and I wouldn't
be surprised to see it follow through,'' Sloane said. ``I can see
gold possibly testing the lows (below $400 an ounce) that it made in
September and silver maybe breaking $6 and heading to $5.75.''
   Bette Raptopoulos, metals analyst with Prudential Bache
Securities Inc. in New York, said much of Friday's silver decline
was due to dealer selling of the physical metal on speculation that
a month-old miners' strike in Peru was nearing its end and
availabilty of silver soon would increase.
   Gold settled $2.70 to $3.80 lower with December at $418.10 a troy
ounce.
   Copper futures advanced on the Commodities Exchange on continuing
concerns about supply disruptions in Chile and Peru, analysts said.
   Copper settled .50 cent to 2.60 cents higher with December at
$1.359 a pound.
   Hog futures prices dropped sharply on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange as the futures market adjusted to unexpected weakness in
the pork-products market, said Thomas Morgan, president of Sterling
Research Corp. in Arlington Heights, Ill.
   Cattle futures retreated ahead of the Agriculture Department's
monthly tally of cattle being fattened for slaughter on feedlots in
the seven largest cattle-producing states.
   The report showed a 5 percent decline since last year in the
number of cattle on feed as of Nov. 1, the number placed on feedlots
in October and the number marketed off of feedlots last month.
   All the numbers were slightly above market expectations were
neutral to slightly bearish for futures prices, Morgan said.
   Live cattle settled .32 cent to .55 cent lower with December at
72.35 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .50 cent to .80 cent lower
with January at 81.97 cents a pound; live hogs were 1.17 cent lower
to .08 cent higher with December at 40.15 cents a pound; and frozen
pork bellies were .50 cent to .65 cent lower with February at 43.07
cents a pound.
   Corn and soybean futures ended modestly lower while most wheat
futures advanced slightly in subdued trading on the Chicago Board of
Trade.
   Wheat gained on light support from commercial players. After the
close, the Agriculture Department announced sales of 110,000 metric
tons of U.S. wheat to Iraq at subsidized prices.
   The November soybean contract expired at noon CST at $7.27} a
bushel, 8\ cents above Thursday's final price.
   Wheat settled \ cent lower to 1} cents higher with December at
$4.11 a bushel; corn was { cent to 2 cents lower with December at
$2.58\ a bushel; oats were { cent to 3{ cents lower with December at
$2.00{ a bushel; soybeans were 2 cents to 6\ cents lower with
January at $7.31 a bushel.
   Oil futures prices ended mixed in choppy trading on the New York
Mercantile Exchange as OPEC members continued to meet informally in
Vienna to discuss the longstanding problem of overproduction.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 4 cents to 31 cents
higher with December at $13.60 a barrel; heating oil was .21 cent to
.26 cent lower with December at 42.76 a gallon; unleaded gasoline
was unchanged to .36 cent lower with December at 45.65 cents a
gallon.
   Stock-index futures advanced moderately on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for December delivery of the Standard &
Poor's 500 settled 1.15 points higher at 265.80.
</TEXT>
