<1ST_LINE>r f AM-PepperellSuit     11-18 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pepperell Suit,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pepperell Files Additional Suit To Stall Farley Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Point-Pepperell Inc. filed suit against
Farley Inc. Friday, charging that Farley's chairman made
contradictory statements about whether he planned to break up the
textile giant if Farley's takeover bid is successful.
   Pepperell seeks a temporary restraining order and preliminary
injunction against Farley's offer for the company. The offer is
currently scheduled to expire Monday.
   Farley, a Chicago-based manufacturer of precision metal products
and clothing, announced a tender offer for stock in Pepperell, a
West Point, Ga.-based textile company, on May 23. Farley currently
owns 2.87 million shares, or 9.8 percent, of Pepperell stock.
   The suit alleges that while Chairman William Farley has stated
publicly he has no plans to break up Pepperell, filings with the
Securities and Exchange Commission indicate that Farley plans to
keep Pepperell's household fabrics business and sell the apparel,
apparel fabrics and industrial fabrics divisions to create funds to
repay acquisition costs.
   In the suit, Pepperell asks that Farley be ordered to clarify its
intentions toward Pepperell.
   Pepperell also had filed an emergency appeal Wednesday with the
11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in an attempt to halt Farley's
takeover attempt. No ruling had been made on that appeal by Friday.
</TEXT>
