<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-88 2135EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-EasternShuttle     11-18 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern Shuttle,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Unions At Eastern Seek To Block Sale of Shuttle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three unions at Eastern Airlines on Friday
formally asked for a preliminary injunction to block the $365
million sale of its Northeast shuttle service to real estate magnate
Donald Trump.
   The motion filed in U.S. District Court in Washington by the
International Association of Machinists, the Air Line Pilots
Association and Local 553 of the Transport Workers Union had been
anticipated for a month.
   U.S. District Judge Barrington Parker in October had scheduled a
hearing on it for Dec. 2, giving Eastern until Nov. 25 to file a
response.
   The three unions contended in the motion that the sale of the
Boston-New York-Washington shuttle violates the Railway Labor Act as
part of an attempt by Eastern's parent, Texas Air Corp., to break
the unions in the midst of collective bargaining on new contracts.
   ``The sale is yet another attempt by (Texas Air Chairman) Frank
Lorenzo to dismantle Eastern Airlines,'' said Jack Bavis, head of
the pilots union at the carrier. ``They've done nothing but squeeze
out assets over the last two years. The shuttle is one of the
strongest links in Eastern's structure.''
   Although the shuttle has been consistently profitable, Texas Air
contends the sale is necessary to raise cash for preserving the rest
of Eastern, which has lost more than $300 million since 1986.
   The shuttle deal is scheduled for completion on Dec. 15.
</TEXT>
