<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-88 2233EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-OilPrices     11-18 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Mixed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices turned mixed as OPEC ministers
prepared to hold formal meetings to discuss curbing overproduction.
   But market watchers said they weren't optimistic that the
gathering to be held Monday in Vienna would help eliminate the
worldwide oil glut and boost sagging prices.
   ``There's a growing sentiment that OPEC is having a difficult
time getting their act together,'' said Peter Beutel, an energy
analyst with Elders Futures Inc.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the December contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, rose
31 cents to settle Friday at $13.60 a barrel, after losing 38 cents
on Thursday. Other contract months also gained ground.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange Friday,
the December contract for unleaded gasoline settled at 45.65 cents a
gallon, unchanged from Thursday. The contract fell 0.85 cent on
Thursday.
   The December contract for wholesale home heating oil, which fell
1.50 cents in the previous session, lost 0.21 cent to settle at
42.76 cents a gallon.
   Informal OPEC talks in Vienna hit a snag on Friday, with some
ministers working to break an impasse between Iran and Iraq.
   At issue is Iraq's insistence on being allowed to produce the
same amount of oil as rival Iran. Iran has steadfastly refused such
parity.
   The Oranization of Petroleum Exporting Countries sets quotas or
ceilings on the amount of oil its 13 members can produce. The
ministers are trying to arrange a new accord _ the current one dates
to 1986 _ that would limit the recent surge in production that has
added to the already glutted market. All 13 ministers plan to meet
formally beginning Monday.
</TEXT>
