<DOCNO> AP881118-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-88 2241EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-RJRNabisco     11-18 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-RJR Nabisco,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deadline for Bidders Passes in Biggest-Ever Takeover</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   RJR Nabisco Inc. aides were spending the weekend
scrutinizing at least two debt-financed takeover bids for the food
and tobacco behemoth, up for sale in what amounts to history's
biggest corporate auction.
   Contenders for the 19th largest U.S. company had until 5 p.m. EST
Friday to submit proposals to a special committee of RJR Nabisco
directors on how much they were willing to pay and how they intended
to raise the purchase money.
   RJR spokeswoman Polly Howe said the committee intended to remain
silent about the bidding process indefinitely. ``They are not
discussing or disclosing or confirming. There is no comment
regarding the proposals,'' she said.
   Sources familiar with process confirmed that the two main bidders
for the company submitted proposals by the deadline but details
about them weren't disclosed. It also remained unclear whether any
other bids were delivered.
   Wall Street speculators, who had battered the RJR stock down to
$82.75 a share earlier in the week after being spooked by rumors of
withdrawn bids, ran it back up to $84 in heavy trading Friday.
   ``People had gotten a little anxious,'' said Marc I. Cohen, a
securities analyst who follows RJR Nabisco for the investment firm
Sanford C. Bernstein & Co. in New York. ``It was overdone.''
   Though details of any winning offer were not expected to be
disclosed until Sunday afternoon at the earliest, most analysts
reckoned it would put at least a $91-a-share value on the company's
225.3 million shares, or about $20.5 billion.
   Before the Friday deadline, two known contenders were vying for
the company in a takeover battle that has dwarfed all previous
records in size and complexity.
   One is a group consisting of RJR Nabisco's top managers and the
investment firms Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. and Salomon Brothers
Inc. The managers incited the battle by disclosing last month they
were considering buying up all outstanding RJR Nabisco shares with
borrowed money, the takeover tactic commonly known as a leveraged
buyout.
   The other bidding group is headed by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &
Co., undisputed leader in leveraged buyouts. The Kohlberg faction
also includes the powerful investment firms of Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc., Morgan Stanley & Co., Wasserstein Perella & Co. and
Merrill Lynch & Co.
   In the early stages of the fight both groups offered more than
$20 billion for RJR Nabisco, the Atlanta-based maker of hundreds of
items that range from Jose Cuervo tequila to Salem cigarettes and
Life Savers candy to Milk Bone doggie snacks.
   Lawyers and investment advisers for RJR Nabisco's special
directors committee were expected to hole up in their New York
offices analyzing the bids at least through Sunday morning. The
five-member committee was then expected to consider which bid to
accept.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
