<DOCNO> AP881118-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-88 2244EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-Dollar-Markets     11-18 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Markets,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Central Banks Bolster Dollar for Second Day</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The slumping dollar has again been bolstered by
central banks buying the U.S. currency in foreign-exchange markets.
   For a second straight day, Friday's coordinated intervention
drove the dollar higher. That sparked a small gain on the stock
market, but deep-rooted bearish sentiment continued to envelop the
U.S. currency.
   ``The market hasn't really been frightened by the intervention,''
said David Redding, an international money-market economist at
Bankers Trust Co. ``The fundamental psychology (toward the dollar)
is still fairly negative.''
   The dollar purchases in the open market by the Federal Reserve,
the Bank of Japan and several major European central banks extended
a worldwide buying spree that appeared to be the heaviest since the
spring.
   On Wall Street, which had been unnerved by the dollar's slide,
the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks rose 9.96 points to
2,062.41, trimming its loss for the week to 4.62 points.
   Bond prices also gained, pushing interest rates lower. The yield
on the Treasury's closely watched 30-year bond fell to 9.11 percent
from 9.17 percent late Thursday.
   Investors in the financial markets worry that a weak dollar could
drive up interest rates and spark higher inflation, since it would
raise prices of imports and some domestic commodities.
   Currency traders reported that the central bank intervention
began with the Bank of Japan buying dollars in the Tokyo market,
where the U.S. currency had dropped on Thursday to a near 40-year
low of 121.50 Japanese yen.
   The Bank of Japan was later joined in European foreign-exchange
markets by the central banks of West Germany, Britain, Switzerland,
France, Italy, Austria and other nations, traders said. All the
participating central banks were reported to be buying dollars to
soak up the supply of the U.S. currency while selling yen and West
German marks.
   Dealers said the dollar was jolted early in the New York trading
day by remarks by Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady, who told
NBC's ``Today Show'' he's not concerned with the currency market
gyrations. The comment sent the dollar down about a pfennig against
the mark, bringing the Fed back into the market with more sales of
the mark to buy dollars.
   Then Federal Reserve Board Vice Chairman Manuel Johnson jawboned
the dollar higher by calling its recent steep decline a ``purely
speculative'' phenomenon that has been brought under control by the
concerted intervention.
   The dollar rose in Tokyo and strengthened further in London and
New York. The dollar was quoted at 122.60 yen in late New York
trading, up from 122.15 yen late Thursday.
   Against the mark, the dollar advanced to 1.7370 from 1.7230 marks
late Thursday. The British pound slipped against the dollar,
fetching $1.8155 compared with $1.8287 the day before.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881118-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-88 2211EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Pillsbury     11-18 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Pillsbury,0626</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burger King Franchisees Oppose Spin-off</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burger King Corp. franchisees voiced strong
opposition Friday to a plan by the Pillsbury Co. to spin off the
fast-food chain as part of a defensive restructuring aimed at
thwarting a hostile $5.23 billion takeover bid from Britain's Grand
Metropolitan PLC.
   The National Business Planning Council, the official franchisee
group, said in a letter to Burger King Chairman Jerry Levin that the
spin-off would add too much debt to the slumping company, which is
based in Miami.
   ``We strongly oppose this proposed course of conduct,'' B.N.
Pothitous wrote on behalf of the council.
   Pothitous said the franchisee group ``cannot and will not''
support any restructuring that will restrict further investment and
competitive growth in the chain.
   Levin, who was at Pillsbury headquarters in Minneapolis Friday
afternoon, said the letter confirms conversations he had with the
franchisees throughout the week.
   ``They informed us they were quite concerned with the level of
debt in the models we showed them,'' Levin said. ``We will explain
those concerns and issues to our board of directors.''
   Levin would not say when the directors will meet again. He said
he presented only one restructuring model to the franchisees.
   He said franchisees ``made a lot of good points and we learned a
lot'' during the week of meetings.
   The franchisees also met this week with officials from Grand Met.
The British liquor, gambling and specialty products conglomerate has
said it would invest money in Burger King and streamline its
operations if the takeover bid is successful.
   The fast-food chain accounted for $1.91 billion of Pillsbury's
$6.19 billion sales in fiscal 1988. Operating profits for the year
were $48.2 million at Burger King while net earnings for Pillsbury
were $69 million, or 81 cents a share.
   Grand Met's $60 a share tender offer has been extended three
times. The offer was set to expire again at midnight Friday, but
could be extended Monday.
   Pillsbury's board of directors rejected the all-cash tender offer
as inadequate on Oct. 17 and later announced the plan to spin off
Burger King into a separate public company. Pillsbury shareholders
would receive stock in the new Burger King, which would issue a
special shareholder dividend _ the size of which has not been
disclosed.
   Grand Met and dissident shareholders are suing Pillsbury to
invalidate the company's ``poison pill'' takeover defense and to
block the spin off of Burger King. The pill would make a takeover
prohibitively expensive and a newly separate Burger King would
present a huge tax liability for Grand Met if a takeover is
successful, according to the lawsuits.
   Pillsbury Chairman Philip Smith has refused offers to meet with
Grand Met officials to negotiate the tender offer. Smith has said
Pillsbury shareholders would be better off in the long run under the
restructuring being proposed by the board of directors.
   Pillsbury stock closed Friday at $57.25 a share in composite New
York Stock Exchange trading.
   Meanwhile, Pillsbury on Friday named C. Ronald Petty as president
and chief operating officer of Burger King.
   Levin said franchisees have ``an enormous amount of respect for
Ron's talents and a high degree of confidence that he will provide
strong leadership in the new position.''
   Petty, 44, has 15 years of experience in the fast food industry,
including stints with Burger King USA, Burger King International and
the real estate division of McDonald's Restaurants.
   Grand Met spokesman Walter Montgomery said the British company is
``pleased but not surprised'' by the franchisees' opposition to the
Burger King plan. He said Grand Met remains confident the tender
offer will prevail.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
